qTextArr:
['The Signora had no business to do it,', 'no business
at all. She promised us south rooms with a view close together, instead
of which here are north rooms, looking into a courtyard, and a long way
apart. Oh, Lucy!']
qText:
The Signora had no business to do it, no business
at all. She promised us south rooms with a view close together, instead
of which here are north rooms, looking into a courtyard, and a long way
apart. Oh, Lucy!
speaker: Miss Bartlett

qTextArr: ['And a Cockney, besides!', 'It might be London.']
qText: And a Cockney, besides! It might be London.
speaker: Lucy

qTextArr: ["Charlotte, don't you feel,\ntoo, that we might be in London? I can hardly believe that all kinds of\nother things are just outside. I suppose it is one's being so tired."]
qText:
Charlotte, don't you feel,
too, that we might be in London? I can hardly believe that all kinds of
other things are just outside. I suppose it is one's being so tired.
speaker: Lucy

qTextArr: ['This meat has surely been used for soup,']
qText: This meat has surely been used for soup,
speaker: Miss Bartlett

qTextArr: ['I want so to see the Arno. The rooms the Signora promised us in her\nletter would have looked over the Arno. The Signora had no business to\ndo it at all. Oh, it is a shame!']
qText:
I want so to see the Arno. The rooms the Signora promised us in her
letter would have looked over the Arno. The Signora had no business to
do it at all. Oh, it is a shame!
speaker: Lucy

qTextArr: ['Any nook does for me,', "but it does seem hard\nthat you shouldn't have a view."]
qText:
Any nook does for me, but it does seem hard
that you shouldn't have a view.
speaker: Miss Bartlett

qTextArr: ["Charlotte, you mustn't spoil me:\nof course, you must look over the Arno, too. I meant that. The first\nvacant room in the front--"]
qText:
Charlotte, you mustn't spoil me:
of course, you must look over the Arno, too. I meant that. The first
vacant room in the front--
speaker: Lucy

qTextArr: ['You must have it,']
qText: You must have it,
speaker: Miss Bartlett

qTextArr: ['No, no. You must have it.']
qText: No, no. You must have it.
speaker: Lucy

qTextArr: ['I insist on it. Your mother would never forgive me, Lucy.']
qText: I insist on it. Your mother would never forgive me, Lucy.
speaker: Miss Bartlett

qTextArr: ['She would never forgive me.']
qText: She would never forgive me.
speaker: Lucy

qText: I have a view, I have a view.

qText: A view? Oh, a view! How delightful a view is!

qText:
This is my son, his name's George. He has a view

speaker: Mr. Emerson

qText: Ah,
speaker: Miss Bartlett

qText:
What I mean, is that you can have our rooms, and we'll

qText:
Thank you very much indeed; that is out of the

qText: Because it is quite out of the question, thank you.
speaker: Miss Bartlett

qText: You see, we don't like to take--
speaker: Lucy

qText: But why? Women like looking at a view; men don't.

qText: George, persuade them!

qText:
It's so obvious they should have the rooms, There's
nothing else to say.

qTextArr: ['Eat your dinner, dear,']
qText: Eat your dinner, dear,
speaker: Miss Bartlett

qTextArr: ['Eat your dinner, dear. This pension is a failure. To-morrow we will\nmake a change.']
qText:
Eat your dinner, dear. This pension is a failure. To-morrow we will
make a change.
speaker: Miss Bartlett

qTextArr: ["Oh, oh! Why, it's\nMr. Beebe! Oh, how perfectly lovely! Oh, Charlotte, we must stop now,\nhowever bad the rooms are. Oh!"]
qText:
Oh, oh! Why, it's
Mr. Beebe! Oh, how perfectly lovely! Oh, Charlotte, we must stop now,
however bad the rooms are. Oh!
speaker: Lucy
refExp: Lucy who had not yet acquired decency at once rose to her feet exclaiming

qTextArr: ["How do you do, Mr. Beebe? I expect that you have forgotten us: Miss\nBartlett and Miss Honeychurch, who were at Tunbridge Wells when you\nhelped the Vicar of St. Peter's that very cold Easter."]
qText:
How do you do, Mr. Beebe? I expect that you have forgotten us: Miss
Bartlett and Miss Honeychurch, who were at Tunbridge Wells when you
helped the Vicar of St. Peter's that very cold Easter.
speaker: Miss Bartlett

qTextArr: ['I AM so glad to see you,', 'Just fancy how small the world is. Summer\nStreet, too, makes it so specially funny.']
qText:
I AM so glad to see you, Just fancy how small the world is. Summer
Street, too, makes it so specially funny.
speaker: Lucy

qTextArr: ['Miss Honeychurch lives in the parish of Summer Street,', 'and she happened to tell me in the course\nof conversation that you have just accepted the living--']
qText:
Miss Honeychurch lives in the parish of Summer Street, and she happened to tell me in the course
of conversation that you have just accepted the living--
speaker: Miss Bartlett

qTextArr: ["Yes, I heard from mother so last week. She didn't know that I knew you\nat Tunbridge Wells; but I wrote back at once, and I said: 'Mr. Beebe\nis--'"]
qText:
Yes, I heard from mother so last week. She didn't know that I knew you
at Tunbridge Wells; but I wrote back at once, and I said: 'Mr. Beebe
is--'
speaker: Lucy

qTextArr: ['Quite right,', 'I move into the Rectory at Summer\nStreet next June. I am lucky to be appointed to such a charming\nneighbourhood.']
qText:
Quite right, I move into the Rectory at Summer
Street next June. I am lucky to be appointed to such a charming
neighbourhood.
speaker: Mr. Beebe

qTextArr: ['Oh, how glad I am! The name of our house is Windy Corner.']
qText: Oh, how glad I am! The name of our house is Windy Corner.
speaker: Lucy

qTextArr: ["There is mother and me generally, and my brother, though it's not often\nwe get him to ch---- The church is rather far off, I mean."]
qText:
There is mother and me generally, and my brother, though it's not often
we get him to ch---- The church is rather far off, I mean.
speaker: Lucy

qTextArr: ['Lucy, dearest, let Mr. Beebe eat his dinner.']
qText: Lucy, dearest, let Mr. Beebe eat his dinner.
speaker: Miss Bartlett

qTextArr: ['I am eating it, thank you, and enjoying it.']
qText: I am eating it, thank you, and enjoying it.
speaker: Mr. Beebe

qTextArr: ["Don't neglect the country round,", 'The first fine afternoon drive up to Fiesole, and round by\nSettignano, or something of that sort.']
qText:
Don't neglect the country round, The first fine afternoon drive up to Fiesole, and round by
Settignano, or something of that sort.
speaker: Mr. Beebe

qTextArr: ['No!', 'Mr. Beebe, you are\nwrong. The first fine afternoon your ladies must go to Prato.']
qText:
No! Mr. Beebe, you are
wrong. The first fine afternoon your ladies must go to Prato.
speaker: Miss Lavish

qTextArr: ['That lady looks so clever,', 'We\nare in luck.']
qText:
That lady looks so clever, We
are in luck.
speaker: Miss Bartlett
refExp: whispered Miss Bartlett to her cousin

qTextArr: ['Prato! They must go to Prato. That place is\ntoo sweetly squalid for words. I love it; I revel in shaking off the\ntrammels of respectability, as you know.']
qText:
Prato! They must go to Prato. That place is
too sweetly squalid for words. I love it; I revel in shaking off the
trammels of respectability, as you know.
speaker: Miss Lavish

qTextArr: ['We are most grateful to you,', "The first evening means so much. When you arrived we were in for a\npeculiarly mauvais quart d'heure."]
qText:
We are most grateful to you, The first evening means so much. When you arrived we were in for a
peculiarly mauvais quart d'heure.
speaker: Miss Bartlett

qTextArr: ['Do you, by any chance, know the name of an old man who sat opposite us\nat dinner?']
qText:
Do you, by any chance, know the name of an old man who sat opposite us
at dinner?
speaker: Miss Bartlett
menTexts: [['you', 'an old man who sat opposite us\nat dinner']]

qTextArr: ['Emerson.']
qText: Emerson.
speaker: Mr. Beebe

qTextArr: ['Is he a friend of yours?']
qText: Is he a friend of yours?
speaker: Miss Bartlett

qTextArr: ['We are friendly--as one is in pensions.']
qText: We are friendly--as one is in pensions.
speaker: Mr. Beebe

qTextArr: ['Then I will say no more.']
qText: Then I will say no more.
speaker: Miss Bartlett

qTextArr:
['I am, as it were,', 'the chaperon of my young cousin,
Lucy, and it would be a serious thing if I put her under an obligation
to people of whom we know nothing. His manner was somewhat unfortunate.
I hope I acted for the best.']
qText:
I am, as it were, the chaperon of my young cousin,
Lucy, and it would be a serious thing if I put her under an obligation
to people of whom we know nothing. His manner was somewhat unfortunate.
I hope I acted for the best.
speaker: Miss Bartlett

qTextArr: ['You acted very naturally,']
qText: You acted very naturally,
speaker: Mr. Beebe

qTextArr: ["All the same, I don't think much harm would have\ncome of accepting."]
qText:
All the same, I don't think much harm would have
come of accepting.
speaker: Mr. Beebe
refExp: He seemed thoughtful and after a few moments added

qTextArr: ['No harm, of course. But we could not be under an obligation.']
qText: No harm, of course. But we could not be under an obligation.
speaker: Miss Bartlett

qTextArr:
['He is rather a peculiar man.', 'I think he would not take advantage of your acceptance, nor expect you
to show gratitude. He has the merit--if it is one--of saying exactly
what he means. He has rooms he does not value, and he thinks you would
value them. He no more thought of putting you under an obligation than
he thought of being polite. It is so difficult--at least, I find it
difficult--to understand people who speak the truth.']
qText:
He is rather a peculiar man. I think he would not take advantage of your acceptance, nor expect you
to show gratitude. He has the merit--if it is one--of saying exactly
what he means. He has rooms he does not value, and he thinks you would
value them. He no more thought of putting you under an obligation than
he thought of being polite. It is so difficult--at least, I find it
difficult--to understand people who speak the truth.
speaker: Mr. Beebe
menEnts: [[['Mr. Emerson']], [['Mr. Emerson'], ['Miss Bartlett', 'Lucy'], ['Miss Bartlett', 'Lucy'], ['Mr. Emerson'], ['Mr. Emerson'], ['Mr. Emerson'], ['Mr. Emerson'], ['Mr. Emerson'], ['Miss Bartlett', 'Lucy'], ['Mr. Emerson'], ['Miss Bartlett', 'Lucy']]]

qTextArr: ['I was hoping that he was nice; I do so\nalways hope that people will be nice.']
qText:
I was hoping that he was nice; I do so
always hope that people will be nice.
speaker: Lucy

qTextArr:
["I think he is; nice and tiresome. I differ from him on almost every
point of any importance, and so, I expect--I may say I hope--you will
differ. But his is a type one disagrees with rather than deplores. When
he first came here he not unnaturally put people's backs up. He has no
tact and no manners--I don't mean by that that he has bad manners--and
he will not keep his opinions to himself. We nearly complained about
him to our depressing Signora, but I am glad to say we thought better of
it."]
qText:
I think he is; nice and tiresome. I differ from him on almost every
point of any importance, and so, I expect--I may say I hope--you will
differ. But his is a type one disagrees with rather than deplores. When
he first came here he not unnaturally put people's backs up. He has no
tact and no manners--I don't mean by that that he has bad manners--and
he will not keep his opinions to himself. We nearly complained about
him to our depressing Signora, but I am glad to say we thought better of
it.
speaker: Mr. Beebe

qTextArr: ['Am I to conclude,', 'that he is a Socialist?']
qText: Am I to conclude, that he is a Socialist?

qTextArr: ['And presumably he has brought up his son to be a Socialist, too?']
qText: And presumably he has brought up his son to be a Socialist, too?

qTextArr: ["I hardly know George, for he hasn't learnt to talk yet. He seems a nice\ncreature, and I think he has brains. Of course, he has all his father's\nmannerisms, and it is quite possible that he, too, may be a Socialist."]
qText:
I hardly know George, for he hasn't learnt to talk yet. He seems a nice
creature, and I think he has brains. Of course, he has all his father's
mannerisms, and it is quite possible that he, too, may be a Socialist.
speaker: Mr. Beebe
menEnts: [[['George Emerson'], ['George Emerson'], ['George Emerson'], ['George Emerson'], ['George Emerson'], ['George Emerson']]]

qTextArr: ['Oh, you relieve me,', 'So you think I ought to\nhave accepted their offer? You feel I have been narrow-minded and\nsuspicious?']
qText:
Oh, you relieve me, So you think I ought to
have accepted their offer? You feel I have been narrow-minded and
suspicious?
speaker: Miss Bartlett

qTextArr: ['Not at all,', 'I never suggested that.']
qText: Not at all, I never suggested that.
speaker: Mr. Beebe

qTextArr: ['But ought I not to apologize, at all events, for my apparent rudeness?']
qText: But ought I not to apologize, at all events, for my apparent rudeness?
speaker: Miss Bartlett

qTextArr:
['Was I a bore?', "Why
didn't you talk, Lucy? He prefers young people, I'm sure. I do hope I
haven't monopolized him. I hoped you would have him all the evening, as
well as all dinner-time."]
qText:
Was I a bore? Why
didn't you talk, Lucy? He prefers young people, I'm sure. I do hope I
haven't monopolized him. I hoped you would have him all the evening, as
well as all dinner-time.
speaker: Miss Bartlett

qTextArr: ['He is nice,', 'Just what I remember. He seems to see\ngood in everyone. No one would take him for a clergyman.']
qText:
He is nice, Just what I remember. He seems to see
good in everyone. No one would take him for a clergyman.
speaker: Lucy

qTextArr: ['My dear Lucia--']
qText: My dear Lucia--
speaker: Miss Bartlett

qTextArr: ['Well, you know what I mean. And you know how clergymen generally laugh;\nMr. Beebe laughs just like an ordinary man.']
qText:
Well, you know what I mean. And you know how clergymen generally laugh;
Mr. Beebe laughs just like an ordinary man.
speaker: Lucy

qTextArr: ['Funny girl! How you do remind me of your mother. I wonder if she will\napprove of Mr. Beebe.']
qText:
Funny girl! How you do remind me of your mother. I wonder if she will

speaker: Miss Bartlett

qTextArr: ["I'm sure she will; and so will Freddy."]
qText: I'm sure she will; and so will Freddy.
speaker: Lucy

qText:
I think everyone at Windy Corner will approve; it is the fashionable
world. I am used to Tunbridge Wells, where we are all hopelessly behind
the times.
speaker: Miss Bartlett

qText: Yes,
speaker: Lucy

qTextArr: ['I am\nafraid you are finding me a very depressing companion.']
qText:
I am
afraid you are finding me a very depressing companion.
speaker: Miss Bartlett
refExp: Miss Bartlett sedulously denied disapproving of any one and added

qText:
I must have been selfish or unkind; I must
be more careful. It is so dreadful for Charlotte, being poor.
speaker: Lucy

qTextArr: ['But here you are as safe as in England. Signora Bertolini is so\nEnglish.']
qText:
But here you are as safe as in England. Signora Bertolini is so

qTextArr: ['Yet our rooms smell,', 'We dread going to bed.']
qText: Yet our rooms smell, We dread going to bed.
speaker: Lucy

qTextArr: ['Ah, then you look into the court.']
qText: Ah, then you look into the court.

qText:
If only Mr. Emerson was
more tactful! We were so sorry for you at dinner.

qTextArr: ['I think he was meaning to be kind.']
qText: I think he was meaning to be kind.
speaker: Lucy

qTextArr: ['Undoubtedly he was,']
qText: Undoubtedly he was,
speaker: Miss Bartlett

qTextArr: ["Mr. Beebe has just been scolding me for my suspicious nature. Of\ncourse, I was holding back on my cousin's account."]
qText:
Mr. Beebe has just been scolding me for my suspicious nature. Of
course, I was holding back on my cousin's account.
speaker: Lucy

qTextArr: ['About old Mr. Emerson--I hardly know. No, he is not tactful; yet, have\nyou ever noticed that there are people who do things which are most\nindelicate, and yet at the same time--beautiful?']
qText:
About old Mr. Emerson--I hardly know. No, he is not tactful; yet, have
you ever noticed that there are people who do things which are most
indelicate, and yet at the same time--beautiful?
speaker: Lucy

qTextArr: ['Beautiful?', 'Are not beauty\nand delicacy the same?']
qText:
Beautiful? Are not beauty
and delicacy the same?
speaker: Miss Bartlett

qTextArr: ['So one would have thought,', 'But things are\nso difficult, I sometimes think.']
qText:
So one would have thought, But things are
so difficult, I sometimes think.
speaker: Lucy

qTextArr:
['Miss Bartlett,', "it's all right about the rooms. I'm so glad.
Mr. Emerson was talking about it in the smoking-room, and knowing what
I did, I encouraged him to make the offer again. He has let me come and
ask you. He would be so pleased."]
qText:
Miss Bartlett, it's all right about the rooms. I'm so glad.
Mr. Emerson was talking about it in the smoking-room, and knowing what
I did, I encouraged him to make the offer again. He has let me come and
ask you. He would be so pleased.
speaker: Mr. Beebe

qTextArr: ['Oh, Charlotte,', 'we must have the rooms now.\nThe old man is just as nice and kind as he can be.']
qText:
Oh, Charlotte, we must have the rooms now.
The old man is just as nice and kind as he can be.
speaker: Lucy

qTextArr: ['I fear,', 'that I have been officious. I\nmust apologize for my interference.']
qText:
I fear, that I have been officious. I
must apologize for my interference.
speaker: Mr. Beebe

qTextArr:
['My own wishes, dearest Lucy, are unimportant in comparison with
yours. It would be hard indeed if I stopped you doing as you liked at
Florence, when I am only here through your kindness. If you wish me to
turn these gentlemen out of their rooms, I will do it. Would you then,
Mr. Beebe, kindly tell Mr. Emerson that I accept his kind offer, and
then conduct him to me, in order that I may thank him personally?']
qText:
My own wishes, dearest Lucy, are unimportant in comparison with
yours. It would be hard indeed if I stopped you doing as you liked at
Florence, when I am only here through your kindness. If you wish me to
turn these gentlemen out of their rooms, I will do it. Would you then,
Mr. Beebe, kindly tell Mr. Emerson that I accept his kind offer, and
then conduct him to me, in order that I may thank him personally?
speaker: Miss Bartlett

Remember, Lucy, I alone am implicated in this. I do not wish the

qText: But I would like to help you.

qText: No, dear.

qText:
I want to explain, why it is that I have taken
the largest room. Naturally, of course, I should have given it to you;
but I happen to know that it belongs to the young man, and I was sure
your mother would not like it.
speaker: Miss Bartlett

qTextArr:
['If you are to accept a favour it is more suitable you should be under
an obligation to his father than to him. I am a woman of the world, in
my small way, and I know where things lead to. However, Mr. Beebe is a
guarantee of a sort that they will not presume on this.']
qText:
If you are to accept a favour it is more suitable you should be under
an obligation to his father than to him. I am a woman of the world, in
my small way, and I know where things lead to. However, Mr. Beebe is a
guarantee of a sort that they will not presume on this.
speaker: Miss Bartlett

qTextArr: ["Mother wouldn't mind I'm sure,"]
qText: Mother wouldn't mind I'm sure,
speaker: Lucy

qTextArr: ['What does it mean?']
qText: What does it mean?
speaker: Miss Bartlett

qTextArr:
['If it is Mrs. Grundy who is troubling you, I do assure you that you
can neglect the good person. Being English, Miss Honeychurch will be
perfectly safe. Italians understand. A dear friend of mine, Contessa
Baroncelli, has two daughters, and when she cannot send a maid to school
with them, she lets them go in sailor-hats instead. Every one takes
them for English, you see, especially if their hair is strained tightly
behind.']
qText:
If it is Mrs. Grundy who is troubling you, I do assure you that you
can neglect the good person. Being English, Miss Honeychurch will be
perfectly safe. Italians understand. A dear friend of mine, Contessa
Baroncelli, has two daughters, and when she cannot send a maid to school
with them, she lets them go in sailor-hats instead. Every one takes
them for English, you see, especially if their hair is strained tightly
behind.
speaker: Miss Lavish

qTextArr: ['I will take you by a dear dirty back way, Miss Honeychurch, and if you\nbring me luck, we shall have an adventure.']
qText:
I will take you by a dear dirty back way, Miss Honeychurch, and if you
bring me luck, we shall have an adventure.
speaker: Miss Lavish

qTextArr:
['Tut, tut! Miss Lucy! I hope we shall soon emancipate you from Baedeker.
He does but touch the surface of things. As to the true Italy--he does
not even dream of it. The true Italy is only to be found by patient
observation.']
qText:
Tut, tut! Miss Lucy! I hope we shall soon emancipate you from Baedeker.
He does but touch the surface of things. As to the true Italy--he does
not even dream of it. The true Italy is only to be found by patient
observation.
speaker: Miss Lavish

qTextArr: ['A smell! a true Florentine smell! Every city, let me teach you, has its\nown smell.']
qText:
A smell! a true Florentine smell! Every city, let me teach you, has its
own smell.
speaker: Miss Lavish

qTextArr: ['Is it a very nice smell?']
qText: Is it a very nice smell?
speaker: Lucy

qTextArr: ["One doesn't come to Italy for niceness,"]
qText: One doesn't come to Italy for niceness,
speaker: Miss Lavish

qTextArr: ['one comes for\nlife. Buon giorno! Buon giorno!']
qText:
one comes for
life. Buon giorno! Buon giorno!
speaker: Miss Lavish

qTextArr: ['Look at that\nadorable wine-cart! How the driver stares at us, dear, simple soul!']
qText:
Look at that
adorable wine-cart! How the driver stares at us, dear, simple soul!

qTextArr:
["Buon giorno! Take the word of an old woman, Miss Lucy: you will
never repent of a little civility to your inferiors. That is the
true democracy. Though I am a real Radical as well. There, now you're
shocked."]
qText:
Buon giorno! Take the word of an old woman, Miss Lucy: you will
never repent of a little civility to your inferiors. That is the
true democracy. Though I am a real Radical as well. There, now you're
shocked.
speaker: Miss Lavish

qTextArr: ["Indeed, I'm not!", 'We are Radicals, too, out and out.\nMy father always voted for Mr. Gladstone, until he was so dreadful about\nIreland.']
qText:
Indeed, I'm not! We are Radicals, too, out and out.
My father always voted for Mr. Gladstone, until he was so dreadful about
Ireland.
speaker: Lucy

qTextArr: ['I see, I see. And now you have gone over to the enemy.']
qText: I see, I see. And now you have gone over to the enemy.
speaker: Miss Lavish

qTextArr:
['Oh, please--! If my father was alive, I am sure he would vote Radical
again now that Ireland is all right. And as it is, the glass over our
front door was broken last election, and Freddy is sure it was the
Tories; but mother says nonsense, a tramp.']
qText:
Oh, please--! If my father was alive, I am sure he would vote Radical
again now that Ireland is all right. And as it is, the glass over our
front door was broken last election, and Freddy is sure it was the
Tories; but mother says nonsense, a tramp.
speaker: Lucy

qTextArr: ['Shameful! A manufacturing district, I suppose?']
qText: Shameful! A manufacturing district, I suppose?
speaker: Miss Lavish

qTextArr: ['No--in the Surrey hills. About five miles from Dorking, looking over\nthe Weald.']
qText:
No--in the Surrey hills. About five miles from Dorking, looking over

speaker: Lucy

qTextArr: ['What a delightful part; I know it so well. It is full of the very\nnicest people. Do you know Sir Harry Otway--a Radical if ever there\nwas?']
qText:
What a delightful part; I know it so well. It is full of the very

speaker: Miss Lavish

qTextArr: ['Very well indeed.']
qText: Very well indeed.
speaker: Lucy

qTextArr: ['And old Mrs. Butterworth the philanthropist?']
qText: And old Mrs. Butterworth the philanthropist?

Oh, you

qText:

qTextArr: ["Bless us! Bless us and save us! We've lost the way."]
qText: Bless us! Bless us and save us! We've lost the way.
speaker: Miss Lavish

qTextArr:
['Lost! lost! My dear Miss Lucy, during our political diatribes we have
taken a wrong turning. How those horrid Conservatives would jeer at us!
What are we to do? Two lone females in an unknown town. Now, this is
what I call an adventure.']
qText:
Lost! lost! My dear Miss Lucy, during our political diatribes we have
taken a wrong turning. How those horrid Conservatives would jeer at us!
What are we to do? Two lone females in an unknown town. Now, this is
what I call an adventure.
speaker: Miss Lavish

qTextArr: ["Oh, but that is the word of a craven! And no, you are not, not, NOT to\nlook at your Baedeker. Give it to me; I shan't let you carry it. We will\nsimply drift."]
qText:
Oh, but that is the word of a craven! And no, you are not, not, NOT to
look at your Baedeker. Give it to me; I shan't let you carry it. We will
simply drift.
speaker: Miss Lavish

qTextArr: ['Stop a minute; let those two people go on, or I shall have to speak to\nthem. I do detest conventional intercourse. Nasty! they are going into\nthe church, too. Oh, the Britisher abroad!']
qText:
Stop a minute; let those two people go on, or I shall have to speak to
them. I do detest conventional intercourse. Nasty! they are going into
the church, too. Oh, the Britisher abroad!
speaker: Miss Lavish

qTextArr: ['We sat opposite them at dinner last night. They have given us their\nrooms. They were so very kind.']
qText:
We sat opposite them at dinner last night. They have given us their
rooms. They were so very kind.
speaker: Lucy

['Look at their figures!', "They walk through my

to set an examination paper at Dover, and turn back every tourist who

Look at their figures! They walk through my

speaker: Miss Lavish

qText: What would you ask us?

qText:
Hateful bishop! Hard in life, hard in death. Go out into the sunshine,

qTextArr:
['You are a clever woman,', 'You have done more than
all the relics in the world. I am not of your creed, but I do believe in

qText:
You are a clever woman, You have done more than

qText: Niente,

qText: I'm not sure she understands English,

qText:
That woman understands everything, But what

qTextArr:
['No,', 'I came here with Miss
Lavish, who was to explain everything; and just by the door--it is too
bad!--she simply ran away, and after waiting quite a time, I had to come
in by myself.']
qText:
No, I came here with Miss
Lavish, who was to explain everything; and just by the door--it is too
bad!--she simply ran away, and after waiting quite a time, I had to come

speaker: Lucy

qTextArr: ["Why shouldn't you?"]
qText: Why shouldn't you?

qTextArr: ["Yes, why shouldn't you come by yourself?"]
qText: Yes, why shouldn't you come by yourself?

qTextArr: ['But Miss Lavish has even taken away Baedeker.']
qText: But Miss Lavish has even taken away Baedeker.
speaker: Lucy

qTextArr: ['Baedeker?', "I'm glad it's THAT you minded. It's worth\nminding, the loss of a Baedeker. THAT'S worth minding."]
qText:
Baedeker? I'm glad it's THAT you minded. It's worth
minding, the loss of a Baedeker. THAT'S worth minding.
speaker: Mr. Emerson

qTextArr: ["If you've no Baedeker,", "you'd better join us."]
qText: If you've no Baedeker, you'd better join us.
speaker: George Emerson

qTextArr:
['Thank you very much, but I could not think of that. I hope you do not
suppose that I came to join on to you. I really came to help with the
child, and to thank you for so kindly giving us your rooms last night. I
hope that you have not been put to any great inconvenience.']
qText:
Thank you very much, but I could not think of that. I hope you do not
suppose that I came to join on to you. I really came to help with the
child, and to thank you for so kindly giving us your rooms last night. I
hope that you have not been put to any great inconvenience.
speaker: Lucy

qTextArr:
['My dear,', 'I think that you are repeating what
you have heard older people say. You are pretending to be touchy; but
you are not really. Stop being so tiresome, and tell me instead what
part of the church you want to see. To take you to it will be a real
pleasure.']
qText:
My dear, I think that you are repeating what
you have heard older people say. You are pretending to be touchy; but
you are not really. Stop being so tiresome, and tell me instead what
part of the church you want to see. To take you to it will be a real
pleasure.
speaker: Mr. Emerson

qTextArr: ['I am not touchy, I hope. It is the Giottos that I want to see, if you\nwill kindly tell me which they are.']
qText:
I am not touchy, I hope. It is the Giottos that I want to see, if you
will kindly tell me which they are.
speaker: Lucy

qTextArr:
['Remember,', 'the facts about this church of Santa Croce;
how it was built by faith in the full fervour of medievalism, before
any taint of the Renaissance had appeared. Observe how Giotto in these
frescoes--now, unhappily, ruined by restoration--is untroubled by the
snares of anatomy and perspective. Could anything be more majestic, more
pathetic, beautiful, true? How little, we feel, avails knowledge and
technical cleverness against a man who truly feels!']
qText:
Remember, the facts about this church of Santa Croce;
how it was built by faith in the full fervour of medievalism, before
any taint of the Renaissance had appeared. Observe how Giotto in these
frescoes--now, unhappily, ruined by restoration--is untroubled by the
snares of anatomy and perspective. Could anything be more majestic, more
pathetic, beautiful, true? How little, we feel, avails knowledge and
technical cleverness against a man who truly feels!
speaker: George Emerson

qTextArr:
['No!', "Remember nothing of the sort! Built by faith indeed! That simply means
the workmen weren't paid properly. And as for the frescoes, I see no
truth in them. Look at that fat man in blue! He must weigh as much as I
do, and he is shooting into the sky like an air balloon."]
qText:
No! Remember nothing of the sort! Built by faith indeed! That simply means
the workmen weren't paid properly. And as for the frescoes, I see no
truth in them. Look at that fat man in blue! He must weigh as much as I
do, and he is shooting into the sky like an air balloon.
speaker: Mr. Emerson

qTextArr: ["Now, did this happen, or didn't it? Yes or no?"]
qText: Now, did this happen, or didn't it? Yes or no?
speaker: Mr. Emerson

qTextArr: ['It happened like this, if it happened at all. I would rather go up to\nheaven by myself than be pushed by cherubs; and if I got there I should\nlike my friends to lean out of it, just as they do here.']
qText:
It happened like this, if it happened at all. I would rather go up to
heaven by myself than be pushed by cherubs; and if I got there I should
like my friends to lean out of it, just as they do here.
speaker: George Emerson

qTextArr: ['You will never go up,', 'You and I, dear boy, will\nlie at peace in the earth that bore us, and our names will disappear as\nsurely as our work survives.']
qText:
You will never go up, You and I, dear boy, will
lie at peace in the earth that bore us, and our names will disappear as
surely as our work survives.
speaker: Mr. Emerson

qTextArr: ['In Hell,', "He's unhappy."]
qText: In Hell, He's unhappy.

qTextArr: ['Oh, dear!']
qText: Oh, dear!

qTextArr:
['How can he be unhappy when he is strong and alive? What more is one
to give him? And think how he has been brought up--free from all the
superstition and ignorance that lead men to hate one another in the name
of God. With such an education as that, I thought he was bound to grow
up happy.']
qText:
How can he be unhappy when he is strong and alive? What more is one
to give him? And think how he has been brought up--free from all the
superstition and ignorance that lead men to hate one another in the name

up happy.
speaker: Mr. Emerson

qTextArr:
['What are we to do with him?', 'He comes out for his holiday to
Italy, and behaves--like that; like the little child who ought to have
been playing, and who hurt himself upon the tombstone. Eh? What did you
say?']
qText:
What are we to do with him? He comes out for his holiday to
Italy, and behaves--like that; like the little child who ought to have
been playing, and who hurt himself upon the tombstone. Eh? What did you
say?
speaker: Mr. Emerson

qTextArr:
["Now don't be stupid over this. I don't require you to fall in love with
my boy, but I do think you might try and understand him. You are nearer
his age, and if you let yourself go I am sure you are sensible. You
might help me. He has known so few women, and you have the time.
You stop here several weeks, I suppose? But let yourself go. You are
inclined to get muddled, if I may judge from last night. Let yourself
go. Pull out from the depths those thoughts that you do not understand,
and spread them out in the sunlight and know the meaning of them. By
understanding George you may learn to understand yourself. It will be
good for both of you."]
qText:
Now don't be stupid over this. I don't require you to fall in love with
my boy, but I do think you might try and understand him. You are nearer
his age, and if you let yourself go I am sure you are sensible. You
might help me. He has known so few women, and you have the time.
You stop here several weeks, I suppose? But let yourself go. You are
inclined to get muddled, if I may judge from last night. Let yourself
go. Pull out from the depths those thoughts that you do not understand,
and spread them out in the sunlight and know the meaning of them. By
understanding George you may learn to understand yourself. It will be
good for both of you.
speaker: Mr. Emerson

qTextArr: ["I only know what it is that's wrong with him; not why it is."]
qText: I only know what it is that's wrong with him; not why it is.
speaker: Mr. Emerson

qTextArr: ['And what is it?']
qText: And what is it?
speaker: Lucy

qTextArr: ["The old trouble; things won't fit."]
qText: The old trouble; things won't fit.
speaker: Mr. Emerson

qTextArr: ['What things?']
qText: What things?
speaker: Lucy

qTextArr: ["The things of the universe. It is quite true. They don't."]
qText: The things of the universe. It is quite true. They don't.
speaker: Mr. Emerson

qTextArr: ['Oh, Mr. Emerson, whatever do you mean?']
qText: Oh, Mr. Emerson, whatever do you mean?
speaker: Lucy

qTextArr:
["George and I both know this, but why does it distress him? We know that
we come from the winds, and that we shall return to them; that all life
is perhaps a knot, a tangle, a blemish in the eternal smoothness. But
why should this make us unhappy? Let us rather love one another, and
work and rejoice. I don't believe in this world sorrow."]
qText:
George and I both know this, but why does it distress him? We know that
we come from the winds, and that we shall return to them; that all life
is perhaps a knot, a tangle, a blemish in the eternal smoothness. But
why should this make us unhappy? Let us rather love one another, and
work and rejoice. I don't believe in this world sorrow.
speaker: Mr. Emerson

qText:

qText: Miss Bartlett.

qTextArr: ['In the nave.']
qText: In the nave.

qTextArr: ['Poor girl!', 'Poor girl!']
qText: Poor girl! Poor girl!
speaker: Mr. Emerson

qTextArr:
["Poor girl? I fail to understand the point of that remark. I think
myself a very fortunate girl, I assure you. I'm thoroughly happy, and
having a splendid time. Pray don't waste time mourning over me. There's
enough sorrow in the world, isn't there, without trying to invent it.
Good-bye. Thank you both so much for all your kindness. Ah, yes! there
does come my cousin. A delightful morning! Santa Croce is a wonderful
church."]
qText:
Poor girl? I fail to understand the point of that remark. I think
myself a very fortunate girl, I assure you. I'm thoroughly happy, and
having a splendid time. Pray don't waste time mourning over me. There's
enough sorrow in the world, isn't there, without trying to invent it.
Good-bye. Thank you both so much for all your kindness. Ah, yes! there
does come my cousin. A delightful morning! Santa Croce is a wonderful
church.
speaker: Lucy

['Cousin of one of my parishioners. I do not consider her choice of a
piece happy. Beethoven is so usually simple and direct in his appeal
that it is sheer perversity to choose a thing like that, which, if
anything, disturbs.']
qText:

piece happy. Beethoven is so usually simple and direct in his appeal
that it is sheer perversity to choose a thing like that, which, if

qText:
It will be a novel, dealing with modern Italy.
Let me refer you for an account to Miss Catharine Alan, who uses words

speaker: Mr. Beebe

qTextArr:
["I wish Miss Lavish would tell me herself. We started such friends. But
I don't think she ought to have run away with Baedeker that morning in
Santa Croce. Charlotte was most annoyed at finding me practically alone,
and so I couldn't help being a little annoyed with Miss Lavish."]
qText:
I wish Miss Lavish would tell me herself. We started such friends. But
I don't think she ought to have run away with Baedeker that morning in
Santa Croce. Charlotte was most annoyed at finding me practically alone,
and so I couldn't help being a little annoyed with Miss Lavish.
speaker: Lucy

qTextArr: ['The two ladies, at all events, have made it up.']
qText: The two ladies, at all events, have made it up.
speaker: Mr. Beebe

qTextArr: ['Oh, dear Miss Honeychurch, you will catch a chill! And Mr. Beebe here\nbesides. Who would suppose this is Italy? There is my sister actually\nnursing the hot-water can; no comforts or proper provisions.']
qText:
Oh, dear Miss Honeychurch, you will catch a chill! And Mr. Beebe here
besides. Who would suppose this is Italy? There is my sister actually
nursing the hot-water can; no comforts or proper provisions.
speaker: Miss Catherine Alan

qTextArr:
['I could hear your beautiful playing, Miss Honeychurch, though I was in
my room with the door shut. Doors shut; indeed, most necessary. No one
has the least idea of privacy in this country. And one person catches it
from another.']
qText:
I could hear your beautiful playing, Miss Honeychurch, though I was in
my room with the door shut. Doors shut; indeed, most necessary. No one
has the least idea of privacy in this country. And one person catches it
from another.
speaker: Miss Catherine Alan

qTextArr: ['Fa niente, sono vecchia.']
qText: Fa niente, sono vecchia.
speaker: The Chambermaid
refExp: the chambermaid burst in upon him in his bath exclaiming

qTextArr:
['I quite agree with you, Miss Alan. The Italians
are a most unpleasant people. They pry everywhere, they see everything,
and they know what we want before we know it ourselves. We are at their
mercy. They read our thoughts, they foretell our desires. From the
cab-driver down to--to Giotto, they turn us inside out, and I resent
it. Yet in their heart of hearts they are--how superficial! They have no
conception of the intellectual life. How right is Signora Bertolini, who
exclaimed to me the other day:']
qText:
I quite agree with you, Miss Alan. The Italians
are a most unpleasant people. They pry everywhere, they see everything,
and they know what we want before we know it ourselves. We are at their
mercy. They read our thoughts, they foretell our desires. From the
cab-driver down to--to Giotto, they turn us inside out, and I resent
it. Yet in their heart of hearts they are--how superficial! They have no
conception of the intellectual life. How right is Signora Bertolini, who
exclaimed to me the other day:

qTextArr:
['Oh, Mr. Beebe,', "Indeed,
though it is dreadful for her to smoke, it is not quite as dreadful as
you suppose. She took to it, practically in despair, after her
life's work was carried away in a landslip. Surely that makes it more

qText:
Oh, Mr. Beebe, Indeed,
though it is dreadful for her to smoke, it is not quite as dreadful as
you suppose. She took to it, practically in despair, after her
life's work was carried away in a landslip. Surely that makes it more
excusable.
speaker: Miss Catherine Alan

qTextArr: ['What was that?']
qText: What was that?
speaker: Lucy

qTextArr:
['It was
a novel--and I am afraid, from what I can gather, not a very nice novel.
It is so sad when people who have abilities misuse them, and I must say
they nearly always do. Anyhow, she left it almost finished in the Grotto
of the Calvary at the Capuccini Hotel at Amalfi while she went for a
little ink. She said:', 'But you know
what Italians are, and meanwhile the Grotto fell roaring on to the
beach, and the saddest thing of all is that she cannot remember what she
has written. The poor thing was very ill after it, and so got tempted
into cigarettes. It is a great secret, but I am glad to say that she is
writing another novel. She told Teresa and Miss Pole the other day that
she had got up all the local colour--this novel is to be about modern
Italy; the other was historical--but that she could not start till she
had an idea. First she tried Perugia for an inspiration, then she came
here--this must on no account get round. And so cheerful through it all!
I cannot help thinking that there is something to admire in everyone,
even if you do not approve of them.']
qText:
It was
a novel--and I am afraid, from what I can gather, not a very nice novel.
It is so sad when people who have abilities misuse them, and I must say
they nearly always do. Anyhow, she left it almost finished in the Grotto
of the Calvary at the Capuccini Hotel at Amalfi while she went for a
little ink. She said: But you know
what Italians are, and meanwhile the Grotto fell roaring on to the
beach, and the saddest thing of all is that she cannot remember what she
has written. The poor thing was very ill after it, and so got tempted
into cigarettes. It is a great secret, but I am glad to say that she is
writing another novel. She told Teresa and Miss Pole the other day that
she had got up all the local colour--this novel is to be about modern
Italy; the other was historical--but that she could not start till she
had an idea. First she tried Perugia for an inspiration, then she came
here--this must on no account get round. And so cheerful through it all!
I cannot help thinking that there is something to admire in everyone,
even if you do not approve of them.

All the same, she is a little too--I hardly like to say unwomanly, but

qTextArr: ["I don't know, Miss Honeychurch, if you have noticed that Miss Pole, the\nlady who has so much yellow hair, takes lemonade. That old Mr. Emerson,\nwho puts things very strangely--"]
qText:
I don't know, Miss Honeychurch, if you have noticed that Miss Pole, the
lady who has so much yellow hair, takes lemonade. That old Mr. Emerson,
who puts things very strangely--
speaker: Miss Catherine Alan

qTextArr:
['Stomach. He warned Miss Pole of her stomach-acidity, he called it--and
he may have meant to be kind. I must say I forgot myself and laughed; it
was so sudden. As Teresa truly said, it was no laughing matter. But the
point is that Miss Lavish was positively ATTRACTED by his mentioning
S., and said she liked plain speaking, and meeting different grades of
thought. She thought they were commercial travellers--', 'was the
word she used--and all through dinner she tried to prove that England,
our great and beloved country, rests on nothing but commerce. Teresa was
very much annoyed, and left the table before the cheese, saying as she
did so:', 'and pointed to that beautiful picture of Lord Tennyson. Then Miss
Lavish said:', "Just imagine! 'Tut! The early
Victorians.' My sister had gone, and I felt bound to speak. I said", 'It was horrible
speaking. I reminded her how the Queen had been to Ireland when she did
not want to go, and I must say she was dumbfounded, and made no reply.
But, unluckily, Mr. Emerson overheard this part, and called in his deep
voice:', 'The
woman! I tell things so badly; but you see what a tangle we were in
by this time, all on account of S. having been mentioned in the first
place. But that was not all. After dinner Miss Lavish actually came up
and said:', 'Needless to say, I refused such an unsuitable
invitation, and she had the impertinence to tell me that it would
broaden my ideas, and said that she had four brothers, all University
men, except one who was in the army, who always made a point of talking
to commercial travellers.']
qText:
Stomach. He warned Miss Pole of her stomach-acidity, he called it--and
he may have meant to be kind. I must say I forgot myself and laughed; it
was so sudden. As Teresa truly said, it was no laughing matter. But the
point is that Miss Lavish was positively ATTRACTED by his mentioning
S., and said she liked plain speaking, and meeting different grades of
thought. She thought they were commercial travellers-- was the
word she used--and all through dinner she tried to prove that England,
our great and beloved country, rests on nothing but commerce. Teresa was
very much annoyed, and left the table before the cheese, saying as she
did so: and pointed to that beautiful picture of Lord Tennyson. Then Miss
Lavish said: Just imagine! 'Tut! The early
Victorians.' My sister had gone, and I felt bound to speak. I said It was horrible
speaking. I reminded her how the Queen had been to Ireland when she did
not want to go, and I must say she was dumbfounded, and made no reply.
But, unluckily, Mr. Emerson overheard this part, and called in his deep
voice: The
woman! I tell things so badly; but you see what a tangle we were in
by this time, all on account of S. having been mentioned in the first
place. But that was not all. After dinner Miss Lavish actually came up
and said: Needless to say, I refused such an unsuitable
invitation, and she had the impertinence to tell me that it would
broaden my ideas, and said that she had four brothers, all University
men, except one who was in the army, who always made a point of talking
to commercial travellers.

qText:

qText:
I didn't know what to do with them, They were covered with blood. There! I'm glad I've told you; and all
the time we were making conversation I was wondering what to do with
them. They've gone. I did mind them so, and one is so foolish, it seemed better
that they should go out to the sea--I don't know; I may just mean that
they frightened me. For something
tremendous has happened; I must face it without getting muddled. It
isn't exactly that a man has died.
speaker: George Emerson

me absolutely everything that you saw from the beginning.

qTextArr: ['But perhaps you would rather not?']
qText: But perhaps you would rather not?
speaker: Miss Lavish

qTextArr: ["I'm sorry--if you could manage without it, I think I would rather not."]
qText: I'm sorry--if you could manage without it, I think I would rather not.
speaker: Lucy

qTextArr: ['It is I who am sorry,', "literary hacks are shameless\ncreatures. I believe there's no secret of the human heart into which we\nwouldn't pry."]
qText:
It is I who am sorry, literary hacks are shameless
creatures. I believe there's no secret of the human heart into which we
wouldn't pry.
speaker: Miss Lavish

qTextArr: ["What is the heroine's name?"]
qText: What is the heroine's name?
speaker: Miss Bartlett

qTextArr: ['Leonora,']
qText: Leonora,
speaker: Miss Lavish

qTextArr: ["I do hope she's nice."]
qText: I do hope she's nice.
speaker: Miss Bartlett

qTextArr: ['And what is the plot?']
qText: And what is the plot?
speaker: Miss Bartlett

qTextArr:
['I hope you will excuse me for boring on like this,', 'It is so tempting to talk to really sympathetic people.
Of course, this is the barest outline. There will be a deal of local
colouring, descriptions of Florence and the neighbourhood, and I shall
also introduce some humorous characters. And let me give you all fair
warning: I intend to be unmerciful to the British tourist.']
qText:
I hope you will excuse me for boring on like this, It is so tempting to talk to really sympathetic people.
Of course, this is the barest outline. There will be a deal of local
colouring, descriptions of Florence and the neighbourhood, and I shall
also introduce some humorous characters. And let me give you all fair
warning: I intend to be unmerciful to the British tourist.
speaker: Miss Lavish

qTextArr: ['Oh, you wicked woman,', 'I am sure you are thinking\nof the Emersons.']
qText:
Oh, you wicked woman, I am sure you are thinking
of the Emersons.
speaker: Miss Bartlett

qTextArr:
["I confess that in Italy my sympathies are not with my own countrymen.
It is the neglected Italians who attract me, and whose lives I am going
to paint so far as I can. For I repeat and I insist, and I have always
held most strongly, that a tragedy such as yesterday's is not the less
tragic because it happened in humble life."]
qText:
I confess that in Italy my sympathies are not with my own countrymen.
It is the neglected Italians who attract me, and whose lives I am going
to paint so far as I can. For I repeat and I insist, and I have always
held most strongly, that a tragedy such as yesterday's is not the less
tragic because it happened in humble life.
speaker: Miss Lavish

qTextArr: ['She is my idea of a really clever woman,', 'That\nlast remark struck me as so particularly true. It should be a most\npathetic novel.']
qText:
She is my idea of a really clever woman, That
last remark struck me as so particularly true. It should be a most
pathetic novel.
speaker: Miss Bartlett

qTextArr:
['She is emancipated, but only in the very best sense of the word,', 'None but the superficial would be
shocked at her. We had a long talk yesterday. She believes in justice
and truth and human interest. She told me also that she has a high
opinion of the destiny of woman--Mr. Eager! Why, how nice! What a
pleasant surprise!']
qText:
She is emancipated, but only in the very best sense of the word, None but the superficial would be
shocked at her. We had a long talk yesterday. She believes in justice
and truth and human interest. She told me also that she has a high
opinion of the destiny of woman--Mr. Eager! Why, how nice! What a
pleasant surprise!
speaker: Miss Bartlett

qTextArr: ['Ah, not for me,', 'for I have been watching\nyou and Miss Honeychurch for quite a little time.']
qText:
Ah, not for me, for I have been watching
you and Miss Honeychurch for quite a little time.
speaker: Rev. Cuthbert Eager

qTextArr: ['We were chatting to Miss Lavish.']
qText: We were chatting to Miss Lavish.
speaker: Miss Bartlett

qTextArr: ['So I saw. Were you indeed? Andate via! sono occupato!']
qText: So I saw. Were you indeed? Andate via! sono occupato!
speaker: Rev. Cuthbert Eager

qTextArr:
["I am about to venture a suggestion. Would you and
Miss Honeychurch be disposed to join me in a drive some day this week--a
drive in the hills? We might go up by Fiesole and back by Settignano.
There is a point on that road where we could get down and have an
hour's ramble on the hillside. The view thence of Florence is most
beautiful--far better than the hackneyed view of Fiesole. It is the view
that Alessio Baldovinetti is fond of introducing into his pictures. That
man had a decided feeling for landscape. Decidedly. But who looks at it
to-day? Ah, the world is too much for us."]
qText:
I am about to venture a suggestion. Would you and
Miss Honeychurch be disposed to join me in a drive some day this week--a
drive in the hills? We might go up by Fiesole and back by Settignano.
There is a point on that road where we could get down and have an
hour's ramble on the hillside. The view thence of Florence is most
beautiful--far better than the hackneyed view of Fiesole. It is the view
that Alessio Baldovinetti is fond of introducing into his pictures. That
man had a decided feeling for landscape. Decidedly. But who looks at it
to-day? Ah, the world is too much for us.
speaker: Rev. Cuthbert Eager
menEnts: [[['Miss Bartlett'], ['Lucy'], ['Lucy', 'Rev. Cuthbert Eager', 'Miss Bartlett'], ['Lucy', 'Rev. Cuthbert Eager', 'Miss Bartlett'], ['Lucy', 'Miss Bartlett', 'Rev. Cuthbert Eager']]]

qTextArr:
['So we shall be a partie carree,', 'In these days of
toil and tumult one has great needs of the country and its message of
purity. Andate via! andate presto, presto! Ah, the town! Beautiful as it
is, it is the town.']
qText:
So we shall be a partie carree, In these days of
toil and tumult one has great needs of the country and its message of
purity. Andate via! andate presto, presto! Ah, the town! Beautiful as it
is, it is the town.
speaker: Rev. Cuthbert Eager

qTextArr:
['This very square--so I am told--witnessed yesterday the most sordid of
tragedies. To one who loves the Florence of Dante and Savonarola
there is something portentous in such desecration--portentous and
humiliating.']
qText:
This very square--so I am told--witnessed yesterday the most sordid of
tragedies. To one who loves the Florence of Dante and Savonarola
there is something portentous in such desecration--portentous and
humiliating.
speaker: Rev. Cuthbert Eager

qTextArr: ['Humiliating indeed,', 'Miss Honeychurch happened to\nbe passing through as it happened. She can hardly bear to speak of it.']
qText:
Humiliating indeed, Miss Honeychurch happened to
be passing through as it happened. She can hardly bear to speak of it.
speaker: Miss Bartlett

qTextArr: ['And how came we to have you here?']
qText: And how came we to have you here?
speaker: Rev. Cuthbert Eager

qTextArr: ['Do\nnot blame her, please, Mr. Eager. The fault is mine: I left her\nunchaperoned.']
qText:
Do
not blame her, please, Mr. Eager. The fault is mine: I left her
unchaperoned.
speaker: Miss Bartlett

qTextArr: ['So you were here alone, Miss Honeychurch?']
qText: So you were here alone, Miss Honeychurch?
speaker: Rev. Cuthbert Eager

qTextArr: ['Practically.']
qText: Practically.
speaker: Lucy

qTextArr: ['One of our pension acquaintances kindly brought her home,']
qText: One of our pension acquaintances kindly brought her home,
speaker: Miss Bartlett

qTextArr: ['For her also it must have been a terrible experience. I trust that\nneither of you was at all--that it was not in your immediate proximity?']
qText:
For her also it must have been a terrible experience. I trust that
neither of you was at all--that it was not in your immediate proximity?
speaker: Rev. Cuthbert Eager

qTextArr: ['He died by the fountain, I believe,']
qText: He died by the fountain, I believe,
speaker: Lucy

qTextArr: ['And you and your friend--']
qText: And you and your friend--
speaker: Rev. Cuthbert Eager

qTextArr: ['Were over at the Loggia.']
qText: Were over at the Loggia.
speaker: Lucy

qTextArr:
['That must have saved you much. You have not, of course, seen the
disgraceful illustrations which the gutter Press--This man is a public
nuisance; he knows that I am a resident perfectly well, and yet he goes
on worrying me to buy his vulgar views.']
qText:
That must have saved you much. You have not, of course, seen the
disgraceful illustrations which the gutter Press--This man is a public
nuisance; he knows that I am a resident perfectly well, and yet he goes
on worrying me to buy his vulgar views.
speaker: Rev. Cuthbert Eager

qTextArr: ['This is too much!']
qText: This is too much!
speaker: Rev. Cuthbert Eager

qTextArr: ['Willingly would I purchase--']
qText: Willingly would I purchase--
speaker: Miss Bartlett

qTextArr: ['Ignore him,']
qText: Ignore him,
speaker: Rev. Cuthbert Eager

qTextArr: ['How wonderfully people rise in these days!']
qText: How wonderfully people rise in these days!
speaker: Miss Bartlett

qTextArr:
['Generally,', 'one has only sympathy for their
success. The desire for education and for social advance--in these
things there is something not wholly vile. There are some working men
whom one would be very willing to see out here in Florence--little as
they would make of it.']
qText:
Generally, one has only sympathy for their
success. The desire for education and for social advance--in these
things there is something not wholly vile. There are some working men
whom one would be very willing to see out here in Florence--little as
they would make of it.
speaker: Rev. Cuthbert Eager

qTextArr: ['Is he a journalist now?']
qText: Is he a journalist now?
speaker: Miss Bartlett

qTextArr: ['He is not; he made an advantageous marriage.']
qText: He is not; he made an advantageous marriage.
speaker: Rev. Cuthbert Eager

qTextArr: ['Oh, so he has a wife.']
qText: Oh, so he has a wife.
speaker: Miss Bartlett

qTextArr:
['Dead, Miss Bartlett, dead. I wonder--yes I wonder how he has the
effrontery to look me in the face, to dare to claim acquaintance with
me. He was in my London parish long ago. The other day in Santa Croce,
when he was with Miss Honeychurch, I snubbed him. Let him beware that he
does not get more than a snub.']
qText:
Dead, Miss Bartlett, dead. I wonder--yes I wonder how he has the
effrontery to look me in the face, to dare to claim acquaintance with
me. He was in my London parish long ago. The other day in Santa Croce,
when he was with Miss Honeychurch, I snubbed him. Let him beware that he
does not get more than a snub.
speaker: Rev. Cuthbert Eager
menEnts: [[['Miss Bartlett'], ['Mr. Emerson'], ['Mr. Emerson'], ['Mr. Emerson'], ['Lucy'], ['Mr. Emerson'], ['Mr. Emerson'], ['Mr. Emerson']]]

qTextArr: ['What?']
qText: What?
speaker: Lucy

qTextArr: ['Exposure!']
qText: Exposure!
speaker: Rev. Cuthbert Eager

qTextArr: ['Do you mean,', 'that he is an irreligious man? We know that\nalready.']
qText:
Do you mean, that he is an irreligious man? We know that
already.
speaker: Lucy

qTextArr: ['Lucy, dear--']
qText: Lucy, dear--
speaker: Miss Bartlett

qTextArr: ['I should be astonished if you knew all. The boy--an innocent child at\nthe time--I will exclude. God knows what his education and his inherited\nqualities may have made him.']
qText:
I should be astonished if you knew all. The boy--an innocent child at
the time--I will exclude. God knows what his education and his inherited
qualities may have made him.
speaker: Rev. Cuthbert Eager

qTextArr: ['Perhaps,', 'it is something that we had better not\nhear.']
qText:
Perhaps, it is something that we had better not
hear.
speaker: Miss Bartlett

qTextArr: ['To speak plainly,', 'it is. I will say no more.']
qText: To speak plainly, it is. I will say no more.
speaker: Rev. Cuthbert Eager

qTextArr: ['You have said very little.']
qText: You have said very little.
speaker: Lucy

qTextArr: ['It was my intention to say very little,']
qText: It was my intention to say very little,
speaker: Rev. Cuthbert Eager

qTextArr: ['Murder, if you want to know,', 'That man murdered his\nwife!']
qText:
Murder, if you want to know, That man murdered his
wife!
speaker: Rev. Cuthbert Eager

qText: How?
speaker: Lucy

qTextArr: ['To all intents and purposes he murdered her. That day in Santa\nCroce--did they say anything against me?']
qText:
To all intents and purposes he murdered her. That day in Santa
Croce--did they say anything against me?
speaker: Rev. Cuthbert Eager

qTextArr: ['Not a word, Mr. Eager--not a single word.']
qText: Not a word, Mr. Eager--not a single word.
speaker: Lucy

qTextArr: ['Oh, I thought they had been libelling me to you. But I suppose it is\nonly their personal charms that makes you defend them.']
qText:
Oh, I thought they had been libelling me to you. But I suppose it is
only their personal charms that makes you defend them.
speaker: Rev. Cuthbert Eager
menEnts: [[['Mr. Emerson', 'George Emerson'], ['Lucy'], ['Mr. Emerson', 'George Emerson'], ['Lucy'], ['Mr. Emerson', 'George Emerson']]]

qTextArr: ["I'm not defending them,", "They're nothing to me."]
qText: I'm not defending them, They're nothing to me.
speaker: Lucy

qTextArr: ['How could you think she was defending them?']
qText: How could you think she was defending them?
speaker: Miss Bartlett

qTextArr: ['She will find it difficult. For that man has murdered his wife in the\nsight of God.']
qText:
She will find it difficult. For that man has murdered his wife in the
sight of God.
speaker: Mr. Beebe

qTextArr: ['I must be going,']
qText: I must be going,
speaker: Rev. Cuthbert Eager

qTextArr: ['Drive? Oh, is our drive to come off?']
qText: Drive? Oh, is our drive to come off?
speaker: Lucy

qTextArr:
['Bother the drive!', 'It
is just the drive we had arranged with Mr. Beebe without any fuss at
all. Why should he invite us in that absurd manner? We might as well
invite him. We are each paying for ourselves.']
qText:
Bother the drive! It
is just the drive we had arranged with Mr. Beebe without any fuss at
all. Why should he invite us in that absurd manner? We might as well
invite him. We are each paying for ourselves.
speaker: Lucy

qTextArr: ['If that is so, dear--if the drive we and Mr. Beebe are going with Mr.\nEager is really the same as the one we are going with Mr. Beebe, then I\nforesee a sad kettle of fish.']
qText:
If that is so, dear--if the drive we and Mr. Beebe are going with Mr.
Eager is really the same as the one we are going with Mr. Beebe, then I
foresee a sad kettle of fish.
speaker: Miss Bartlett

qText: How?
speaker: Lucy

qTextArr: ['Because Mr. Beebe has asked Eleanor Lavish to come, too.']
qText: Because Mr. Beebe has asked Eleanor Lavish to come, too.
speaker: Miss Bartlett

qTextArr: ['That will mean another carriage.']
qText: That will mean another carriage.
speaker: Lucy

qTextArr: ['Far worse. Mr. Eager does not like Eleanor. She knows it herself. The\ntruth must be told; she is too unconventional for him.']
qText:
Far worse. Mr. Eager does not like Eleanor. She knows it herself. The
truth must be told; she is too unconventional for him.
speaker: Miss Bartlett

qTextArr: ['where things might lead to,']
qText: where things might lead to,
speaker: Miss Bartlett

qTextArr:
['Whether it is Mr. Beebe who forgot to tell Mr. Eager, or Mr.
Eager who forgot when he told us, or whether they have decided to leave
Eleanor out altogether--which they could scarcely do--but in any case
we must be prepared. It is you they really want; I am only asked for
appearances. You shall go with the two gentlemen, and I and Eleanor will
follow behind. A one-horse carriage would do for us. Yet how difficult
it is!']
qText:
Whether it is Mr. Beebe who forgot to tell Mr. Eager, or Mr.
Eager who forgot when he told us, or whether they have decided to leave
Eleanor out altogether--which they could scarcely do--but in any case
we must be prepared. It is you they really want; I am only asked for
appearances. You shall go with the two gentlemen, and I and Eleanor will
follow behind. A one-horse carriage would do for us. Yet how difficult

qTextArr: ['It is indeed,']
qText: It is indeed,
speaker: Lucy

qTextArr: ['What do you think about it?']
qText: What do you think about it?
speaker: Miss Bartlett

qTextArr: ["I don't know what I think, nor what I want."]
qText: I don't know what I think, nor what I want.
speaker: Lucy

qTextArr: ["Oh, dear, Lucy! I do hope Florence isn't boring you. Speak the word,\nand, as you know, I would take you to the ends of the earth to-morrow."]
qText:
Oh, dear, Lucy! I do hope Florence isn't boring you. Speak the word,
and, as you know, I would take you to the ends of the earth to-morrow.
speaker: Miss Bartlett

qTextArr: ['Thank you, Charlotte,']
qText: Thank you, Charlotte,
speaker: Lucy

qTextArr: ['And the news?']
qText: And the news?
speaker: Miss Bartlett

qTextArr: ['Mrs. Vyse and her son have gone to Rome,', 'Do you know the Vyses?']
qText: Mrs. Vyse and her son have gone to Rome, Do you know the Vyses?
speaker: Lucy

qTextArr: ['Oh, not that way back. We can never have too much of the dear Piazza\nSignoria.']
qText:
Oh, not that way back. We can never have too much of the dear Piazza
Signoria.
speaker: Miss Bartlett

qTextArr: ["They're nice people, the Vyses. So clever--my idea of what's really\nclever. Don't you long to be in Rome?"]
qText:
They're nice people, the Vyses. So clever--my idea of what's really
clever. Don't you long to be in Rome?
speaker: Lucy

qTextArr: ['I die for it!']
qText: I die for it!
speaker: Miss Bartlett

qTextArr:
['Charlotte!', "Here's an idea. What if we popped
off to Rome to-morrow--straight to the Vyses' hotel? For I do know what
I want. I'm sick of Florence. No, you said you'd go to the ends of the
earth! Do! Do!"]
qText:
Charlotte! Here's an idea. What if we popped
off to Rome to-morrow--straight to the Vyses' hotel? For I do know what
I want. I'm sick of Florence. No, you said you'd go to the ends of the
earth! Do! Do!
speaker: Lucy

qTextArr: ['Oh, you droll person! Pray, what would become of your drive in the\nhills?']
qText:
Oh, you droll person! Pray, what would become of your drive in the
hills?
speaker: Miss Bartlett
refExp: Miss Bartlett with equal vivacity replied

qTextArr: ['So, Miss Honeychurch, you are travelling? As a student of art?']
qText: So, Miss Honeychurch, you are travelling? As a student of art?
speaker: Rev. Cuthbert Eager

qTextArr: ['Oh, dear me, no--oh, no!']
qText: Oh, dear me, no--oh, no!
speaker: Lucy

qTextArr: ['Perhaps as a student of human nature,', 'like\nmyself?']
qText:
Perhaps as a student of human nature, like
myself?
speaker: Miss Lavish

qTextArr: ['Oh, no. I am here as a tourist.']
qText: Oh, no. I am here as a tourist.
speaker: Lucy

qTextArr:
['Oh, indeed,', "Are you indeed? If you will not think me
rude, we residents sometimes pity you poor tourists not a little--handed
about like a parcel of goods from Venice to Florence, from Florence to
Rome, living herded together in pensions or hotels, quite unconscious
of anything that is outside Baedeker, their one anxiety to get 'done'
or 'through' and go on somewhere else. The result is, they mix up towns,
rivers, palaces in one inextricable whirl. You know the American girl
in Punch who says:", 'And the father
replies:', "There's travelling for you. Ha! ha! ha!"]
qText:
Oh, indeed, Are you indeed? If you will not think me
rude, we residents sometimes pity you poor tourists not a little--handed
about like a parcel of goods from Venice to Florence, from Florence to
Rome, living herded together in pensions or hotels, quite unconscious
of anything that is outside Baedeker, their one anxiety to get 'done'
or 'through' and go on somewhere else. The result is, they mix up towns,
rivers, palaces in one inextricable whirl. You know the American girl
in Punch who says: And the father
replies: There's travelling for you. Ha! ha! ha!
speaker: Rev. Cuthbert Eager

qTextArr: ['I quite agree,', 'The narrowness and superficiality of the\nAnglo-Saxon tourist is nothing less than a menace.']
qText:
I quite agree, The narrowness and superficiality of the
Anglo-Saxon tourist is nothing less than a menace.
speaker: Miss Lavish

qTextArr:
['Quite so. Now, the English colony at Florence, Miss Honeychurch--and it
is of considerable size, though, of course, not all equally--a few are
here for trade, for example. But the greater part are students. Lady
Helen Laverstock is at present busy over Fra Angelico. I mention her
name because we are passing her villa on the left. No, you can only see
it if you stand--no, do not stand; you will fall. She is very proud of
that thick hedge. Inside, perfect seclusion. One might have gone back
six hundred years. Some critics believe that her garden was the scene of
The Decameron, which lends it an additional interest, does it not?']
qText:
Quite so. Now, the English colony at Florence, Miss Honeychurch--and it
is of considerable size, though, of course, not all equally--a few are
here for trade, for example. But the greater part are students. Lady
Helen Laverstock is at present busy over Fra Angelico. I mention her
name because we are passing her villa on the left. No, you can only see
it if you stand--no, do not stand; you will fall. She is very proud of
that thick hedge. Inside, perfect seclusion. One might have gone back
six hundred years. Some critics believe that her garden was the scene of
The Decameron, which lends it an additional interest, does it not?
speaker: Rev. Cuthbert Eager

qTextArr: ['It does indeed!', 'Tell me, where do they place the\nscene of that wonderful seventh day?']
qText:
It does indeed! Tell me, where do they place the
scene of that wonderful seventh day?
speaker: Miss Lavish

qTextArr:
["Doubtless you know
her monographs in the series of 'Mediaeval Byways'? He is working at
Gemistus Pletho. Sometimes as I take tea in their beautiful grounds I
hear, over the wall, the electric tram squealing up the new road with
its loads of hot, dusty, unintelligent tourists who are going to 'do'
Fiesole in an hour in order that they may say they have been there, and
I think--think--I think how little they think what lies so near them."]
qText:
Doubtless you know
her monographs in the series of 'Mediaeval Byways'? He is working at
Gemistus Pletho. Sometimes as I take tea in their beautiful grounds I
hear, over the wall, the electric tram squealing up the new road with
its loads of hot, dusty, unintelligent tourists who are going to 'do'

qText: Va bene, signore, va bene, va bene,

qTextArr: ['She is my sister,']
qText: She is my sister,
speaker: The Driver

qTextArr: ['Most certainly I would let them be,', 'But I dare say I\nshall receive scant support. I have always flown in the face of the\nconventions all my life. This is what I call an adventure.']
qText:
Most certainly I would let them be, But I dare say I
shall receive scant support. I have always flown in the face of the
conventions all my life. This is what I call an adventure.

qTextArr: ['We must not submit,', "I knew he was trying it on. He is\ntreating us as if we were a party of Cook's tourists."]
qText:
We must not submit, I knew he was trying it on. He is
treating us as if we were a party of Cook's tourists.

qTextArr: ['Surely no!']
qText: Surely no!
speaker: Miss Lavish

qTextArr:
['Leave them alone,', "Do we find happiness so often that we should turn it off the
box when it happens to sit there? To be driven by lovers--A king might
envy us, and if we part them it's more like sacrilege than anything I
know."]
qText:
Leave them alone, Do we find happiness so often that we should turn it off the
box when it happens to sit there? To be driven by lovers--A king might
envy us, and if we part them it's more like sacrilege than anything I
know.

qTextArr:
["That I deny. It was as restful as sleeping. Aha! he is jolting us now.
Can you wonder? He would like to throw us out, and most certainly he is
justified. And if I were superstitious I'd be frightened of the girl,
too. It doesn't do to injure young people. Have you ever heard of
Lorenzo de Medici?"]
qText:
That I deny. It was as restful as sleeping. Aha! he is jolting us now.
Can you wonder? He would like to throw us out, and most certainly he is
justified. And if I were superstitious I'd be frightened of the girl,
too. It doesn't do to injure young people. Have you ever heard of
Lorenzo de Medici?
speaker: Mr. Emerson

qTextArr:
["Fifty miles of Spring, and we've come up to admire them. Do you suppose
there's any difference between Spring in nature and Spring in man? But
there we go, praising the one and condemning the other as improper,
ashamed that the same laws work eternally through both."]
qText:
Fifty miles of Spring, and we've come up to admire them. Do you suppose
there's any difference between Spring in nature and Spring in man? But
there we go, praising the one and condemning the other as improper,
ashamed that the same laws work eternally through both.
speaker: Mr. Emerson

qTextArr:
["Lucy; without a moment's doubt, Lucy. The ground will do for me. Really
I have not had rheumatism for years. If I do feel it coming on I shall
stand. Imagine your mother's feelings if I let you sit in the wet
in your white linen."]
qText:
Lucy; without a moment's doubt, Lucy. The ground will do for me. Really
I have not had rheumatism for years. If I do feel it coming on I shall
stand. Imagine your mother's feelings if I let you sit in the wet
in your white linen.
speaker: Miss Bartlett

qTextArr: ["Here we are, all settled delightfully. Even if my\ndress is thinner it will not show so much, being brown. Sit down, dear;\nyou are too unselfish; you don't assert yourself enough."]
speaker: Miss Bartlett

qTextArr: ["Now don't be alarmed; this isn't a cold. It's the tiniest\ncough, and I have had it three days. It's nothing to do with sitting\nhere at all."]
qText:
Now don't be alarmed; this isn't a cold. It's the tiniest
cough, and I have had it three days. It's nothing to do with sitting
here at all.
speaker: Miss Bartlett

qTextArr:
['Courage, Miss Honeychurch, courage and faith. If I might say so, there
is something almost blasphemous in this horror of the elements. Are we
seriously to suppose that all these clouds, all this immense electrical
display, is simply called into existence to extinguish you or me?']
qText:
Courage, Miss Honeychurch, courage and faith. If I might say so, there
is something almost blasphemous in this horror of the elements. Are we
seriously to suppose that all these clouds, all this immense electrical
display, is simply called into existence to extinguish you or me?
speaker: Rev. Cuthbert Eager

qTextArr: ['No--of course--']
qText: No--of course--
speaker: Lucy

qTextArr:
['Even from the scientific standpoint the chances against our being
struck are enormous. The steel knives, the only articles which might
attract the current, are in the other carriage. And, in any case, we are
infinitely safer than if we were walking. Courage--courage and faith.']
qText:
Even from the scientific standpoint the chances against our being
struck are enormous. The steel knives, the only articles which might
attract the current, are in the other carriage. And, in any case, we are
infinitely safer than if we were walking. Courage--courage and faith.
speaker: Rev. Cuthbert Eager

qTextArr: ["I have been obstinate and silly--worse than you know, far worse. Once\nby the river--Oh, but he isn't killed--he wouldn't be killed, would he?"]
qText:
I have been obstinate and silly--worse than you know, far worse. Once
by the river--Oh, but he isn't killed--he wouldn't be killed, would he?
speaker: Lucy

qTextArr: ['I trust not. One would always pray against that.']
qText: I trust not. One would always pray against that.
speaker: Miss Bartlett

qTextArr:
["He is really--I think he was taken by surprise, just as I was before.
But this time I'm not to blame; I want you to believe that. I simply
slipped into those violets. No, I want to be really truthful. I am a
little to blame. I had silly thoughts. The sky, you know, was gold,
and the ground all blue, and for a moment he looked like someone in a
book."]
qText:
He is really--I think he was taken by surprise, just as I was before.
But this time I'm not to blame; I want you to believe that. I simply
slipped into those violets. No, I want to be really truthful. I am a
little to blame. I had silly thoughts. The sky, you know, was gold,
and the ground all blue, and for a moment he looked like someone in a
book.
speaker: Lucy

qTextArr: ['In a book?']
qText: In a book?
speaker: Miss Bartlett

qTextArr: ['Heroes--gods--the nonsense of schoolgirls.']
qText: Heroes--gods--the nonsense of schoolgirls.
speaker: Lucy

qTextArr: ['And then?']
qText: And then?
speaker: Miss Bartlett

qTextArr: ['But, Charlotte, you know what happened then.']
qText: But, Charlotte, you know what happened then.
speaker: Lucy

qTextArr: ['I want to be truthful,', 'It is so hard to be absolutely\ntruthful.']
qText:
I want to be truthful, It is so hard to be absolutely
truthful.
speaker: Lucy

qTextArr: ["Don't be troubled, dearest. Wait till you are calmer. We will talk it\nover before bed-time in my room."]
qText:
Don't be troubled, dearest. Wait till you are calmer. We will talk it
over before bed-time in my room.
speaker: Miss Bartlett

qTextArr: ['At last,', "I shall understand myself. I shan't again\nbe troubled by things that come out of nothing, and mean I don't know\nwhat."]
qText:
At last, I shall understand myself. I shan't again
be troubled by things that come out of nothing, and mean I don't know
what.
speaker: Lucy

qText:
Well, dear, I at all events am ready for Bedfordshire. Come into my
room, and I will give a good brush to your hair.

qText: What is to be done? A point, dearest, which you alone can settle.

qText: It has been raining for nearly four hours,
speaker: Lucy

qText: How do you propose to silence him?

qText: How are you going to stop him talking about it?

I, too, intend to judge him charitably. But unfortunately I have met
