qTextArr: ['Exploits?']
qText: Exploits?
speaker: Lucy

qTextArr:
['My poor dear, did you suppose that this was his first? Come here
and listen to me. I am only gathering it from his own remarks. Do you
remember that day at lunch when he argued with Miss Alan that liking one
person is an extra reason for liking another?']
qText:
My poor dear, did you suppose that this was his first? Come here
and listen to me. I am only gathering it from his own remarks. Do you
remember that day at lunch when he argued with Miss Alan that liking one
person is an extra reason for liking another?
speaker: Miss Bartlett

qTextArr:
['Well, I am no prude. There is no need to call him a wicked young man,
but obviously he is thoroughly unrefined. Let us put it down to his
deplorable antecedents and education, if you wish. But we are no farther
on with our question. What do you propose to do?']
qText:
Well, I am no prude. There is no need to call him a wicked young man,
but obviously he is thoroughly unrefined. Let us put it down to his
deplorable antecedents and education, if you wish. But we are no farther
on with our question. What do you propose to do?
speaker: Miss Bartlett
menEnts: [[['George Emerson'], ['George Emerson'], ['Miss Bartlett', 'Lucy'], ['George Emerson'], ['Lucy'], ['Miss Bartlett', 'Lucy'], ['Miss Bartlett', 'Lucy'], ['Lucy']]]

qTextArr: ['I propose to speak to him,']
qText: I propose to speak to him,
speaker: Lucy

qTextArr: ['You see, Charlotte, your kindness--I shall never forget it. But--as you\nsaid--it is my affair. Mine and his.']
qText:
You see, Charlotte, your kindness--I shall never forget it. But--as you
said--it is my affair. Mine and his.
speaker: Lucy

qTextArr: ['And you are going to IMPLORE him, to BEG him to keep silence?']
qText: And you are going to IMPLORE him, to BEG him to keep silence?
speaker: Miss Bartlett

qTextArr: ['Certainly not. There would be no difficulty. Whatever you ask him he\nanswers, yes or no; then it is over. I have been frightened of him. But\nnow I am not one little bit.']
qText:
Certainly not. There would be no difficulty. Whatever you ask him he
answers, yes or no; then it is over. I have been frightened of him. But
now I am not one little bit.
speaker: Lucy

qTextArr:
['But we fear him for you, dear. You are so young and inexperienced, you
have lived among such nice people, that you cannot realize what men can
be--how they can take a brutal pleasure in insulting a woman whom her
sex does not protect and rally round. This afternoon, for example, if I
had not arrived, what would have happened?']
qText:
But we fear him for you, dear. You are so young and inexperienced, you
have lived among such nice people, that you cannot realize what men can
be--how they can take a brutal pleasure in insulting a woman whom her
sex does not protect and rally round. This afternoon, for example, if I
had not arrived, what would have happened?
speaker: Miss Bartlett

qTextArr: ["I can't think,"]
qText: I can't think,
speaker: Lucy

qTextArr: ["What would have happened if I hadn't arrived?"]
qText: What would have happened if I hadn't arrived?
speaker: Miss Bartlett

qTextArr: ["I can't think,"]
qText: I can't think,
speaker: Lucy

qTextArr: ['When he insulted you, how would you have replied?']
qText: When he insulted you, how would you have replied?
speaker: Miss Bartlett

qTextArr: ["I hadn't time to think. You came."]
qText: I hadn't time to think. You came.
speaker: Lucy

qTextArr: ["Yes, but won't you tell me now what you would have done?"]
qText: Yes, but won't you tell me now what you would have done?
speaker: Miss Bartlett

qTextArr: ['I should have--']
qText: I should have--
speaker: Lucy

qTextArr: ['Come away from the window, dear,', 'You will be seen\nfrom the road.']
qText:
Come away from the window, dear, You will be seen

speaker: Miss Bartlett

qTextArr:
["Oh, for a real man! We are only two women, you and I. Mr. Beebe is
hopeless. There is Mr. Eager, but you do not trust him. Oh, for your
brother! He is young, but I know that his sister's insult would rouse
in him a very lion. Thank God, chivalry is not yet dead. There are still
left some men who can reverence woman."]
qText:
Oh, for a real man! We are only two women, you and I. Mr. Beebe is
hopeless. There is Mr. Eager, but you do not trust him. Oh, for your
brother! He is young, but I know that his sister's insult would rouse
in him a very lion. Thank God, chivalry is not yet dead. There are still
left some men who can reverence woman.
speaker: Miss Bartlett

qTextArr: ['Dearest Lucy, how will you ever forgive me?']
qText: Dearest Lucy, how will you ever forgive me?
speaker: Miss Bartlett

qTextArr: ['Charlotte dear, what do you mean? As if I have anything to forgive!']
qText: Charlotte dear, what do you mean? As if I have anything to forgive!
speaker: Lucy

qTextArr: ['You have a great deal, and I have a very great deal to forgive myself,\ntoo. I know well how much I vex you at every turn.']
qText:
You have a great deal, and I have a very great deal to forgive myself,
too. I know well how much I vex you at every turn.
speaker: Miss Bartlett

qTextArr: ['But no--']
qText: But no--
speaker: Lucy

qTextArr:
['Ah, but yes! I feel that our tour together is hardly the success I had
hoped. I might have known it would not do. You want someone younger
and stronger and more in sympathy with you. I am too uninteresting and
old-fashioned--only fit to pack and unpack your things.']
qText:
Ah, but yes! I feel that our tour together is hardly the success I had
hoped. I might have known it would not do. You want someone younger
and stronger and more in sympathy with you. I am too uninteresting and
old-fashioned--only fit to pack and unpack your things.
speaker: Miss Bartlett

qTextArr: ['Please--']
qText: Please--
speaker: Lucy

qTextArr:
['My only consolation was that you found people more to your taste, and
were often able to leave me at home. I had my own poor ideas of what a
lady ought to do, but I hope I did not inflict them on you more than was
necessary. You had your own way about these rooms, at all events.']
qText:
My only consolation was that you found people more to your taste, and
were often able to leave me at home. I had my own poor ideas of what a
lady ought to do, but I hope I did not inflict them on you more than was
necessary. You had your own way about these rooms, at all events.
speaker: Miss Bartlett

qTextArr: ["You mustn't say these things,"]
qText: You mustn't say these things,
speaker: Lucy

qTextArr: ['I have been a failure,', 'Failed to make you\nhappy; failed in my duty to your mother. She has been so generous to me;\nI shall never face her again after this disaster.']
speaker: Miss Bartlett

qTextArr: ["But mother will understand. It is not your fault, this trouble, and it\nisn't a disaster either."]
qText:
But mother will understand. It is not your fault, this trouble, and it
isn't a disaster either.
speaker: Lucy

qTextArr: ['It is my fault, it is a disaster. She will never forgive me, and\nrightly. For instance, what right had I to make friends with Miss\nLavish?']
qText:
It is my fault, it is a disaster. She will never forgive me, and
rightly. For instance, what right had I to make friends with Miss
Lavish?
speaker: Miss Bartlett

qTextArr: ['Every right.']
qText: Every right.
speaker: Lucy

qTextArr: ['When I was here for your sake? If I have vexed you it is equally true\nthat I have neglected you. Your mother will see this as clearly as I do,\nwhen you tell her.']
qText:
When I was here for your sake? If I have vexed you it is equally true
that I have neglected you. Your mother will see this as clearly as I do,
when you tell her.
speaker: Miss Bartlett

qTextArr: ['Why need mother hear of it?']
qText: Why need mother hear of it?
speaker: Lucy
refExp: Lucy from a cowardly wish to improve the situation said

qTextArr: ['But you tell her everything?']
qText: But you tell her everything?
speaker: Miss Bartlett

qTextArr: ['I suppose I do generally.']
qText: I suppose I do generally.
speaker: Lucy

qTextArr: ['I dare not break your confidence. There is something sacred in it.\nUnless you feel that it is a thing you could not tell her.']
qText:
I dare not break your confidence. There is something sacred in it.
Unless you feel that it is a thing you could not tell her.
speaker: Miss Bartlett

qTextArr: ['Naturally I should have told her. But in case she should blame you in\nany way, I promise I will not, I am very willing not to. I will never\nspeak of it either to her or to any one.']
qText:
Naturally I should have told her. But in case she should blame you in
any way, I promise I will not, I am very willing not to. I will never
speak of it either to her or to any one.
speaker: Lucy

qTextArr: ['I wish one word with you in the drawing-room, Mr. Emerson, please.']
qText: I wish one word with you in the drawing-room, Mr. Emerson, please.
speaker: Miss Bartlett

qTextArr: ['Good-night, Mr.\nEmerson.']
qText:
Good-night, Mr.
Emerson.
speaker: Miss Bartlett

qTextArr: ["It isn't true. It can't all be true. I want not to be\nmuddled. I want to grow older quickly."]
qText:
It isn't true. It can't all be true. I want not to be
muddled. I want to grow older quickly.
speaker: Lucy

qTextArr: ['Go to bed at once, dear. You need all the rest you can get.']
qText: Go to bed at once, dear. You need all the rest you can get.
speaker: Miss Bartlett

qTextArr: ["Where aren't they?", "I\ntell you I'm getting fairly sick."]
qText:
Where aren't they? I
tell you I'm getting fairly sick.
speaker: Freddy

qTextArr: ["For goodness' sake go out of my drawing-room, then?"]
qText: For goodness' sake go out of my drawing-room, then?
speaker: Mrs. Honeychurch

qTextArr: ['I think things are coming to a head,']
qText: I think things are coming to a head,
speaker: Mrs. Honeychurch

qTextArr: ['Time they did.']
qText: Time they did.
speaker: Freddy

qTextArr: ['I am glad that Cecil is asking her this once more.']
qText: I am glad that Cecil is asking her this once more.
speaker: Mrs. Honeychurch

qTextArr: ["It's his third go, isn't it?"]
qText: It's his third go, isn't it?
speaker: Freddy

qTextArr: ['Freddy I do call the way you talk unkind.']
qText: Freddy I do call the way you talk unkind.
speaker: Mrs. Honeychurch

qTextArr:
["I didn't mean to be unkind.", "But I do think Lucy might
have got this off her chest in Italy. I don't know how girls manage
things, but she can't have said", "properly before, or she wouldn't
have to say it again now. Over the whole thing--I can't explain--I do
feel so uncomfortable."]
qText:
I didn't mean to be unkind. But I do think Lucy might
have got this off her chest in Italy. I don't know how girls manage
things, but she can't have said properly before, or she wouldn't
have to say it again now. Over the whole thing--I can't explain--I do
feel so uncomfortable.
speaker: Freddy

qTextArr: ['Do you indeed, dear? How interesting!']
qText: Do you indeed, dear? How interesting!
speaker: Mrs. Honeychurch

qTextArr: ['I feel--never mind.']
qText: I feel--never mind.
speaker: Freddy

qTextArr: ["Just listen to what I have written to Mrs. Vyse. I said: 'Dear Mrs.\nVyse.'"]
qText:
Just listen to what I have written to Mrs. Vyse. I said: 'Dear Mrs.
Vyse.'
speaker: Mrs. Honeychurch

qTextArr: ['Yes, mother, you told me. A jolly good letter.']
qText: Yes, mother, you told me. A jolly good letter.
speaker: Freddy

qTextArr: ['I said:']
qText: I said:
speaker: Mrs. Honeychurch

qTextArr: ["I was rather amused at Cecil asking my permission at all. He\nhas always gone in for unconventionality, and parents nowhere, and so\nforth. When it comes to the point, he can't get on without me."]
qText:
I was rather amused at Cecil asking my permission at all. He
has always gone in for unconventionality, and parents nowhere, and so
forth. When it comes to the point, he can't get on without me.
speaker: Mrs. Honeychurch

qTextArr: ['Nor me.']
qText: Nor me.
speaker: Freddy

qText: You?
speaker: Mrs. Honeychurch

qTextArr: ['What do you mean?']
qText: What do you mean?
speaker: Mrs. Honeychurch

qTextArr: ['He asked me for my permission also.']
qText: He asked me for my permission also.
speaker: Freddy

qTextArr: ['How very odd of him!']
qText: How very odd of him!
speaker: Mrs. Honeychurch

qTextArr: ['Why so?', "Why shouldn't my permission be\nasked?"]
qText:
Why so? Why shouldn't my permission be
asked?
speaker: Freddy

qTextArr: ['What do you know about Lucy or girls or anything? What ever did you\nsay?']
qText:
What do you know about Lucy or girls or anything? What ever did you
say?
speaker: Mrs. Honeychurch

qTextArr: ['I said to Cecil,']
qText: I said to Cecil,
speaker: Freddy

qTextArr: ['What a helpful answer!']
qText: What a helpful answer!
speaker: Mrs. Honeychurch

qTextArr: ['The bother is this,']
qText: The bother is this,
speaker: Freddy

qTextArr: ['Freddy, you must come. There they still are!']
qText: Freddy, you must come. There they still are!
speaker: Mrs. Honeychurch

qTextArr: ["I don't see you ought to go peeping like that."]
qText: I don't see you ought to go peeping like that.
speaker: Freddy

qTextArr: ["Peeping like that! Can't I look out of my own window?"]
qText: Peeping like that! Can't I look out of my own window?
speaker: Mrs. Honeychurch

qTextArr: ['Still page 322?']
qText: Still page 322?
speaker: Mrs. Honeychurch
refExp: she returned to the writingtable observing

qTextArr: ['The bother is this: I have put my foot in it with Cecil most awfully.']
qText: The bother is this: I have put my foot in it with Cecil most awfully.
speaker: Freddy

qTextArr: ["Not content with 'permission', which I did\ngive--that is to say, I said,"]
qText:
Not content with 'permission', which I did
give--that is to say, I said,
speaker: Freddy

qTextArr:
["--well, not content with
that, he wanted to know whether I wasn't off my head with joy. He
practically put it like this: Wasn't it a splendid thing for Lucy and
for Windy Corner generally if he married her? And he would have an
answer--he said it would strengthen his hand."]
qText:
--well, not content with
that, he wanted to know whether I wasn't off my head with joy. He
practically put it like this: Wasn't it a splendid thing for Lucy and
for Windy Corner generally if he married her? And he would have an
answer--he said it would strengthen his hand.
speaker: Freddy

qTextArr: ['I hope you gave a careful answer, dear.']
qText: I hope you gave a careful answer, dear.
speaker: Mrs. Honeychurch

qTextArr: ["I answered 'No'", "There! Fly into a\nstew! I can't help it--had to say it. I had to say no. He ought never to\nhave asked me."]
qText:
I answered 'No' There! Fly into a
stew! I can't help it--had to say it. I had to say no. He ought never to
have asked me.
speaker: Freddy

qTextArr:
['Ridiculous child!', "You think you're so holy and
truthful, but really it's only abominable conceit. Do you suppose that
a man like Cecil would take the slightest notice of anything you say? I
hope he boxed your ears. How dare you say no?"]
qText:
Ridiculous child! You think you're so holy and
truthful, but really it's only abominable conceit. Do you suppose that
a man like Cecil would take the slightest notice of anything you say? I
hope he boxed your ears. How dare you say no?
speaker: Mrs. Honeychurch

qTextArr:
["Oh, do keep quiet, mother! I had to say no when I couldn't say yes. I
tried to laugh as if I didn't mean what I said, and, as Cecil laughed
too, and went away, it may be all right. But I feel my foot's in it. Oh,
do keep quiet, though, and let a man do some work."]
qText:
Oh, do keep quiet, mother! I had to say no when I couldn't say yes. I
tried to laugh as if I didn't mean what I said, and, as Cecil laughed
too, and went away, it may be all right. But I feel my foot's in it. Oh,
do keep quiet, though, and let a man do some work.
speaker: Freddy

qTextArr: ['No,', 'I shall not keep quiet. You know all that has passed between\nthem in Rome; you know why he is down here, and yet you deliberately\ninsult him, and try to turn him out of my house.']
qText:
No, I shall not keep quiet. You know all that has passed between
them in Rome; you know why he is down here, and yet you deliberately
insult him, and try to turn him out of my house.
speaker: Mrs. Honeychurch

qTextArr: ['Not a bit!', "I only let out I didn't like him. I don't hate\nhim, but I don't like him. What I mind is that he'll tell Lucy."]
qText:
Not a bit! I only let out I didn't like him. I don't hate
him, but I don't like him. What I mind is that he'll tell Lucy.
speaker: Freddy

qTextArr:
['Well, I like him,', "I know his mother; he's
good, he's clever, he's rich, he's well connected--Oh, you needn't kick
the piano! He's well connected--I'll say it again if you like: he's
well connected."]
qText:
Well, I like him, I know his mother; he's
good, he's clever, he's rich, he's well connected--Oh, you needn't kick
the piano! He's well connected--I'll say it again if you like: he's
well connected.
speaker: Mrs. Honeychurch

qTextArr: ['And he has beautiful manners.']
qText: And he has beautiful manners.
speaker: Mrs. Honeychurch

qTextArr: ["I liked him till just now. I suppose it's having him spoiling Lucy's\nfirst week at home; and it's also something that Mr. Beebe said, not\nknowing."]
qText:
I liked him till just now. I suppose it's having him spoiling Lucy's
first week at home; and it's also something that Mr. Beebe said, not
knowing.
speaker: Freddy

qTextArr: ['Mr. Beebe?', "I don't\nsee how Mr. Beebe comes in."]
qText:
Mr. Beebe? I don't
see how Mr. Beebe comes in.
speaker: Mrs. Honeychurch

qTextArr: ["You know Mr. Beebe's funny way, when you never quite know what he\nmeans. He said:"]
qText:
You know Mr. Beebe's funny way, when you never quite know what he
means. He said:
speaker: Freddy

qTextArr: ['I was very cute, I\nasked him what he meant. He said']
qText:
I was very cute, I
asked him what he meant. He said
speaker: Freddy

qTextArr: ["I\ncouldn't make him say any more, but it set me thinking. Since Cecil has\ncome after Lucy he hasn't been so pleasant, at least--I can't explain."]
qText:
I
couldn't make him say any more, but it set me thinking. Since Cecil has
come after Lucy he hasn't been so pleasant, at least--I can't explain.
speaker: Freddy

qTextArr: ['You never can, dear. But I can. You are jealous of Cecil because he may\nstop Lucy knitting you silk ties.']
qText:
You never can, dear. But I can. You are jealous of Cecil because he may
stop Lucy knitting you silk ties.
speaker: Mrs. Honeychurch

qTextArr:
['Will this do?', 'Then I put in at the top,', 'I must write
the letter out again--', "I
said that because I didn't want Mrs. Vyse to think us old-fashioned. She
goes in for lectures and improving her mind, and all the time a thick
layer of flue under the beds, and the maid's dirty thumb-marks where you
turn on the electric light. She keeps that flat abominably--"]
qText:
Will this do? Then I put in at the top, I must write
the letter out again-- I
said that because I didn't want Mrs. Vyse to think us old-fashioned. She
goes in for lectures and improving her mind, and all the time a thick
layer of flue under the beds, and the maid's dirty thumb-marks where you
turn on the electric light. She keeps that flat abominably--
speaker: Mrs. Honeychurch

qTextArr: ['Suppose Lucy marries Cecil, would she live in a flat, or in the\ncountry?']
qText:
Suppose Lucy marries Cecil, would she live in a flat, or in the
country?
speaker: Freddy

qTextArr: ["Don't interrupt so foolishly. Where was I? Oh yes--"]
qText: Don't interrupt so foolishly. Where was I? Oh yes--
speaker: Mrs. Honeychurch

qTextArr: ["No, I'll cross that last bit out--it looks patronizing. I'll\nstop at"]
qText:
No, I'll cross that last bit out--it looks patronizing. I'll
stop at
speaker: Mrs. Honeychurch

qTextArr: ['Or shall I cross that out,\ntoo?']
qText:
Or shall I cross that out,
too?
speaker: Mrs. Honeychurch

qTextArr: ['Cross it out, too,']
qText: Cross it out, too,
speaker: Freddy

qTextArr: ['Then the whole thing runs:']
qText: Then the whole thing runs:
speaker: Mrs. Honeychurch

qTextArr: ['Look out!']
qText: Look out!
speaker: Freddy

qTextArr: ['Oh, Cecil!', 'oh, Cecil, do tell me!']
qText: Oh, Cecil! oh, Cecil, do tell me!
speaker: Mrs. Honeychurch

qTextArr: ['I promessi sposi,']
qText: I promessi sposi,
speaker: Cecil

qTextArr: ['She has accepted me,']
qText: She has accepted me,
speaker: Cecil

qTextArr: ['I am so glad,', 'Welcome as one of the family!', 'This is indeed a joyous day! I feel sure that you\nwill make our dear Lucy happy.']
qText:
I am so glad, Welcome as one of the family! This is indeed a joyous day! I feel sure that you
will make our dear Lucy happy.
speaker: Mrs. Honeychurch

qTextArr: ['I hope so,']
qText: I hope so,
speaker: Cecil

qTextArr: ['We mothers--']
qText: We mothers--
speaker: Mrs. Honeychurch

qTextArr: ['I say, Lucy!']
qText: I say, Lucy!
speaker: Cecil

qTextArr: ['Steady on!']
qText: Steady on!
speaker: Freddy

qTextArr: ['Not a kiss for me?']
qText: Not a kiss for me?
speaker: Mrs. Honeychurch

qTextArr: ['Would you take them into the garden and tell Mrs. Honeychurch all about\nit?', "And I'd stop here and tell my mother."]
qText:
Would you take them into the garden and tell Mrs. Honeychurch all about
it? And I'd stop here and tell my mother.
speaker: Cecil

qTextArr: ['We go with Lucy?']
qText: We go with Lucy?
speaker: Freddy

qTextArr: ['Yes, you go with Lucy.']
qText: Yes, you go with Lucy.
speaker: Cecil

qTextArr: ['He is only a boy,', 'I represent all\nthat he despises. Why should he want me for a brother-in-law?']
qText:
He is only a boy, I represent all
that he despises. Why should he want me for a brother-in-law?
speaker: Cecil

qTextArr: ['Mr. Beebe!']
qText: Mr. Beebe!
speaker: The Maid

qTextArr: ["I've come for tea, Mr. Vyse. Do you suppose that I shall get it?"]
qText: I've come for tea, Mr. Vyse. Do you suppose that I shall get it?
speaker: Mr. Beebe

qTextArr: ["I should say so. Food is the thing one does get here--Don't sit in that\nchair; young Honeychurch has left a bone in it."]
qText:
I should say so. Food is the thing one does get here--Don't sit in that
chair; young Honeychurch has left a bone in it.
speaker: Cecil

qTextArr: ['Pfui!']
qText: Pfui!
speaker: Mr. Beebe

qTextArr: ['I know,', "I know. I can't think why Mrs. Honeychurch allows\nit."]
qText:
I know, I know. I can't think why Mrs. Honeychurch allows
it.
speaker: Cecil

qTextArr: ["I've come for tea and for gossip. Isn't this news?"]
qText: I've come for tea and for gossip. Isn't this news?
speaker: Mr. Beebe

qTextArr: ["News? I don't understand you,", 'News?']
qText: News? I don't understand you, News?
speaker: Cecil

qTextArr: ['I met Sir Harry Otway as I came up; I have every reason to hope that I\nam first in the field. He has bought Cissie and Albert from Mr. Flack!']
qText:
I met Sir Harry Otway as I came up; I have every reason to hope that I
am first in the field. He has bought Cissie and Albert from Mr. Flack!
speaker: Mr. Beebe

qTextArr: ['Has he indeed?']
qText: Has he indeed?
speaker: Cecil

qTextArr: ["Unpardonable question! To have stopped a week at Windy Corner and not\nto have met Cissie and Albert, the semi-detached villas that have been\nrun up opposite the church! I'll set Mrs. Honeychurch after you."]
qText:
Unpardonable question! To have stopped a week at Windy Corner and not
to have met Cissie and Albert, the semi-detached villas that have been
run up opposite the church! I'll set Mrs. Honeychurch after you.
speaker: Mr. Beebe

qTextArr:
["I'm shockingly stupid over local affairs,", "I can't even remember the difference between a Parish
Council and a Local Government Board. Perhaps there is no difference, or
perhaps those aren't the right names. I only go into the country to see
my friends and to enjoy the scenery. It is very remiss of me. Italy and
London are the only places where I don't feel to exist on sufferance."]
qText:
I'm shockingly stupid over local affairs, I can't even remember the difference between a Parish
Council and a Local Government Board. Perhaps there is no difference, or
perhaps those aren't the right names. I only go into the country to see
my friends and to enjoy the scenery. It is very remiss of me. Italy and
London are the only places where I don't feel to exist on sufferance.
speaker: Cecil

qTextArr: ['Let me see, Mr. Vyse--I forget--what is your profession?']
qText: Let me see, Mr. Vyse--I forget--what is your profession?
speaker: Mr. Beebe

qTextArr:
['I have no profession,', "It is another example of my
decadence. My attitude--quite an indefensible one--is that so long as I
am no trouble to any one I have a right to do as I like. I know I ought
to be getting money out of people, or devoting myself to things I don't
care a straw about, but somehow, I've not been able to begin."]
qText:
I have no profession, It is another example of my
decadence. My attitude--quite an indefensible one--is that so long as I
am no trouble to any one I have a right to do as I like. I know I ought
to be getting money out of people, or devoting myself to things I don't
care a straw about, but somehow, I've not been able to begin.
speaker: Cecil

qTextArr: ['You are very fortunate,', 'It is a wonderful\nopportunity, the possession of leisure.']
qText:
You are very fortunate, It is a wonderful
opportunity, the possession of leisure.
speaker: Mr. Beebe

qTextArr: ["I am glad that you approve. I daren't face the healthy person--for\nexample, Freddy Honeychurch."]
qText:
I am glad that you approve. I daren't face the healthy person--for
example, Freddy Honeychurch.
speaker: Cecil

qTextArr: ["Oh, Freddy's a good sort, isn't he?"]
qText: Oh, Freddy's a good sort, isn't he?
speaker: Mr. Beebe

qTextArr: ['Admirable. The sort who has made England what she is.']
qText: Admirable. The sort who has made England what she is.
speaker: Cecil

qTextArr: ['Where are the others?', 'I insist on extracting\ntea before evening service.']
qText:
Where are the others? I insist on extracting
tea before evening service.
speaker: Mr. Beebe

qTextArr:
['I suppose Anne never told them you were here. In this house one is so
coached in the servants the day one arrives. The fault of Anne is
that she begs your pardon when she hears you perfectly, and kicks the
chair-legs with her feet. The faults of Mary--I forget the faults of
Mary, but they are very grave. Shall we look in the garden?']
qText:
I suppose Anne never told them you were here. In this house one is so
coached in the servants the day one arrives. The fault of Anne is
that she begs your pardon when she hears you perfectly, and kicks the
chair-legs with her feet. The faults of Mary--I forget the faults of
Mary, but they are very grave. Shall we look in the garden?
speaker: Cecil

qTextArr: ['I know the faults of Mary. She leaves the dust-pans standing on the\nstairs.']
qText:
I know the faults of Mary. She leaves the dust-pans standing on the
stairs.
speaker: Mr. Beebe

qTextArr: ['The fault of Euphemia is that she will not, simply will not, chop the\nsuet sufficiently small.']
qText:
The fault of Euphemia is that she will not, simply will not, chop the
suet sufficiently small.
speaker: Cecil

qTextArr: ['The faults of Freddy--']
qText: The faults of Freddy--
speaker: Cecil

qTextArr: ['Ah, he has too many. No one but his mother can remember the faults of\nFreddy. Try the faults of Miss Honeychurch; they are not innumerable.']
qText:
Ah, he has too many. No one but his mother can remember the faults of
Freddy. Try the faults of Miss Honeychurch; they are not innumerable.
speaker: Mr. Beebe

qTextArr: ['She has none,']
qText: She has none,
speaker: Cecil

qTextArr: ['I quite agree. At present she has none.']
qText: I quite agree. At present she has none.
speaker: Mr. Beebe

qTextArr: ['At present?']
qText: At present?
speaker: Cecil

qTextArr:
["I'm not cynical. I'm only thinking of my pet theory about Miss
Honeychurch. Does it seem reasonable that she should play so
wonderfully, and live so quietly? I suspect that one day she will be
wonderful in both. The water-tight compartments in her will break down,
and music and life will mingle. Then we shall have her heroically good,
heroically bad--too heroic, perhaps, to be good or bad."]
qText:
I'm not cynical. I'm only thinking of my pet theory about Miss
Honeychurch. Does it seem reasonable that she should play so
wonderfully, and live so quietly? I suspect that one day she will be
wonderful in both. The water-tight compartments in her will break down,
and music and life will mingle. Then we shall have her heroically good,
heroically bad--too heroic, perhaps, to be good or bad.
speaker: Mr. Beebe

qTextArr: ['And at present you think her not wonderful as far as life goes?']
qText: And at present you think her not wonderful as far as life goes?
speaker: Cecil

qTextArr:
["Well, I must say I've only seen her at Tunbridge Wells, where she was
not wonderful, and at Florence. Since I came to Summer Street she has
been away. You saw her, didn't you, at Rome and in the Alps. Oh, I
forgot; of course, you knew her before. No, she wasn't wonderful in
Florence either, but I kept on expecting that she would be."]
qText:
Well, I must say I've only seen her at Tunbridge Wells, where she was
not wonderful, and at Florence. Since I came to Summer Street she has
been away. You saw her, didn't you, at Rome and in the Alps. Oh, I
forgot; of course, you knew her before. No, she wasn't wonderful in
Florence either, but I kept on expecting that she would be.
speaker: Mr. Beebe

qTextArr: ['In what way?']
qText: In what way?
speaker: Cecil

qTextArr:
["I could as easily tell you what tune she'll play next. There was simply
the sense that she had found wings, and meant to use them. I can show
you a beautiful picture in my Italian diary: Miss Honeychurch as a
kite, Miss Bartlett holding the string. Picture number two: the string
breaks."]
qText:
I could as easily tell you what tune she'll play next. There was simply
the sense that she had found wings, and meant to use them. I can show
you a beautiful picture in my Italian diary: Miss Honeychurch as a
kite, Miss Bartlett holding the string. Picture number two: the string
breaks.
speaker: Mr. Beebe

qTextArr: ['But the string never broke?']
qText: But the string never broke?
speaker: Cecil

qTextArr: ["No. I mightn't have seen Miss Honeychurch rise, but I should certainly\nhave heard Miss Bartlett fall."]
qText:
No. I mightn't have seen Miss Honeychurch rise, but I should certainly
have heard Miss Bartlett fall.
speaker: Mr. Beebe

qTextArr: ['It has broken now,']
qText: It has broken now,
speaker: Cecil

qTextArr: ['Broken? What do you mean?']
qText: Broken? What do you mean?
speaker: Mr. Beebe

qTextArr: ['I meant,', 'that she is going to marry me.']
qText: I meant, that she is going to marry me.
speaker: Cecil

qTextArr: ['I am sorry; I must apologize. I had no idea you were intimate with her,\nor I should never have talked in this flippant, superficial way. Mr.\nVyse, you ought to have stopped me.']
qText:
I am sorry; I must apologize. I had no idea you were intimate with her,
or I should never have talked in this flippant, superficial way. Mr.
Vyse, you ought to have stopped me.
speaker: Mr. Beebe

qTextArr: ['I am sorry I have given you a shock,', "I fear that\nLucy's choice does not meet with your approval."]
qText:
I am sorry I have given you a shock, I fear that
Lucy's choice does not meet with your approval.

qTextArr:
['I count myself a lucky person,', "When I'm in London I
feel I could never live out of it. When I'm in the country I feel the
same about the country. After all, I do believe that birds and trees and
the sky are the most wonderful things in life, and that the people who
live amongst them must be the best. It's true that in nine cases out of
ten they don't seem to notice anything. The country gentleman and
the country labourer are each in their way the most depressing of
companions. Yet they may have a tacit sympathy with the workings
of Nature which is denied to us of the town. Do you feel that, Mrs.
Honeychurch?"]

['Indeed you may!', "Here we are with the difficulty solved

position to me, replied that she would pay the rent in advance. As
if one cares about that! And several references I took up were most
unsatisfactory--people swindlers, or not respectable. And oh, the

deceit of the most promising people. My dear Lucy, the deceit!"]

["I can't remember why. I suppose it comes out of some book. It's only a
puddle now, but you see that stream going through it? Well, a good deal
of water comes down after heavy rains, and can't get away at once, and
the pool becomes quite large and beautiful. Then Freddy used to bathe

qText:
I can't remember why. I suppose it comes out of some book. It's only a
puddle now, but you see that stream going through it? Well, a good deal
of water comes down after heavy rains, and can't get away at once, and
the pool becomes quite large and beautiful. Then Freddy used to bathe
there. He is very fond of it.
speaker: Lucy

qText: And you?

Oh, it has been such a nuisance--first he, then they--no one knowing

speaker: Lucy

qTextArr:
['But they really are coming now,', 'I wrote to Miss
Teresa a few days ago--she was wondering how often the butcher called,

are coming. I heard from them this morning.']
qText:
But they really are coming now, I wrote to Miss
Teresa a few days ago--she was wondering how often the butcher called,
and my reply of once a month must have impressed her favourably. They
are coming. I heard from them this morning.

qTextArr:
['I shall hate those Miss Alans!', "Just because
they're old and silly one's expected to say 'How sweet!' I hate

right--worn to a shadow."]
qText:
I shall hate those Miss Alans! Just because
they're old and silly one's expected to say 'How sweet!' I hate
their 'if'-ing and 'but'-ing and 'and'-ing. And poor Lucy--serve her
right--worn to a shadow.
speaker: Mrs. Honeychurch

fair wear and tear one.--That doesn't count. I told you not Saturn."]
qText:
If they are coming, Sir Harry will let them move

whitewashing the ceilings, because it made them nervous, and put in the

But look at Lucy--complaining of Saturn, and all the time's got the

qText:
Oh, good gracious, there isn't going to be another muddle! Do you notice, Lucy, I'm always right? I said
don't interfere with Cissie Villa. I'm always right. I'm quite uneasy at

qText: Emerson. I'll bet you anything you like.

qText:
What a weathercock Sir Harry is, I wish I had

qText:
The Emersons who were at Florence, do you mean? No, I don't suppose it

These particular Emersons consisted of a father and a son--the son

Murdered his wife? Lucy, don't desert us--go
on playing bumble-puppy. Really, the Pension Bertolini must have been

qTextArr:
['Hullo!', "I was hoping you'd come. I heard you all
bear-gardening, but there's better fun up here. I, even I, have won a
great victory for the Comic Muse. George Meredith's right--the cause of
Comedy and the cause of Truth are really the same; and I, even I, have
found tenants for the distressful Cissie Villa. Don't be angry! Don't be
angry! You'll forgive me when you hear it all."]
qText:
Hullo! I was hoping you'd come. I heard you all
bear-gardening, but there's better fun up here. I, even I, have won a
great victory for the Comic Muse. George Meredith's right--the cause of
Comedy and the cause of Truth are really the same; and I, even I, have
found tenants for the distressful Cissie Villa. Don't be angry! Don't be
angry! You'll forgive me when you hear it all.
speaker: Cecil

qTextArr:
['I have heard,', "Freddy has told us. Naughty Cecil! I suppose
I must forgive you. Just think of all the trouble I took for nothing!
Certainly the Miss Alans are a little tiresome, and I'd rather have nice
friends of yours. But you oughtn't to tease one so."]
qText:
I have heard, Freddy has told us. Naughty Cecil! I suppose
I must forgive you. Just think of all the trouble I took for nothing!
Certainly the Miss Alans are a little tiresome, and I'd rather have nice
friends of yours. But you oughtn't to tease one so.
speaker: Lucy

qTextArr:
['Friends of mine?', 'But, Lucy, the whole joke is to come!
Come here.', 'Do you know where
I met these desirable tenants? In the National Gallery, when I was up to
see my mother last week.']
qText:
Friends of mine? But, Lucy, the whole joke is to come!
Come here. Do you know where
I met these desirable tenants? In the National Gallery, when I was up to
see my mother last week.
speaker: Cecil

qTextArr: ['What an odd place to meet people!', "I don't quite\nunderstand."]
qText:
What an odd place to meet people! I don't quite
understand.
speaker: Lucy

qTextArr: ['In the Umbrian Room. Absolute strangers. They were admiring Luca\nSignorelli--of course, quite stupidly. However, we got talking, and they\nrefreshed me not a little. They had been to Italy.']
qText:
In the Umbrian Room. Absolute strangers. They were admiring Luca
Signorelli--of course, quite stupidly. However, we got talking, and they
refreshed me not a little. They had been to Italy.
speaker: Cecil

qTextArr:
["In the course of conversation they said that they wanted a country
cottage--the father to live there, the son to run down for week-ends.
I thought, 'What a chance of scoring off Sir Harry!' and I took
their address and a London reference, found they weren't actual
blackguards--it was great sport--and wrote to him, making out--"]
qText:
In the course of conversation they said that they wanted a country
cottage--the father to live there, the son to run down for week-ends.
I thought, 'What a chance of scoring off Sir Harry!' and I took
their address and a London reference, found they weren't actual
blackguards--it was great sport--and wrote to him, making out--
speaker: Cecil

qTextArr: ["Cecil! No, it's not fair. I've probably met them before--"]
qText: Cecil! No, it's not fair. I've probably met them before--
speaker: Lucy

qTextArr:
["Perfectly fair. Anything is fair that punishes a snob. That old man
will do the neighbourhood a world of good. Sir Harry is too disgusting
with his 'decayed gentlewomen.' I meant to read him a lesson some time.
No, Lucy, the classes ought to mix, and before long you'll agree with
me. There ought to be intermarriage--all sorts of things. I believe in
democracy--"]
qText:
Perfectly fair. Anything is fair that punishes a snob. That old man
will do the neighbourhood a world of good. Sir Harry is too disgusting
with his 'decayed gentlewomen.' I meant to read him a lesson some time.
No, Lucy, the classes ought to mix, and before long you'll agree with
me. There ought to be intermarriage--all sorts of things. I believe in
democracy--
speaker: Cecil

["It isn't fair, Cecil. I blame you--I blame you very much indeed. You
had no business to undo my work about the Miss Alans, and make me look
ridiculous. You call it scoring off Sir Harry, but do you realize that
it is all at my expense? I consider it most disloyal of you."]

It isn't fair, Cecil. I blame you--I blame you very much indeed. You
had no business to undo my work about the Miss Alans, and make me look
ridiculous. You call it scoring off Sir Harry, but do you realize that
it is all at my expense? I consider it most disloyal of you.

qTextArr:
['But her music!', "The style of her! How she kept to
Schumann when, like an idiot, I wanted Beethoven. Schumann was right for
this evening. Schumann was the thing. Do you know, mother, I shall have
our children educated just like Lucy. Bring them up among honest country
folks for freshness, send them to Italy for subtlety, and then--not
till then--let them come to London. I don't believe in these London
educations--"]
qText:
But her music! The style of her! How she kept to
Schumann when, like an idiot, I wanted Beethoven. Schumann was right for
this evening. Schumann was the thing. Do you know, mother, I shall have
our children educated just like Lucy. Bring them up among honest country
folks for freshness, send them to Italy for subtlety, and then--not
till then--let them come to London. I don't believe in these London
educations--
speaker: Cecil
