Are these people great readers? Are they that
sort?
speaker: Freddy

qTextArr:
['I fancy they know how to read--a rare accomplishment. What have they
got? Byron. Exactly. A Shropshire Lad. Never heard of it. The Way of
All Flesh. Never heard of it. Gibbon. Hullo! dear George reads German.
Um--um--Schopenhauer, Nietzsche, and so we go on. Well, I suppose your
generation knows its own business, Honeychurch.']
qText:
I fancy they know how to read--a rare accomplishment. What have they
got? Byron. Exactly. A Shropshire Lad. Never heard of it. The Way of
All Flesh. Never heard of it. Gibbon. Hullo! dear George reads German.
Um--um--Schopenhauer, Nietzsche, and so we go on. Well, I suppose your
generation knows its own business, Honeychurch.
speaker: Mr. Beebe
menEnts: [[['Mr. Emerson', 'George Emerson'], ['George Emerson', 'Mr. Emerson'], ['George Emerson'], ['Freddy', 'Mr. Beebe'], ['Freddy'], ['Freddy']]]

qTextArr: ['Mr. Beebe, look at that,']
qText: Mr. Beebe, look at that,
speaker: Freddy

qTextArr: ["I know. Isn't it jolly? I like that. I'm certain that's the old man's\ndoing."]
qText:
I know. Isn't it jolly? I like that. I'm certain that's the old man's
doing.
speaker: Mr. Beebe

qTextArr: ['How very odd of him!']
qText: How very odd of him!
speaker: Freddy

qTextArr: ['Surely you agree?']
qText: Surely you agree?
speaker: Mr. Beebe

qTextArr: ['Pictures!', "Giotto--they got that at Florence, I'll be bound."]
qText: Pictures! Giotto--they got that at Florence, I'll be bound.
speaker: Mr. Beebe

qTextArr: ["The same as Lucy's got."]
qText: The same as Lucy's got.
speaker: Freddy

qTextArr: ['Oh, by-the-by, did Miss Honeychurch enjoy London?']
qText: Oh, by-the-by, did Miss Honeychurch enjoy London?
speaker: Mr. Beebe

qTextArr: ['She came back yesterday.']
qText: She came back yesterday.
speaker: Freddy

qTextArr: ['I suppose she had a good time?']
qText: I suppose she had a good time?
speaker: Mr. Beebe

qTextArr: ['Yes, very,', 'She and Cecil are thicker\nthan ever.']
qText:
Yes, very, She and Cecil are thicker
than ever.
speaker: Freddy

qTextArr: ["That's good hearing."]
qText: That's good hearing.
speaker: Mr. Beebe

qTextArr: ["I wish I wasn't such a fool, Mr. Beebe."]
qText: I wish I wasn't such a fool, Mr. Beebe.
speaker: Freddy

qTextArr: ["Lucy used to be nearly as stupid as I am, but it'll be very different\nnow, mother thinks. She will read all kinds of books."]
qText:
Lucy used to be nearly as stupid as I am, but it'll be very different
now, mother thinks. She will read all kinds of books.
speaker: Freddy

qTextArr: ['So will you.']
qText: So will you.
speaker: Mr. Beebe

qTextArr: ['Only medical books. Not books that you can talk about afterwards. Cecil\nis teaching Lucy Italian, and he says her playing is wonderful. There\nare all kinds of things in it that we have never noticed. Cecil says--']
qText:
Only medical books. Not books that you can talk about afterwards. Cecil
is teaching Lucy Italian, and he says her playing is wonderful. There
are all kinds of things in it that we have never noticed. Cecil says--
speaker: Freddy

qTextArr: ["What on earth are those people doing upstairs? Emerson--we think we'll\ncome another time."]
qText:
What on earth are those people doing upstairs? Emerson--we think we'll
come another time.
speaker: Mr. Beebe

qTextArr: ['Let me introduce Mr. Honeychurch, a neighbour.']
qText: Let me introduce Mr. Honeychurch, a neighbour.
speaker: Mr. Beebe

qTextArr: ["How d'ye do? Come and have\na bathe."]
qText:
How d'ye do? Come and have
a bathe.
speaker: Freddy

qTextArr: ['Oh, all right,']
qText: Oh, all right,
speaker: George Emerson

qTextArr:
["That's the best conversational opening I've ever heard. But I'm afraid
it will only act between men. Can you picture a lady who has been
introduced to another lady by a third lady opening civilities with 'How
do you do? Come and have a bathe'? And yet you will tell me that the
sexes are equal."]
qText:
That's the best conversational opening I've ever heard. But I'm afraid
it will only act between men. Can you picture a lady who has been
introduced to another lady by a third lady opening civilities with 'How
do you do? Come and have a bathe'? And yet you will tell me that the
sexes are equal.
speaker: Mr. Beebe

qTextArr: ['I tell you that they shall be,', 'Good afternoon, Mr. Beebe. I tell you they shall\nbe comrades, and George thinks the same.']
qText:
I tell you that they shall be, Good afternoon, Mr. Beebe. I tell you they shall
be comrades, and George thinks the same.
speaker: Mr. Emerson

qTextArr: ['We are to raise ladies to our level?']
qText: We are to raise ladies to our level?
speaker: Mr. Beebe

qTextArr: ['The Garden of Eden,', 'which you\nplace in the past, is really yet to come. We shall enter it when we no\nlonger despise our bodies.']
qText:
The Garden of Eden, which you
place in the past, is really yet to come. We shall enter it when we no
longer despise our bodies.
speaker: Mr. Emerson

qTextArr: ['In this--not in other things--we men are ahead. We despise the body\nless than women do. But not until we are comrades shall we enter the\ngarden.']
qText:
In this--not in other things--we men are ahead. We despise the body
less than women do. But not until we are comrades shall we enter the
garden.
speaker: Mr. Emerson

qTextArr: ['I say, what about this bathe?']
qText: I say, what about this bathe?
speaker: Freddy

qTextArr:
['I believed in a return to Nature once. But how can we return to
Nature when we have never been with her? To-day, I believe that we must
discover Nature. After many conquests we shall attain simplicity. It is
our heritage.']
qText:
I believed in a return to Nature once. But how can we return to
Nature when we have never been with her? To-day, I believe that we must
discover Nature. After many conquests we shall attain simplicity. It is
our heritage.
speaker: Mr. Emerson

qTextArr: ['Let me introduce Mr. Honeychurch, whose sister you will remember at\nFlorence.']
qText:
Let me introduce Mr. Honeychurch, whose sister you will remember at
Florence.
speaker: Mr. Beebe

qTextArr:
['How do you do? Very glad to see you, and that you are taking George for
a bathe. Very glad to hear that your sister is going to marry. Marriage
is a duty. I am sure that she will be happy, for we know Mr. Vyse, too.
He has been most kind. He met us by chance in the National Gallery, and
arranged everything about this delightful house. Though I hope I have
not vexed Sir Harry Otway. I have met so few Liberal landowners, and
I was anxious to compare his attitude towards the game laws with the
Conservative attitude. Ah, this wind! You do well to bathe. Yours is a
glorious country, Honeychurch!']
qText:
How do you do? Very glad to see you, and that you are taking George for
a bathe. Very glad to hear that your sister is going to marry. Marriage
is a duty. I am sure that she will be happy, for we know Mr. Vyse, too.
He has been most kind. He met us by chance in the National Gallery, and
arranged everything about this delightful house. Though I hope I have
not vexed Sir Harry Otway. I have met so few Liberal landowners, and
I was anxious to compare his attitude towards the game laws with the
Conservative attitude. Ah, this wind! You do well to bathe. Yours is a
glorious country, Honeychurch!
speaker: Mr. Emerson
menEnts: [[['Freddy'], ['Freddy'], ['Freddy'], ['George Emerson'], ['Lucy'], ['Lucy'], ['Mr. Emerson', 'George Emerson'], ['Cecil'], ['Cecil'], ['George Emerson', 'Mr. Emerson'], ['Sir Harry Otway'], ['Freddy'], ['Freddy'], ['Freddy']]]

qTextArr: ['Not a bit!', 'I must--that is to say, I have to--have\nthe pleasure of calling on you later on, my mother says, I hope.']
qText:
Not a bit! I must--that is to say, I have to--have
the pleasure of calling on you later on, my mother says, I hope.
speaker: Freddy

qTextArr: ['CALL, my lad? Who taught us that drawing-room twaddle? Call on your\ngrandmother! Listen to the wind among the pines! Yours is a glorious\ncountry.']
qText:
CALL, my lad? Who taught us that drawing-room twaddle? Call on your
grandmother! Listen to the wind among the pines! Yours is a glorious
country.
speaker: Mr. Emerson

qTextArr:
["Mr. Emerson, he will call, I shall call; you or your son will return
our calls before ten days have elapsed. I trust that you have realized
about the ten days' interval. It does not count that I helped you with
the stair-eyes yesterday. It does not count that they are going to bathe
this afternoon."]
qText:
Mr. Emerson, he will call, I shall call; you or your son will return
our calls before ten days have elapsed. I trust that you have realized
about the ten days' interval. It does not count that I helped you with
the stair-eyes yesterday. It does not count that they are going to bathe
this afternoon.
speaker: Mr. Beebe
menEnts: [[['Mr. Emerson'], ['Freddy'], ['Mr. Emerson'], ['George Emerson'], ['Mr. Emerson'], ['Mr. Emerson', 'George Emerson'], ['Freddy', 'George Emerson']]]

qTextArr:
["Yes, go and bathe, George. Why do you dawdle talking? Bring them back
to tea. Bring back some milk, cakes, honey. The change will do you good.
George has been working very hard at his office. I can't believe he's
well."]
qText:
Yes, go and bathe, George. Why do you dawdle talking? Bring them back
to tea. Bring back some milk, cakes, honey. The change will do you good.
George has been working very hard at his office. I can't believe he's
well.
speaker: Mr. Emerson
menEnts: [[['George Emerson'], ['George Emerson'], ['Freddy', 'Mr. Beebe'], ['George Emerson'], ['George Emerson'], ['George Emerson'], ['George Emerson'], ['George Emerson']]]

qTextArr: ['Do you really want this bathe?', "It is only a pond,\ndon't you know. I dare say you are used to something better."]
qText:
Do you really want this bathe? It is only a pond,
don't you know. I dare say you are used to something better.
speaker: Freddy

qTextArr: ['And what a coincidence that you should meet Mr. Vyse! Did you realize\nthat you would find all the Pension Bertolini down here?']
qText:
And what a coincidence that you should meet Mr. Vyse! Did you realize
that you would find all the Pension Bertolini down here?
speaker: Mr. Beebe

qTextArr: ['I did not. Miss Lavish told me.']
qText: I did not. Miss Lavish told me.
speaker: George Emerson

qTextArr: ["When I was a young man, I always meant to write a 'History of\nCoincidence.'"]
qText:
When I was a young man, I always meant to write a 'History of
Coincidence.'
speaker: Mr. Beebe

qTextArr: ["Though, as a matter of fact, coincidences are much rarer than we\nsuppose. For example, it isn't purely coincidentally that you are here\nnow, when one comes to reflect."]
qText:
Though, as a matter of fact, coincidences are much rarer than we
suppose. For example, it isn't purely coincidentally that you are here
now, when one comes to reflect.
speaker: Mr. Beebe

qTextArr: ['It is. I have reflected. It is Fate. Everything is Fate. We are flung\ntogether by Fate, drawn apart by Fate--flung together, drawn apart. The\ntwelve winds blow us--we settle nothing--']
qText:
It is. I have reflected. It is Fate. Everything is Fate. We are flung
together by Fate, drawn apart by Fate--flung together, drawn apart. The
twelve winds blow us--we settle nothing--
speaker: George Emerson

qTextArr: ['You have not reflected at all,']
qText: You have not reflected at all,
speaker: Mr. Beebe

qTextArr: ['Italy.']
qText: Italy.
speaker: George Emerson

qTextArr: ['And where did you meet Mr. Vyse, who is going to marry Miss\nHoneychurch?']
qText:
And where did you meet Mr. Vyse, who is going to marry Miss
Honeychurch?
speaker: Mr. Beebe

qTextArr: ['National Gallery.']
qText: National Gallery.
speaker: George Emerson

qTextArr: ['Looking at Italian art. There you are, and yet you talk of coincidence\nand Fate. You naturally seek out things Italian, and so do we and our\nfriends. This narrows the field immeasurably we meet again in it.']
qText:
Looking at Italian art. There you are, and yet you talk of coincidence
and Fate. You naturally seek out things Italian, and so do we and our
friends. This narrows the field immeasurably we meet again in it.
speaker: Mr. Beebe
menEnts: [[['George Emerson'], ['George Emerson'], ['George Emerson'], ['Freddy', 'Mr. Beebe', 'George Emerson'], ['Freddy', 'Mr. Beebe', 'George Emerson']]]

qTextArr: ['It is Fate that I am here,', 'But you can call it\nItaly if it makes you less unhappy.']
qText:
It is Fate that I am here, But you can call it
Italy if it makes you less unhappy.
speaker: George Emerson

qTextArr: ["And so for this and for other reasons my 'History of Coincidence' is\nstill to write."]
qText:
And so for this and for other reasons my 'History of Coincidence' is
still to write.
speaker: Mr. Beebe

qTextArr: ['We are all so glad that you\nhave come.']
qText:
We are all so glad that you
have come.
speaker: Mr. Beebe

qTextArr: ['Here we are!']
qText: Here we are!
speaker: Freddy

qTextArr: ['Oh, good!']
qText: Oh, good!
speaker: Mr. Beebe

qTextArr: ["In there's the pond. I wish it was bigger,"]
qText: In there's the pond. I wish it was bigger,
speaker: Freddy

qTextArr: ["It's distinctly successful, as ponds go,", 'No apologies\nare necessary for the pond.']
qText:
It's distinctly successful, as ponds go, No apologies
are necessary for the pond.
speaker: Mr. Beebe

qTextArr: ["Aren't those masses of willow-herb splendid? I love willow-herb in\nseed. What's the name of this aromatic plant?"]
qText:
Aren't those masses of willow-herb splendid? I love willow-herb in
seed. What's the name of this aromatic plant?
speaker: Mr. Beebe

qTextArr: ['These abrupt changes of vegetation--this little spongeous tract of\nwater plants, and on either side of it all the growths are tough or\nbrittle--heather, bracken, hurts, pines. Very charming, very charming.']
qText:
These abrupt changes of vegetation--this little spongeous tract of
water plants, and on either side of it all the growths are tough or
brittle--heather, bracken, hurts, pines. Very charming, very charming.
speaker: Mr. Beebe

qTextArr: ["Mr. Beebe, aren't you bathing?"]
qText: Mr. Beebe, aren't you bathing?
speaker: Freddy

qTextArr: ["Water's wonderful!"]
qText: Water's wonderful!
speaker: Freddy

qTextArr: ["Water's water,"]
qText: Water's water,
speaker: George Emerson

qTextArr: ['Apooshoo, apooshoo, apooshoo,']
qText: Apooshoo, apooshoo, apooshoo,
speaker: Freddy

qTextArr: ['Is it worth it?']
qText: Is it worth it?
speaker: George Emerson

qTextArr: ["Hee-poof--I've swallowed a pollywog, Mr. Beebe, water's wonderful,\nwater's simply ripping."]
qText:
Hee-poof--I've swallowed a pollywog, Mr. Beebe, water's wonderful,
water's simply ripping.
speaker: Freddy

qTextArr: ["Water's not so bad,"]
qText: Water's not so bad,
speaker: George Emerson

qTextArr: ["Water's wonderful. Mr. Beebe, do."]
qText: Water's wonderful. Mr. Beebe, do.
speaker: Freddy

qTextArr: ['Apooshoo, kouf.']
qText: Apooshoo, kouf.
speaker: George Emerson

qTextArr: ['I may as well wash too']
qText: I may as well wash too
speaker: Mr. Beebe

qTextArr: ['Race you round it, then,']
qText: Race you round it, then,
speaker: Freddy

qTextArr: ['A try! A try!']
qText: A try! A try!
speaker: Freddy

qTextArr: ['Socker rules,']
qText: Socker rules,
speaker: George Emerson

qTextArr: ['Goal!']
qText: Goal!
speaker: Freddy

qTextArr: ['Goal!']
qText: Goal!
speaker: George Emerson

qTextArr: ['Pass!']
qText: Pass!
speaker: Freddy

qTextArr: ['Take care my watch!']
qText: Take care my watch!
speaker: Mr. Beebe

qTextArr: ["Take care my hat! No, that's enough, Freddy. Dress now. No, I say!"]
qText: Take care my hat! No, that's enough, Freddy. Dress now. No, I say!
speaker: Mr. Beebe

qTextArr: ["That'll do!", 'Hi! Steady on! I see people coming you fellows!']
qText: That'll do! Hi! Steady on! I see people coming you fellows!
speaker: Mr. Beebe

qTextArr: ['Hi! hi! LADIES!']
qText: Hi! hi! LADIES!
speaker: Mr. Beebe

qTextArr: ['Gracious alive!', 'Whoever were those\nunfortunate people? Oh, dears, look away! And poor Mr. Beebe, too!\nWhatever has happened?']
qText:
Gracious alive! Whoever were those
unfortunate people? Oh, dears, look away! And poor Mr. Beebe, too!
Whatever has happened?
speaker: Mrs. Honeychurch

qTextArr: ['Come this way immediately,']
qText: Come this way immediately,
speaker: Cecil

qTextArr: ["Oh, poor Mr. Beebe! Was that his waistcoat we left in the path? Cecil,\nMr. Beebe's waistcoat--"]
qText:
Oh, poor Mr. Beebe! Was that his waistcoat we left in the path? Cecil,
Mr. Beebe's waistcoat--
speaker: Mrs. Honeychurch

qTextArr: ['No business of ours,']
qText: No business of ours,
speaker: Cecil

qTextArr: ['I fancy Mr. Beebe jumped back into the pond.']
qText: I fancy Mr. Beebe jumped back into the pond.
speaker: Mrs. Honeychurch

qTextArr: ['This way, please, Mrs. Honeychurch, this way.']
qText: This way, please, Mrs. Honeychurch, this way.
speaker: Cecil

qTextArr: ["Well, I can't help it,", "I can't\nbe trodden on, can I?"]
qText:
Well, I can't help it, I can't
be trodden on, can I?
speaker: Freddy

qTextArr: ["Good gracious me, dear; so it's you! What miserable management! Why not\nhave a comfortable bath at home, with hot and cold laid on?"]
qText:
Good gracious me, dear; so it's you! What miserable management! Why not
have a comfortable bath at home, with hot and cold laid on?
speaker: Mrs. Honeychurch

qTextArr: ["Look here, mother, a fellow must wash, and a fellow's got to dry, and\nif another fellow--"]
qText:
Look here, mother, a fellow must wash, and a fellow's got to dry, and
if another fellow--
speaker: Freddy

qTextArr: ["Dear, no doubt you're right as usual, but you are in no position to\nargue. Come, Lucy."]
qText:
Dear, no doubt you're right as usual, but you are in no position to
argue. Come, Lucy.
speaker: Mrs. Honeychurch

qTextArr: ["Oh, look--don't look! Oh, poor Mr.\nBeebe! How unfortunate again--"]
qText:
Oh, look--don't look! Oh, poor Mr.
Beebe! How unfortunate again--
speaker: Mrs. Honeychurch

qTextArr: ["And me, I've swallowed one,", "I've\nswallowed a pollywog. It wriggleth in my tummy. I shall die--Emerson you\nbeast, you've got on my bags."]
qText:
And me, I've swallowed one, I've
swallowed a pollywog. It wriggleth in my tummy. I shall die--Emerson you
beast, you've got on my bags.
speaker: Freddy

qTextArr: ['Hush, dears,', 'And do be sure you dry yourselves thoroughly first. All these\ncolds come of not drying thoroughly.']
qText:
Hush, dears, And do be sure you dry yourselves thoroughly first. All these
colds come of not drying thoroughly.
speaker: Mrs. Honeychurch

qTextArr: ['Mother, do come away,', "Oh for goodness' sake, do come."]
qText: Mother, do come away, Oh for goodness' sake, do come.
speaker: Lucy

qTextArr: ['Hullo!']
qText: Hullo!
speaker: George Emerson

qTextArr: ['Hullo, Miss Honeychurch! Hullo!']
qText: Hullo, Miss Honeychurch! Hullo!
speaker: George Emerson

qTextArr: ['Bow, Lucy; better bow. Whoever is it? I shall bow.']
qText: Bow, Lucy; better bow. Whoever is it? I shall bow.
speaker: Mrs. Honeychurch

qTextArr: ['I will bow,', 'I will not shake hands with him.\nThat will be just the proper thing.']
qText:
I will bow, I will not shake hands with him.
That will be just the proper thing.
speaker: Lucy

qTextArr: ['Lucy,', 'is anything the matter\nwith Cecil?']
qText:
Lucy, is anything the matter
with Cecil?
speaker: Mrs. Honeychurch

qTextArr: ["No, I don't think so, mother; Cecil's all right."]
qText: No, I don't think so, mother; Cecil's all right.
speaker: Lucy

qTextArr: ["Perhaps he's tired."]
qText: Perhaps he's tired.
speaker: Mrs. Honeychurch

qTextArr: ['Because otherwise']
qText: Because otherwise
speaker: Mrs. Honeychurch

qTextArr: ['because otherwise I cannot account for him.']
qText: because otherwise I cannot account for him.
speaker: Mrs. Honeychurch

qTextArr: ['I do think Mrs. Butterworth is rather tiresome, if you mean that.']
qText: I do think Mrs. Butterworth is rather tiresome, if you mean that.
speaker: Lucy

qTextArr: ['Cecil has told you to think so. You were devoted to her as a little\ngirl, and nothing will describe her goodness to you through the typhoid\nfever. No--it is just the same thing everywhere.']
qText:
Cecil has told you to think so. You were devoted to her as a little
girl, and nothing will describe her goodness to you through the typhoid
fever. No--it is just the same thing everywhere.
speaker: Mrs. Honeychurch

qTextArr: ['Let me just put your bonnet away, may I?']
qText: Let me just put your bonnet away, may I?
speaker: Lucy

qTextArr: ['Surely he could answer her civilly for one half-hour?']
qText: Surely he could answer her civilly for one half-hour?
speaker: Mrs. Honeychurch

qTextArr: ['Cecil has a very high standard for people,', "It's part of his ideals--it is really that that makes\nhim sometimes seem--"]
qText:
Cecil has a very high standard for people, It's part of his ideals--it is really that that makes
him sometimes seem--
speaker: Lucy

qTextArr: ['Oh, rubbish! If high ideals make a young man rude, the sooner he gets\nrid of them the better,']
qText:
Oh, rubbish! If high ideals make a young man rude, the sooner he gets
rid of them the better,
speaker: Mrs. Honeychurch

qTextArr: ["Now, mother! I've seen you cross with Mrs. Butterworth yourself!"]
qText: Now, mother! I've seen you cross with Mrs. Butterworth yourself!
speaker: Lucy

qTextArr: ['Not in that way. At times I could wring her neck. But not in that way.\nNo. It is the same with Cecil all over.']
qText:
Not in that way. At times I could wring her neck. But not in that way.
No. It is the same with Cecil all over.
speaker: Mrs. Honeychurch

qTextArr: ['By-the-by--I never told you. I had a letter from Charlotte while I was\naway in London.']
qText:
By-the-by--I never told you. I had a letter from Charlotte while I was
away in London.
speaker: Lucy

qTextArr:
['Since Cecil came back from London, nothing appears to please him.
Whenever I speak he winces;--I see him, Lucy; it is useless to
contradict me. No doubt I am neither artistic nor literary nor
intellectual nor musical, but I cannot help the drawing-room furniture;
your father bought it and we must put up with it, will Cecil kindly
remember.']
qText:
Since Cecil came back from London, nothing appears to please him.
Whenever I speak he winces;--I see him, Lucy; it is useless to
contradict me. No doubt I am neither artistic nor literary nor
intellectual nor musical, but I cannot help the drawing-room furniture;
your father bought it and we must put up with it, will Cecil kindly
remember.
speaker: Mrs. Honeychurch

qTextArr: ["I--I see what you mean, and certainly Cecil oughtn't to. But he does\nnot mean to be uncivil--he once explained--it is the things that upset\nhim--he is easily upset by ugly things--he is not uncivil to PEOPLE."]
qText:
I--I see what you mean, and certainly Cecil oughtn't to. But he does
not mean to be uncivil--he once explained--it is the things that upset
him--he is easily upset by ugly things--he is not uncivil to PEOPLE.
speaker: Lucy

qTextArr: ['Is it a thing or a person when Freddy sings?']
qText: Is it a thing or a person when Freddy sings?
speaker: Mrs. Honeychurch

qTextArr: ["You can't expect a really musical person to enjoy comic songs as we\ndo."]
qText:
You can't expect a really musical person to enjoy comic songs as we
do.
speaker: Lucy

qTextArr: ["Then why didn't he leave the room? Why sit wriggling and sneering and\nspoiling everyone's pleasure?"]
qText:
Then why didn't he leave the room? Why sit wriggling and sneering and
spoiling everyone's pleasure?
speaker: Mrs. Honeychurch

qTextArr: ["We mustn't be unjust to people,"]
qText: We mustn't be unjust to people,
speaker: Lucy

qTextArr: ["Go and dress, dear; you'll be late."]
qText: Go and dress, dear; you'll be late.
speaker: Mrs. Honeychurch

qTextArr: ['All right, mother--']
qText: All right, mother--
speaker: Lucy

qTextArr: ["Don't say"]
qText: Don't say
speaker: Mrs. Honeychurch

qTextArr: ['and stop. Go']
qText: and stop. Go
speaker: Mrs. Honeychurch

qTextArr: ['Oh, dear, what shall I do, what shall I do?']
qText: Oh, dear, what shall I do, what shall I do?
speaker: Lucy

qTextArr: ['I say, those are topping people.']
qText: I say, those are topping people.
speaker: Freddy

qTextArr:
["My dear baby, how tiresome you've been! You have no business to take
them bathing in the Sacred Lake; it's much too public. It was all right for
you but most awkward for everyone else. Do be more careful. You forget
the place is growing half suburban."]
qText:
My dear baby, how tiresome you've been! You have no business to take
them bathing in the Sacred Lake; it's much too public. It was all right for
you but most awkward for everyone else. Do be more careful. You forget
the place is growing half suburban.
speaker: Lucy

qTextArr: ['I say, is anything on to-morrow week?']
qText: I say, is anything on to-morrow week?
speaker: Freddy

qTextArr: ['Not that I know of.']
qText: Not that I know of.
speaker: Lucy

qTextArr: ['Then I want to ask the Emersons up to Sunday tennis.']
qText: Then I want to ask the Emersons up to Sunday tennis.
speaker: Freddy

qTextArr: ["Oh, I wouldn't do that, Freddy, I wouldn't do that with all this\nmuddle."]
qText:
Oh, I wouldn't do that, Freddy, I wouldn't do that with all this
muddle.
speaker: Lucy

qTextArr: ["What's wrong with the court? They won't mind a bump or two, and I've\nordered new balls."]
qText:
What's wrong with the court? They won't mind a bump or two, and I've
ordered new balls.
speaker: Freddy

qTextArr: ["I meant it's better not. I really mean it."]
qText: I meant it's better not. I really mean it.
speaker: Lucy

qTextArr: ["Lucy, what a noise you're making! I\nhave something to say to you. Did you say you had had a letter from\nCharlotte?"]
qText:
Lucy, what a noise you're making! I
have something to say to you. Did you say you had had a letter from
Charlotte?
speaker: Mrs. Honeychurch
refExp: Mrs Honeychurch opened her door and said

qTextArr: ["Yes. I really can't stop. I must dress too."]
qText: Yes. I really can't stop. I must dress too.
speaker: Lucy

qTextArr: ["How's Charlotte?"]
qText: How's Charlotte?
speaker: Mrs. Honeychurch

qTextArr: ['All right.']
qText: All right.
speaker: Lucy

qTextArr: ['Lucy!']
qText: Lucy!
speaker: Mrs. Honeychurch

qTextArr: ["You've a bad habit of hurrying away in the middle of one's sentences.\nDid Charlotte mention her boiler?"]
qText:
You've a bad habit of hurrying away in the middle of one's sentences.
Did Charlotte mention her boiler?
speaker: Mrs. Honeychurch

qTextArr: ['Her WHAT?']
qText: Her WHAT?
speaker: Lucy

qTextArr: ["Don't you remember that her boiler was to be had out in October, and\nher bath cistern cleaned out, and all kinds of terrible to-doings?"]
qText:
Don't you remember that her boiler was to be had out in October, and
her bath cistern cleaned out, and all kinds of terrible to-doings?
speaker: Mrs. Honeychurch

qTextArr: ["I can't remember all Charlotte's worries,", 'I shall\nhave enough of my own, now that you are not pleased with Cecil.']
qText:
I can't remember all Charlotte's worries, I shall
have enough of my own, now that you are not pleased with Cecil.
speaker: Lucy

qTextArr: ['Come\nhere, old lady--thank you for putting away my bonnet--kiss me.']
qText:
Come
here, old lady--thank you for putting away my bonnet--kiss me.
speaker: Mrs. Honeychurch

qTextArr: ["Lucy, what's Emerson like?"]
qText: Lucy, what's Emerson like?
speaker: Freddy

qTextArr: ['I saw him in Florence,']
qText: I saw him in Florence,
speaker: Lucy

qTextArr: ['Is he the clever sort, or is he a decent chap?']
qText: Is he the clever sort, or is he a decent chap?
speaker: Freddy

qTextArr: ['Ask Cecil; it is Cecil who brought him here.']
qText: Ask Cecil; it is Cecil who brought him here.
speaker: Lucy

qTextArr: ['He is the clever sort, like myself,']
qText: He is the clever sort, like myself,
speaker: Cecil

qTextArr: ['How well did you know them at the Bertolini?']
qText: How well did you know them at the Bertolini?
speaker: Mrs. Honeychurch

qTextArr: ['Oh, very slightly. I mean, Charlotte knew them even less than I did.']
qText: Oh, very slightly. I mean, Charlotte knew them even less than I did.
speaker: Lucy

qTextArr: ['Oh, that reminds me--you never told me what Charlotte said in her\nletter.']
qText:
Oh, that reminds me--you never told me what Charlotte said in her
letter.
speaker: Mrs. Honeychurch

qTextArr: ['One thing and another,', "Among other things, that an awful\nfriend of hers had been bicycling through Summer Street, wondered if\nshe'd come up and see us, and mercifully didn't."]
qText:
One thing and another, Among other things, that an awful
friend of hers had been bicycling through Summer Street, wondered if
she'd come up and see us, and mercifully didn't.
speaker: Lucy

qTextArr: ['Lucy, I do call the way you talk unkind.']
qText: Lucy, I do call the way you talk unkind.
speaker: Mrs. Honeychurch

qTextArr: ['She was a novelist,']
qText: She was a novelist,
speaker: Lucy

qTextArr: ['This year, next year, now, never,']
qText: This year, next year, now, never,
speaker: Freddy

qTextArr: ["I have been thinking, Lucy, of that letter of Charlotte's. How is she?"]
qText: I have been thinking, Lucy, of that letter of Charlotte's. How is she?
speaker: Mrs. Honeychurch

qTextArr: ['I tore the thing up.']
qText: I tore the thing up.
speaker: Lucy

qTextArr: ["Didn't she say how she was? How does she sound? Cheerful?"]
qText: Didn't she say how she was? How does she sound? Cheerful?
speaker: Mrs. Honeychurch

qTextArr: ['Oh, yes I suppose so--no--not very cheerful, I suppose.']
qText: Oh, yes I suppose so--no--not very cheerful, I suppose.
speaker: Lucy

qTextArr: ["Then, depend upon it, it IS the boiler. I know myself how water preys\nupon one's mind. I would rather anything else--even a misfortune with\nthe meat."]
qText:
Then, depend upon it, it IS the boiler. I know myself how water preys
upon one's mind. I would rather anything else--even a misfortune with
the meat.
speaker: Mrs. Honeychurch

qTextArr: ['So would I,']
qText: So would I,
speaker: Freddy

qTextArr:
['And I have been thinking,', 'surely we could
squeeze Charlotte in here next week, and give her a nice holiday while
plumbers at Tunbridge Wells finish. I have not seen poor Charlotte for
so long.']
qText:
And I have been thinking, surely we could
squeeze Charlotte in here next week, and give her a nice holiday while
plumbers at Tunbridge Wells finish. I have not seen poor Charlotte for
so long.
speaker: Mrs. Honeychurch

qTextArr:
['Mother, no!', "It's impossible. We can't have Charlotte on
the top of the other things; we're squeezed to death as it is. Freddy's
got a friend coming Tuesday, there's Cecil, and you've promised to take
in Minnie Beebe because of the diphtheria scare. It simply can't be
done."]
qText:
Mother, no! It's impossible. We can't have Charlotte on
the top of the other things; we're squeezed to death as it is. Freddy's
got a friend coming Tuesday, there's Cecil, and you've promised to take
in Minnie Beebe because of the diphtheria scare. It simply can't be
done.
speaker: Lucy
menEnts: [[['Mrs. Honeychurch']], [['Freddy', 'Lucy', 'Mrs. Honeychurch'], ['Miss Bartlett'], ['Freddy', 'Lucy', 'Mrs. Honeychurch'], ['Freddy'], ['Mr. Floyd'], ['Cecil'], ['Mrs. Honeychurch'], ['Minnie Beebe']]]

qTextArr: ['Nonsense! It can.']
qText: Nonsense! It can.
speaker: Mrs. Honeychurch

qTextArr: ['If Minnie sleeps in the bath. Not otherwise.']
qText: If Minnie sleeps in the bath. Not otherwise.
speaker: Lucy

qTextArr: ['Minnie can sleep with you.']
qText: Minnie can sleep with you.
speaker: Mrs. Honeychurch

qTextArr: ["I won't have her."]
qText: I won't have her.
speaker: Lucy

qTextArr: ["Then, if you're so selfish, Mr. Floyd must share a room with Freddy."]
qText: Then, if you're so selfish, Mr. Floyd must share a room with Freddy.
speaker: Mrs. Honeychurch

qTextArr: ['Miss Bartlett, Miss Bartlett, Miss Bartlett,']
qText: Miss Bartlett, Miss Bartlett, Miss Bartlett,
speaker: Cecil

qTextArr: ["It's impossible,", "I don't want to make difficulties,\nbut it really isn't fair on the maids to fill up the house so."]
qText:
It's impossible, I don't want to make difficulties,
but it really isn't fair on the maids to fill up the house so.
speaker: Lucy

qTextArr: ["The truth is, dear, you don't like Charlotte."]
qText: The truth is, dear, you don't like Charlotte.
speaker: Mrs. Honeychurch

qTextArr:
["No, I don't. And no more does Cecil. She gets on our nerves. You
haven't seen her lately, and don't realize how tiresome she can be,
though so good. So please, mother, don't worry us this last summer; but
spoil us by not asking her to come."]
qText:
No, I don't. And no more does Cecil. She gets on our nerves. You
haven't seen her lately, and don't realize how tiresome she can be,
though so good. So please, mother, don't worry us this last summer; but
spoil us by not asking her to come.
speaker: Lucy

qTextArr: ['Hear, hear!']
qText: Hear, hear!
speaker: Cecil

qTextArr:
["This isn't very kind of
you two. You have each other and all these woods to walk in, so full of
beautiful things; and poor Charlotte has only the water turned off and
plumbers. You are young, dears, and however clever young people are, and
however many books they read, they will never guess what it feels like
to grow old."]
qText:
This isn't very kind of
you two. You have each other and all these woods to walk in, so full of
beautiful things; and poor Charlotte has only the water turned off and
plumbers. You are young, dears, and however clever young people are, and
however many books they read, they will never guess what it feels like
to grow old.
speaker: Mrs. Honeychurch
refExp: Mrs Honeychurch with more gravity than usual and with more feeling than she usually permitted herself replied

qTextArr:
['I must say Cousin Charlotte was very kind to me that year I called on
my bike,', 'She thanked me for coming till I felt like
such a fool, and fussed round no end to get an egg boiled for my tea
just right.']
qText:
I must say Cousin Charlotte was very kind to me that year I called on
my bike, She thanked me for coming till I felt like
such a fool, and fussed round no end to get an egg boiled for my tea
just right.
speaker: Freddy

qTextArr: ['I know, dear. She is kind to everyone, and yet Lucy makes this\ndifficulty when we try to give her some little return.']
qText:
I know, dear. She is kind to everyone, and yet Lucy makes this
difficulty when we try to give her some little return.
speaker: Mrs. Honeychurch

qTextArr: ["I\ncan't help it, mother. I don't like Charlotte. I admit it's horrid of\nme."]
qText:
I
can't help it, mother. I don't like Charlotte. I admit it's horrid of
me.
speaker: Lucy

qTextArr: ['From your own account, you told her as much.']
qText: From your own account, you told her as much.
speaker: Mrs. Honeychurch

qTextArr: ['Well, she would leave Florence so stupidly. She flurried--']
qText: Well, she would leave Florence so stupidly. She flurried--
speaker: Lucy

qTextArr: ['I suppose Miss Bartlett must come, since she boils eggs so well,']
qText: I suppose Miss Bartlett must come, since she boils eggs so well,
speaker: Cecil

qTextArr: ["I didn't mean the egg was WELL boiled,", "because in\npoint of fact she forgot to take it off, and as a matter of fact I don't\ncare for eggs. I only meant how jolly kind she seemed."]
qText:
I didn't mean the egg was WELL boiled, because in
point of fact she forgot to take it off, and as a matter of fact I don't
care for eggs. I only meant how jolly kind she seemed.
speaker: Freddy

qTextArr: ['May me and Lucy get down from\nour chairs?', "We don't want no\ndessert."]
qText:
May me and Lucy get down from
our chairs? We don't want no
dessert.
speaker: Cecil

qTextArr: ['A nice fellow,', 'He will work off his\ncrudities in time. I rather mistrust young men who slip into life\ngracefully.']
qText:
A nice fellow, He will work off his
crudities in time. I rather mistrust young men who slip into life
gracefully.
speaker: Mr. Beebe

qTextArr: ['He seems in better spirits. He laughs more.']
qText: He seems in better spirits. He laughs more.
speaker: Lucy

qTextArr: ['Yes,', 'He is waking up.']
qText: Yes, He is waking up.
speaker: Mr. Beebe

qTextArr: ['I shall never forgive myself,', 'I have upset everything. Bursting in on young people! But I insist on\npaying for my cab up. Grant that, at any rate.']
qText:
I shall never forgive myself, I have upset everything. Bursting in on young people! But I insist on
paying for my cab up. Grant that, at any rate.
speaker: Miss Bartlett

qTextArr: ["Just what I've been trying to convince\nCousin Charlotte of, Lucy, for the last half hour."]
qText:
Just what I've been trying to convince
Cousin Charlotte of, Lucy, for the last half hour.
speaker: Freddy
refExp: her brother in whose memory the boiled egg had already grown unsubstantial exclaimed

qTextArr: ['I do not feel myself an ordinary visitor,']
qText: I do not feel myself an ordinary visitor,
speaker: Miss Bartlett

qTextArr: ["All right, if you'd really rather. Five shillings, and I gave a bob to\nthe driver."]
qText:
All right, if you'd really rather. Five shillings, and I gave a bob to
the driver.
speaker: Freddy

qTextArr: ['But who\nam I to give the sovereign to?']
qText:
But who
am I to give the sovereign to?
speaker: Miss Bartlett
refExp: Miss Bartlett accepted their moneys and then said

qTextArr: ["Let's leave it all till mother comes back,"]
qText: Let's leave it all till mother comes back,
speaker: Lucy

qTextArr: ['No, dear; your mother may take quite a long drive now that she is not\nhampered with me. We all have our little foibles, and mine is the prompt\nsettling of accounts.']
qText:
No, dear; your mother may take quite a long drive now that she is not
hampered with me. We all have our little foibles, and mine is the prompt
settling of accounts.
speaker: Miss Bartlett

qTextArr: ['Please--please--I know I am a sad spoil-sport, but it would make me\nwretched. I should practically be robbing the one who lost.']
qText:
Please--please--I know I am a sad spoil-sport, but it would make me
wretched. I should practically be robbing the one who lost.
speaker: Miss Bartlett

qTextArr: ['Freddy owes me fifteen shillings,', 'So it will work\nout right if you give the pound to me.']
qText:
Freddy owes me fifteen shillings, So it will work
out right if you give the pound to me.
speaker: Cecil

qTextArr: ['Fifteen shillings,', 'How is that, Mr.\nVyse?']
qText:
Fifteen shillings, How is that, Mr.
Vyse?
speaker: Miss Bartlett

qTextArr: ["Because, don't you see, Freddy paid your cab. Give me the pound, and we\nshall avoid this deplorable gambling."]
qText:
Because, don't you see, Freddy paid your cab. Give me the pound, and we
shall avoid this deplorable gambling.
speaker: Cecil

qTextArr: ["But I don't see that!", "I don't see why Mr. Vyse is to have the\nquid."]
qText:
But I don't see that! I don't see why Mr. Vyse is to have the
quid.
speaker: Minnie Beebe

qTextArr: ["But I don't see--"]
qText: But I don't see--
speaker: Minnie Beebe

qTextArr:
["No, thank you. I'm done. I don't see why--Freddy, don't poke me. Miss
Honeychurch, your brother's hurting me. Ow! What about Mr. Floyd's
ten shillings? Ow! No, I don't see and I never shall see why Miss
What's-her-name shouldn't pay that bob for the driver."]
qText:
No, thank you. I'm done. I don't see why--Freddy, don't poke me. Miss
Honeychurch, your brother's hurting me. Ow! What about Mr. Floyd's
ten shillings? Ow! No, I don't see and I never shall see why Miss
What's-her-name shouldn't pay that bob for the driver.
speaker: Minnie Beebe

qTextArr: ['I had forgotten the driver,', 'Thank you,\ndear, for reminding me. A shilling was it? Can any one give me change\nfor half a crown?']
qText:
I had forgotten the driver, Thank you,
dear, for reminding me. A shilling was it? Can any one give me change
for half a crown?
speaker: Miss Bartlett

qTextArr: ["I'll get it,"]
qText: I'll get it,
speaker: Lucy

qTextArr: ["Cecil, give me that sovereign. No, give me up that sovereign. I'll get\nEuphemia to change it, and we'll start the whole thing again from the\nbeginning."]
qText:
Cecil, give me that sovereign. No, give me up that sovereign. I'll get
Euphemia to change it, and we'll start the whole thing again from the
beginning.
speaker: Lucy

qTextArr: ['Lucy--Lucy--what a nuisance I am!']
qText: Lucy--Lucy--what a nuisance I am!
speaker: Miss Bartlett

qTextArr: ['Have you told him about him yet?']
qText: Have you told him about him yet?
speaker: Miss Bartlett
refExp: Miss Bartlett stopped her wails and said

qTextArr: ["No, I haven't,", "Let me see--a\nsovereign's worth of silver."]
qText:
No, I haven't, Let me see--a
sovereign's worth of silver.
speaker: Lucy

qTextArr: ["No, I haven't told Cecil or any one,", "I promised you I shouldn't. Here is your money--all shillings, except\ntwo half-crowns. Would you count it? You can settle your debt nicely\nnow."]
qText:
No, I haven't told Cecil or any one, I promised you I shouldn't. Here is your money--all shillings, except
two half-crowns. Would you count it? You can settle your debt nicely
now.
speaker: Lucy
menEnts: [[['Cecil']], [['Miss Bartlett'], ['Miss Bartlett'], ['Miss Bartlett'], ['Miss Bartlett'], ['Miss Bartlett'], ['Miss Bartlett']]]

qTextArr: ['How dreadful!', 'how more than dreadful, if Mr. Vyse\nshould come to hear of it from some other source.']
qText:
How dreadful! how more than dreadful, if Mr. Vyse
should come to hear of it from some other source.
speaker: Miss Bartlett

qTextArr: ['Oh, no, Charlotte,', 'George Emerson\nis all right, and what other source is there?']
qText:
Oh, no, Charlotte, George Emerson
is all right, and what other source is there?
speaker: Lucy

qTextArr: ['For instance, the driver. I saw him looking\nthrough the bushes at you, remember he had a violet between his teeth.']
qText:
For instance, the driver. I saw him looking
through the bushes at you, remember he had a violet between his teeth.
speaker: Miss Bartlett

qTextArr: ["We shall get the silly affair on our nerves\nif we aren't careful. How could a Florentine cab-driver ever get hold of\nCecil?"]
qText:
We shall get the silly affair on our nerves
if we aren't careful. How could a Florentine cab-driver ever get hold of
Cecil?
speaker: Lucy

qTextArr: ['We must think of every possibility.']
qText: We must think of every possibility.
speaker: Miss Bartlett

qTextArr: ["Oh, it's all right."]
qText: Oh, it's all right.
speaker: Lucy

qTextArr: ['Or perhaps old Mr. Emerson knows. In fact, he is certain to know.']
qText: Or perhaps old Mr. Emerson knows. In fact, he is certain to know.
speaker: Miss Bartlett

qTextArr: ["I don't care if he does. I was grateful to you for your letter, but\neven if the news does get round, I think I can trust Cecil to laugh at\nit."]
qText:
I don't care if he does. I was grateful to you for your letter, but
even if the news does get round, I think I can trust Cecil to laugh at
it.
speaker: Lucy

qTextArr: ['To contradict it?']
qText: To contradict it?
speaker: Miss Bartlett

qTextArr: ['No, to laugh at it.']
qText: No, to laugh at it.
speaker: Lucy

qTextArr: ['Very well, dear, you know best. Perhaps gentlemen are different to what\nthey were when I was young. Ladies are certainly different.']
qText:
Very well, dear, you know best. Perhaps gentlemen are different to what
they were when I was young. Ladies are certainly different.
speaker: Miss Bartlett

qTextArr: ['Now, Charlotte!']
qText: Now, Charlotte!
speaker: Lucy

qTextArr:
['I am no match for you in conversation, dearest. I
blush when I think how I interfered at Florence, and you so well able
to look after yourself, and so much cleverer in all ways than I am. You
will never forgive me.']
qText:
I am no match for you in conversation, dearest. I
blush when I think how I interfered at Florence, and you so well able
to look after yourself, and so much cleverer in all ways than I am. You
will never forgive me.
speaker: Miss Bartlett

qTextArr: ["Shall we go out, then. They will smash all the china if we don't."]
qText: Shall we go out, then. They will smash all the china if we don't.
speaker: Lucy

qTextArr: ['Dear, one moment--we may not have this chance for a chat again. Have\nyou seen the young one yet?']
qText:
Dear, one moment--we may not have this chance for a chat again. Have
you seen the young one yet?
speaker: Miss Bartlett

qTextArr: ['Yes, I have.']
qText: Yes, I have.
speaker: Lucy

qTextArr: ['What happened?']
qText: What happened?
speaker: Miss Bartlett

qTextArr: ['We met at the Rectory.']
qText: We met at the Rectory.
speaker: Lucy

qTextArr: ['What line is he taking up?']
qText: What line is he taking up?
speaker: Miss Bartlett

qTextArr:
["No line. He talked about Italy, like any other person. It is really all
right. What advantage would he get from being a cad, to put it bluntly?
I do wish I could make you see it my way. He really won't be any
nuisance, Charlotte."]
qText:
No line. He talked about Italy, like any other person. It is really all
right. What advantage would he get from being a cad, to put it bluntly?
I do wish I could make you see it my way. He really won't be any
nuisance, Charlotte.
speaker: Lucy

qTextArr: ['Once a cad, always a cad. That is my poor opinion.']
qText: Once a cad, always a cad. That is my poor opinion.
speaker: Miss Bartlett

qTextArr: ['Cecil said one day--and I thought it so profound--that\nthere are two kinds of cads--the conscious and the subconscious.']
qText:
Cecil said one day--and I thought it so profound--that
there are two kinds of cads--the conscious and the subconscious.
speaker: Lucy

qTextArr: ['Once a cad, always a cad,']
qText: Once a cad, always a cad,
speaker: Miss Bartlett

qTextArr:
["What I mean by subconscious is that Emerson lost his head. I fell into
all those violets, and he was silly and surprised. I don't think we
ought to blame him very much. It makes such a difference when you see a
person with beautiful things behind him unexpectedly. It really does;
it makes an enormous difference, and he lost his head: he doesn't admire
me, or any of that nonsense, one straw. Freddy rather likes him, and
has asked him up here on Sunday, so you can judge for yourself. He has
improved; he doesn't always look as if he's going to burst into
tears. He is a clerk in the General Manager's office at one of the big
railways--not a porter! and runs down to his father for week-ends. Papa
was to do with journalism, but is rheumatic and has retired. There!
Now for the garden."]
qText:
What I mean by subconscious is that Emerson lost his head. I fell into
all those violets, and he was silly and surprised. I don't think we
ought to blame him very much. It makes such a difference when you see a
person with beautiful things behind him unexpectedly. It really does;
it makes an enormous difference, and he lost his head: he doesn't admire
me, or any of that nonsense, one straw. Freddy rather likes him, and
has asked him up here on Sunday, so you can judge for yourself. He has
improved; he doesn't always look as if he's going to burst into
tears. He is a clerk in the General Manager's office at one of the big
railways--not a porter! and runs down to his father for week-ends. Papa
was to do with journalism, but is rheumatic and has retired. There!
Now for the garden.
speaker: Lucy
menEnts: [[['George Emerson'], ['George Emerson'], ['George Emerson'], ['Lucy', 'Miss Bartlett'], ['George Emerson'], ['Miss Bartlett'], ['George Emerson'], ['George Emerson'], ['George Emerson'], ['George Emerson'], ['Freddy'], ['George Emerson'], ['George Emerson'], ['Miss Bartlett'], ['Miss Bartlett'], ['George Emerson'], ['George Emerson'], ['George Emerson'], ['George Emerson'], ['George Emerson'], ['Mr. Emerson'], ['Mr. Emerson']]]

qTextArr: ["Suppose we\ndon't talk about this silly Italian business any more. We want you to\nhave a nice restful visit at Windy Corner, with no worriting."]
qText:
Suppose we
don't talk about this silly Italian business any more. We want you to
have a nice restful visit at Windy Corner, with no worriting.
speaker: Lucy

qTextArr: ["Well, I don't blame them", 'need she go?']
qText: Well, I don't blame them need she go?
speaker: Minnie Beebe

qTextArr: ["Lucy! Lucy! What's that book? Who's been taking a book out of the shelf\nand leaving it about to spoil?"]
qText:
Lucy! Lucy! What's that book? Who's been taking a book out of the shelf
and leaving it about to spoil?
speaker: Mrs. Honeychurch

qTextArr: ["It's only the library book that Cecil's been reading."]
qText: It's only the library book that Cecil's been reading.
speaker: Lucy

qTextArr: ["But pick it up, and don't stand idling there like a flamingo."]
qText: But pick it up, and don't stand idling there like a flamingo.
speaker: Mrs. Honeychurch

qTextArr: ["What! you aren't forgetting your Italy already?"]
qText: What! you aren't forgetting your Italy already?
speaker: Mr. Vyse

qTextArr: ['Lucy--have you a sixpence for Minnie and a shilling for yourself?']
qText: Lucy--have you a sixpence for Minnie and a shilling for yourself?
speaker: Mrs. Honeychurch

qTextArr:
["It's a special collection--I forget what for. I do beg, no vulgar
clinking in the plate with halfpennies; see that Minnie has a nice
bright sixpence. Where is the child? Minnie! That book's all warped.
(Gracious, how plain you look!) Put it under the Atlas to press.
Minnie!"]
qText:
It's a special collection--I forget what for. I do beg, no vulgar
clinking in the plate with halfpennies; see that Minnie has a nice
bright sixpence. Where is the child? Minnie! That book's all warped.
(Gracious, how plain you look!) Put it under the Atlas to press.
Minnie!
speaker: Mrs. Honeychurch

qTextArr: ['Oh, Mrs. Honeychurch--']
qText: Oh, Mrs. Honeychurch--
speaker: Minnie Beebe

qTextArr: ["Minnie, don't be late. Here comes the horse"]
qText: Minnie, don't be late. Here comes the horse
speaker: Mrs. Honeychurch

qTextArr: ["Where's Charlotte? Run up and hurry her. Why is she\nso long? She had nothing to do. She never brings anything but blouses.\nPoor Charlotte--How I do detest blouses! Minnie!"]
qText:
Where's Charlotte? Run up and hurry her. Why is she
so long? She had nothing to do. She never brings anything but blouses.
Poor Charlotte--How I do detest blouses! Minnie!
speaker: Mrs. Honeychurch

qTextArr: ['Dear Marian, I am very sorry, but I have no small change--nothing but\nsovereigns and half crowns. Could any one give me--']
qText:
Dear Marian, I am very sorry, but I have no small change--nothing but
sovereigns and half crowns. Could any one give me--
speaker: Miss Bartlett

qTextArr: ['Yes, easily. Jump in. Gracious me, how smart you look! What a lovely\nfrock! You put us all to shame.']
qText:
Yes, easily. Jump in. Gracious me, how smart you look! What a lovely
frock! You put us all to shame.
speaker: Mrs. Honeychurch

qTextArr: ['If I did not wear my best rags and tatters now, when should I wear\nthem?']
qText:
If I did not wear my best rags and tatters now, when should I wear
them?
speaker: Miss Bartlett

qTextArr: ['Good-bye! Be good!']
qText: Good-bye! Be good!
speaker: Mr. Vyse

qText:
Introduce me, Unless the young man considers that he
knows me already.
speaker: Mrs. Honeychurch

qTextArr: ['Very much,']
qText: Very much,
speaker: Mr. Emerson

qTextArr: ['We find, though,\nthat the Miss Alans were coming, and that we have turned them out. Women\nmind such a thing. I am very much upset about it.']
qText:
We find, though,
that the Miss Alans were coming, and that we have turned them out. Women
mind such a thing. I am very much upset about it.
speaker: Mr. Emerson

qTextArr: ['I believe that there was some misunderstanding,']
qText: I believe that there was some misunderstanding,
speaker: Mrs. Honeychurch

qTextArr: ['Our landlord was told that we should be a different type of person,', 'He\nthought we should be artistic. He is disappointed.']
qText:
Our landlord was told that we should be a different type of person, He
thought we should be artistic. He is disappointed.
speaker: George Emerson
menEnts: [[['Sir Harry Otway'], ['George Emerson', 'Mr. Emerson']], [['Sir Harry Otway'], ['George Emerson', 'Mr. Emerson'], ['Sir Harry Otway']]]

qTextArr: ['And I wonder whether we ought to write to the Miss Alans and offer to\ngive it up. What do you think?']
qText:
And I wonder whether we ought to write to the Miss Alans and offer to
give it up. What do you think?
speaker: George Emerson

qTextArr: ['Oh, stop now you have come,']
qText: Oh, stop now you have come,
speaker: Lucy

qTextArr: ['So George says. He says that the Miss Alans must go to the wall. Yet it\ndoes seem so unkind.']
qText:
So George says. He says that the Miss Alans must go to the wall. Yet it
does seem so unkind.
speaker: Mr. Emerson

qTextArr: ['There is only a certain amount of kindness in the world,']
qText: There is only a certain amount of kindness in the world,
speaker: George Emerson

qTextArr: ['Yes!', "That's exactly what I say. Why all\nthis twiddling and twaddling over two Miss Alans?"]
qText:
Yes! That's exactly what I say. Why all
this twiddling and twaddling over two Miss Alans?
speaker: Mrs. Honeychurch

qTextArr:
['There is a certain amount of kindness, just as there is a certain
amount of light,', "We cast a shadow
on something wherever we stand, and it is no good moving from place to
place to save things; because the shadow always follows. Choose a place
where you won't do harm--yes, choose a place where you won't do very
much harm, and stand in it for all you are worth, facing the sunshine."]
qText:
There is a certain amount of kindness, just as there is a certain
amount of light, We cast a shadow
on something wherever we stand, and it is no good moving from place to
place to save things; because the shadow always follows. Choose a place
where you won't do harm--yes, choose a place where you won't do very
much harm, and stand in it for all you are worth, facing the sunshine.
speaker: George Emerson

qTextArr: ["Oh, Mr. Emerson, I see you're clever!"]
qText: Oh, Mr. Emerson, I see you're clever!
speaker: Mrs. Honeychurch

qText: Eh--?
speaker: George Emerson

qTextArr: ["I see you're going to be clever. I hope you didn't go behaving like\nthat to poor Freddy."]
qText:
I see you're going to be clever. I hope you didn't go behaving like
that to poor Freddy.
speaker: Mrs. Honeychurch

qTextArr: ["No, I didn't,", 'He behaved that way to me. It is his\nphilosophy. Only he starts life with it; and I have tried the Note of\nInterrogation first.']
qText:
No, I didn't, He behaved that way to me. It is his
philosophy. Only he starts life with it; and I have tried the Note of
Interrogation first.
speaker: George Emerson

qTextArr: ["What DO you mean? No, never mind what you mean. Don't explain. He looks\nforward to seeing you this afternoon. Do you play tennis? Do you mind\ntennis on Sunday--?"]
qText:
What DO you mean? No, never mind what you mean. Don't explain. He looks
forward to seeing you this afternoon. Do you play tennis? Do you mind
tennis on Sunday--?
speaker: Mrs. Honeychurch

qText:
George mind tennis on Sunday! George, after his education, distinguish
between Sunday--
speaker: Mr. Emerson

qTextArr: ["Very well, George doesn't mind tennis on Sunday. No more do I. That's\nsettled. Mr. Emerson, if you could come with your son we should be so\npleased."]
qText:
Very well, George doesn't mind tennis on Sunday. No more do I. That's
settled. Mr. Emerson, if you could come with your son we should be so
pleased.
speaker: Mrs. Honeychurch

qText:
And then he wants to give up his house to the
Miss Alans.
speaker: Mrs. Honeychurch

qText: I know,
speaker: George Emerson

qText: Yes, indeed!

qText: Yes, I do hope he will.

The old man hasn't been told;
I knew it was all right.

qText: He has not told, he has not told.

qText:
He has not told his father--to whom he tells all things. It was
not an exploit. He did not laugh at me when I had gone. He does not love me. No. How terrible if he did! But
he has not told. He will not tell.

It is all right. It's a secret between
us two for ever. Cecil will never hear.

qText: How are my proteges?

indeed! Why it's Miss

qText: H'm!

qText: My father

qTextArr:
['says
that there is only one perfect view--the view of the sky straight over
our heads, and that all these views on earth are but bungled copies of
it.']
qText:
says
that there is only one perfect view--the view of the sky straight over
our heads, and that all these views on earth are but bungled copies of
it.
speaker: George Emerson

['He told us another day that views are really crowds--crowds of trees
and houses and hills--and are bound to resemble each other, like human
crowds--and that the power they have over us is sometimes supernatural,
for the same reason.']
qText:
He told us another day that views are really crowds--crowds of trees
and houses and hills--and are bound to resemble each other, like human
crowds--and that the power they have over us is sometimes supernatural,
for the same reason.
speaker: George Emerson

For a crowd is more than the people who make it up. Something gets

hills.

qTextArr:
["No, but have you ever? He is the sort who are all right so long as
they keep to things--books, pictures--but kill when they come to
people. That's why I'll speak out through all this muddle even now. It's
shocking enough to lose you in any case, but generally a man must
deny himself joy, and I would have held back if your Cecil had been a
different person. I would never have let myself go. But I saw him first
in the National Gallery, when he winced because my father mispronounced
the names of great painters. Then he brings us here, and we find it
is to play some silly trick on a kind neighbour. That is the man all
over--playing tricks on people, on the most sacred form of life that
he can find. Next, I meet you together, and find him protecting and
teaching you and your mother to be shocked, when it was for YOU to
settle whether you were shocked or no. Cecil all over again. He daren't
let a woman decide. He's the type who's kept Europe back for a thousand
years. Every moment of his life he's forming you, telling you what's
charming or amusing or ladylike, telling you what a man thinks womanly;
and you, you of all women, listen to his voice instead of to your own.
So it was at the Rectory, when I met you both again; so it has been
the whole of this afternoon. Therefore--not"]
qText:

different person. I would never have let myself go. But I saw him first
in the National Gallery, when he winced because my father mispronounced
the names of great painters. Then he brings us here, and we find it
is to play some silly trick on a kind neighbour. That is the man all
over--playing tricks on people, on the most sacred form of life that
he can find. Next, I meet you together, and find him protecting and
teaching you and your mother to be shocked, when it was for YOU to
settle whether you were shocked or no. Cecil all over again. He daren't
let a woman decide. He's the type who's kept Europe back for a thousand
years. Every moment of his life he's forming you, telling you what's

So it was at the Rectory, when I met you both again; so it has been

qText:
Lucy, be
quick--there's no time for us to talk now--come to me as you came in the
spring, and afterwards I will be gentle and explain. I have cared
for you since that man died. I cannot live without you, I
thought; but I meet you again when all
the world is glorious water and sun. As you came through the wood I
saw that nothing else mattered. I called. I wanted to live and have my
chance of joy.

qTextArr:
["I knew you wouldn't understand,", "I might have
known there would have been these dreadful explanations. Of course,

feeling for weeks. Surely it was better not to speak until I felt
certain.", "Often before I have wondered if
I was fitted for your wife--for instance, in London; and are you fitted
to be my husband? I don't think so. You don't like Freddy, nor my
mother. There was always a lot against our engagement, Cecil, but all
our relations seemed pleased, and we met so often, and it was no good
mentioning it until--well, until all things came to a point. They have
to-day. I see clearly. I must speak. That's all."]
qText:
I knew you wouldn't understand, I might have
known there would have been these dreadful explanations. Of course,
it isn't the tennis--that was only the last straw to all I have been
feeling for weeks. Surely it was better not to speak until I felt
certain. Often before I have wondered if
I was fitted for your wife--for instance, in London; and are you fitted
to be my husband? I don't think so. You don't like Freddy, nor my
mother. There was always a lot against our engagement, Cecil, but all
our relations seemed pleased, and we met so often, and it was no good
mentioning it until--well, until all things came to a point. They have
to-day. I see clearly. I must speak. That's all.
speaker: Lucy

qTextArr:
["I don't mean exactly that. But you will question me, though I beg you
not to, and I must say something. It is that, more or less. When we
were only acquaintances, you let me be myself, but now you're always
protecting me.", "I won't be protected. I will choose
for myself what is ladylike and right. To shield me is an insult. Can't
I be trusted to face the truth but I must get it second-hand through
you? A woman's place! You despise my mother--I know you do--because
she's conventional and bothers over puddings; but, oh goodness!", "conventional, Cecil, you're that, for you may
understand beautiful things, but you don't know how to use them; and you
wrap yourself up in art and books and music, and would try to wrap up
me. I won't be stifled, not by the most glorious music, for people are

qText:
I don't mean exactly that. But you will question me, though I beg you
not to, and I must say something. It is that, more or less. When we
were only acquaintances, you let me be myself, but now you're always
protecting me. I won't be protected. I will choose
for myself what is ladylike and right. To shield me is an insult. Can't
I be trusted to face the truth but I must get it second-hand through
you? A woman's place! You despise my mother--I know you do--because
she's conventional and bothers over puddings; but, oh goodness! conventional, Cecil, you're that, for you may
understand beautiful things, but you don't know how to use them; and you
wrap yourself up in art and books and music, and would try to wrap up
me. I won't be stifled, not by the most glorious music, for people are
more glorious, and you hide them from me. That's why I break off my
engagement. You were all right as long as you kept to things, but when
you came to people--
speaker: Lucy
menEnts: [[['Mr. Vyse', 'Lucy']], [['Mr. Vyse'], ['Mrs. Honeychurch'], ['Mr. Vyse'], ['Mrs. Honeychurch']], [['Mr. Vyse'], ['Mr. Vyse'], ['Mr. Vyse'], ['Mr. Vyse'], ['Mr. Vyse'], ['Mr. Vyse'], ['Mr. Vyse'], ['Mr. Vyse'], ['Mr. Vyse'], ['Mr. Vyse']]]

qTextArr: ['It is true.']
qText: It is true.
speaker: Mr. Vyse

qTextArr: ['True on the whole,']
qText: True on the whole,
speaker: Lucy

qTextArr: ['True, every word. It is a revelation. It is--I.']
qText: True, every word. It is a revelation. It is--I.
speaker: Mr. Vyse

qTextArr: ['Anyhow, those are my reasons for not being your wife.']
qText: Anyhow, those are my reasons for not being your wife.
speaker: Lucy

qTextArr:
['It is true. I
fell to pieces the very first day we were engaged. I behaved like a cad
to Beebe and to your brother. You are even greater than I thought.', "I'm not going to worry you. You are far too good to
me. I shall never forget your insight; and, dear, I only blame you for
this: you might have warned me in the early stages, before you felt
you wouldn't marry me, and so have given me a chance to improve. I have
never known you till this evening. I have just used you as a peg for
my silly notions of what a woman should be. But this evening you are a
different person: new thoughts--even a new voice--"]
qText:
It is true. I
fell to pieces the very first day we were engaged. I behaved like a cad
to Beebe and to your brother. You are even greater than I thought. I'm not going to worry you. You are far too good to
me. I shall never forget your insight; and, dear, I only blame you for
this: you might have warned me in the early stages, before you felt
you wouldn't marry me, and so have given me a chance to improve. I have
never known you till this evening. I have just used you as a peg for
my silly notions of what a woman should be. But this evening you are a
different person: new thoughts--even a new voice--
speaker: Mr. Vyse

qTextArr: ['What do you mean by a new voice?']
qText: What do you mean by a new voice?
speaker: Lucy

qTextArr: ['I mean that a new person seems speaking through you,']
qText: I mean that a new person seems speaking through you,
speaker: Mr. Vyse

qTextArr: ['If you think I am in love with\nsomeone else, you are very much mistaken.']
qText:
If you think I am in love with
someone else, you are very much mistaken.
speaker: Lucy

qTextArr: ["Of course I don't think that. You are not that kind, Lucy."]
qText: Of course I don't think that. You are not that kind, Lucy.
speaker: Mr. Vyse

qTextArr: ["Oh, yes, you do think it. It's your old idea, the idea that has kept\nEurope back--I mean the idea that women are always thinking of men. If\na girl breaks off her engagement, everyone says:"]
qText:
Oh, yes, you do think it. It's your old idea, the idea that has kept
Europe back--I mean the idea that women are always thinking of men. If
a girl breaks off her engagement, everyone says:
speaker: Lucy

qTextArr: ["It's disgusting,\nbrutal! As if a girl can't break it off for the sake of freedom."]
qText:
It's disgusting,
brutal! As if a girl can't break it off for the sake of freedom.
speaker: Lucy

qTextArr: ['I may have said that in the past. I shall never\nsay it again. You have taught me better.']
qText:
I may have said that in the past. I shall never
say it again. You have taught me better.
speaker: Mr. Vyse

qTextArr:
["Of
course, there is no question of 'someone else' in this, no 'jilting' or
any such nauseous stupidity. I beg your pardon most humbly if my words
suggested that there was. I only meant that there was a force in you
that I hadn't known of up till now."]
qText:
Of
course, there is no question of 'someone else' in this, no 'jilting' or
any such nauseous stupidity. I beg your pardon most humbly if my words
suggested that there was. I only meant that there was a force in you
that I hadn't known of up till now.
speaker: Mr. Vyse

qTextArr: ["All right, Cecil, that will do. Don't apologize to me. It was my\nmistake."]
qText:
All right, Cecil, that will do. Don't apologize to me. It was my
mistake.
speaker: Lucy

qTextArr: ['It is a question between ideals, yours and mine--pure abstract ideals,\nand yours are the nobler. I was bound up in the old vicious notions,\nand all the time you were splendid and new.']
qText:
It is a question between ideals, yours and mine--pure abstract ideals,
and yours are the nobler. I was bound up in the old vicious notions,
and all the time you were splendid and new.
speaker: Mr. Vyse

qTextArr:
['I must
actually thank you for what you have done--for showing me what I really
am. Solemnly, I thank you for showing me a true woman. Will you shake
hands?']
qText:
I must
actually thank you for what you have done--for showing me what I really
am. Solemnly, I thank you for showing me a true woman. Will you shake
hands?
speaker: Mr. Vyse

qTextArr: ['Of course I will,', "Good-night, Cecil. Good-bye. That's all right. I'm sorry\nabout it. Thank you very much for your gentleness."]
qText:
Of course I will, Good-night, Cecil. Good-bye. That's all right. I'm sorry
about it. Thank you very much for your gentleness.
speaker: Lucy

qTextArr: ['Let me light your candle, shall I?']
qText: Let me light your candle, shall I?
speaker: Mr. Vyse

qTextArr: ['Thank you. Good-night again. God bless you, Lucy!']
qText: Thank you. Good-night again. God bless you, Lucy!
speaker: Mr. Vyse

qTextArr: ['Good-bye, Cecil.']
qText: Good-bye, Cecil.
speaker: Lucy

qTextArr: ["So you're off for a minute, Mr. Vyse?"]
qText: So you're off for a minute, Mr. Vyse?
speaker: Mr. Beebe

qText: Yes,
speaker: Mr. Vyse

qTextArr: ['I was coming to show you this delightful letter from those friends\nof Miss Honeychurch.']
qText:
I was coming to show you this delightful letter from those friends
of Miss Honeychurch.
speaker: Mr. Beebe

qTextArr: ["Isn't it wonderful? Isn't it\nromance? Most certainly they will go to Constantinople. They are taken\nin a snare that cannot fail. They will end by going round the world."]
qText:
Isn't it wonderful? Isn't it
romance? Most certainly they will go to Constantinople. They are taken
in a snare that cannot fail. They will end by going round the world.
speaker: Mr. Beebe
menEnts: [[['Miss Catharine', 'Miss Teresa'], ['Miss Catharine', 'Miss Teresa'], ['Miss Catharine', 'Miss Teresa']]]

qTextArr:
["Isn't Romance capricious! I never notice it in you young people; you
do nothing but play lawn tennis, and say that romance is dead, while the
Miss Alans are struggling with all the weapons of propriety against the
terrible thing."]
qText:
Isn't Romance capricious! I never notice it in you young people; you
do nothing but play lawn tennis, and say that romance is dead, while the
Miss Alans are struggling with all the weapons of propriety against the
terrible thing.
speaker: Mr. Beebe

qTextArr:
['So
they call it out of decency, but in their hearts they want a pension
with magic windows opening on the foam of perilous seas in fairyland
forlorn! No ordinary view will content the Miss Alans. They want the
Pension Keats.']
qText:
So
they call it out of decency, but in their hearts they want a pension
with magic windows opening on the foam of perilous seas in fairyland
forlorn! No ordinary view will content the Miss Alans. They want the
Pension Keats.
speaker: Mr. Beebe
menEnts: [[['Miss Catharine', 'Miss Teresa'], ['Miss Catharine', 'Miss Teresa'], ['Miss Catharine', 'Miss Teresa'], ['Miss Catharine', 'Miss Teresa']]]

qTextArr: ["I'm awfully sorry to interrupt, Mr. Beebe,", 'but have you\nany matches?']
qText:
I'm awfully sorry to interrupt, Mr. Beebe, but have you
any matches?
speaker: Freddy

qTextArr: ['I have,']
qText: I have,
speaker: Mr. Vyse

qTextArr: ['You have never met these Miss Alans, have you, Mr. Vyse?']
qText: You have never met these Miss Alans, have you, Mr. Vyse?
speaker: Mr. Beebe

qTextArr: ['Never.']
qText: Never.
speaker: Mr. Vyse

qTextArr:
["Then you don't see the wonder of this Greek visit. I haven't been
to Greece myself, and don't mean to go, and I can't imagine any of my
friends going. It is altogether too big for our little lot. Don't you
think so? Italy is just about as much as we can manage. Italy is heroic,
but Greece is godlike or devilish--I am not sure which, and in either
case absolutely out of our suburban focus. All right, Freddy--I am
not being clever, upon my word I am not--I took the idea from another
fellow; and give me those matches when you've done with them."]
qText:
Then you don't see the wonder of this Greek visit. I haven't been
to Greece myself, and don't mean to go, and I can't imagine any of my
friends going. It is altogether too big for our little lot. Don't you
think so? Italy is just about as much as we can manage. Italy is heroic,
but Greece is godlike or devilish--I am not sure which, and in either
case absolutely out of our suburban focus. All right, Freddy--I am
not being clever, upon my word I am not--I took the idea from another
fellow; and give me those matches when you've done with them.
speaker: Mr. Beebe

qTextArr:
['I was saying, if
our poor little Cockney lives must have a background, let it be Italian.
Big enough in all conscience. The ceiling of the Sistine Chapel for
me. There the contrast is just as much as I can realize. But not the
Parthenon, not the frieze of Phidias at any price; and here comes the
victoria.']
qText:
I was saying, if
our poor little Cockney lives must have a background, let it be Italian.
Big enough in all conscience. The ceiling of the Sistine Chapel for
me. There the contrast is just as much as I can realize. But not the
Parthenon, not the frieze of Phidias at any price; and here comes the
victoria.
speaker: Mr. Beebe

qTextArr: ["You're quite right,", 'Greece is not for our little lot']
qText: You're quite right, Greece is not for our little lot
speaker: Mr. Vyse

qTextArr:
["I'm so glad you
only talked about books. Cecil's hard hit. Lucy won't marry him. If
you'd gone on about her, as you did about them, he might have broken
down."]
qText:
I'm so glad you
only talked about books. Cecil's hard hit. Lucy won't marry him. If
you'd gone on about her, as you did about them, he might have broken
down.
speaker: Freddy
