qTextArr: ['But when--']
qText: But when--
speaker: Mr. Beebe

qTextArr: ['Late last night. I must go.']
qText: Late last night. I must go.
speaker: Freddy

qTextArr: ["Perhaps they won't want me down there."]
qText: Perhaps they won't want me down there.
speaker: Mr. Beebe

qTextArr: ['No--go on. Good-bye.']
qText: No--go on. Good-bye.
speaker: Freddy

qTextArr: ['Thank goodness!', 'It was the one foolish thing she ever\ndid. Oh, what a glorious riddance!']
qText:
Thank goodness! It was the one foolish thing she ever
did. Oh, what a glorious riddance!
speaker: Mr. Beebe

qTextArr:
['Oh, how do you do, Mr. Beebe? Gracious what a mess everything is! Look
at my scarlet pompoms, and the wind blowing your skirts about, and the
ground so hard that not a prop will stick in, and then the carriage
having to go out, when I had counted on having Powell, who--give every
one their due--does tie up dahlias properly.']
qText:
Oh, how do you do, Mr. Beebe? Gracious what a mess everything is! Look
at my scarlet pompoms, and the wind blowing your skirts about, and the
ground so hard that not a prop will stick in, and then the carriage
having to go out, when I had counted on having Powell, who--give every
one their due--does tie up dahlias properly.
speaker: Mrs. Honeychurch

qTextArr: ['How do you do?']
qText: How do you do?
speaker: Miss Bartlett

qTextArr: ['Here, Lennie, the bass,']
qText: Here, Lennie, the bass,
speaker: Mrs. Honeychurch

qTextArr: ['Come for a walk with me,', 'You have worried them as much\nas they can stand. Mrs. Honeychurch, I only called in aimlessly. I shall\ntake her up to tea at the Beehive Tavern, if I may.']
qText:
Come for a walk with me, You have worried them as much
as they can stand. Mrs. Honeychurch, I only called in aimlessly. I shall
take her up to tea at the Beehive Tavern, if I may.
speaker: Mr. Beebe

qTextArr: ["Oh, must you? Yes do.--Not the scissors, thank you, Charlotte, when\nboth my hands are full already--I'm perfectly certain that the orange\ncactus will go before I can get to it."]
qText:
Oh, must you? Yes do.--Not the scissors, thank you, Charlotte, when
both my hands are full already--I'm perfectly certain that the orange
cactus will go before I can get to it.
speaker: Mrs. Honeychurch

qTextArr: ["Yes, Charlotte, I don't want you--do go; there's nothing to stop about\nfor, either in the house or out of it."]
qText:
Yes, Charlotte, I don't want you--do go; there's nothing to stop about
for, either in the house or out of it.
speaker: Mrs. Honeychurch

qTextArr: ['It is terrible, this havoc among the flowers,']
qText: It is terrible, this havoc among the flowers,
speaker: Mr. Beebe

qTextArr: ['It is always terrible when the promise of months is destroyed in a\nmoment,']
qText:
It is always terrible when the promise of months is destroyed in a
moment,
speaker: Miss Bartlett

qTextArr: ['Perhaps we ought to send Miss Honeychurch down to her mother. Or will\nshe come with us?']
qText:
Perhaps we ought to send Miss Honeychurch down to her mother. Or will
she come with us?
speaker: Mr. Beebe

qTextArr: ['I think we had better leave Lucy to herself, and to her own pursuits.']
qText: I think we had better leave Lucy to herself, and to her own pursuits.
speaker: Miss Bartlett

qTextArr:
["They're angry with Miss Honeychurch because she was late for
breakfast,", "and Floyd has gone, and Mr. Vyse has
gone, and Freddy won't play with me. In fact, Uncle Arthur, the house is
not AT ALL what it was yesterday."]
qText:
They're angry with Miss Honeychurch because she was late for
breakfast, and Floyd has gone, and Mr. Vyse has
gone, and Freddy won't play with me. In fact, Uncle Arthur, the house is
not AT ALL what it was yesterday.
speaker: Minnie Beebe

qTextArr: ["Don't be a prig,", 'Go and put on your boots.']
qText: Don't be a prig, Go and put on your boots.
speaker: Mr. Beebe

qTextArr: ['How do you do? Miss Bartlett and Minnie are coming with me to tea at\nthe Beehive. Would you come too?']
qText:
How do you do? Miss Bartlett and Minnie are coming with me to tea at
the Beehive. Would you come too?
speaker: Mr. Beebe

qTextArr: ["I don't think I will, thank you."]
qText: I don't think I will, thank you.
speaker: Lucy

qTextArr: ["No, I didn't suppose you would care to much."]
qText: No, I didn't suppose you would care to much.
speaker: Mr. Beebe

qTextArr: ['How delicate those Sonatas are!']
qText: How delicate those Sonatas are!
speaker: Mr. Beebe

qTextArr: ['Miss Honeychurch!']
qText: Miss Honeychurch!
speaker: Mr. Beebe

qText: Yes.
speaker: Lucy

qTextArr: ['I met them on the hill. Your brother told me.']
qText: I met them on the hill. Your brother told me.
speaker: Mr. Beebe

qTextArr: ['Oh he did?']
qText: Oh he did?
speaker: Lucy

qTextArr: ["I needn't say that it will go no further."]
qText: I needn't say that it will go no further.
speaker: Mr. Beebe

qTextArr: ['Mother, Charlotte, Cecil, Freddy, you,']
qText: Mother, Charlotte, Cecil, Freddy, you,
speaker: Lucy

qTextArr: ["If you'll let me say so, I am very glad, and I am certain that you have\ndone the right thing."]
qText:
If you'll let me say so, I am very glad, and I am certain that you have
done the right thing.
speaker: Mr. Beebe

qTextArr: ["So I hoped other people would think, but they don't seem to."]
qText: So I hoped other people would think, but they don't seem to.
speaker: Lucy

qTextArr: ['I could see that Miss Bartlett thought it unwise.']
qText: I could see that Miss Bartlett thought it unwise.
speaker: Mr. Beebe

qTextArr: ['So does mother. Mother minds dreadfully.']
qText: So does mother. Mother minds dreadfully.
speaker: Lucy

qTextArr: ['I am very sorry for that,']
qText: I am very sorry for that,
speaker: Mr. Beebe

qTextArr: ['And Freddy minds.']
qText: And Freddy minds.
speaker: Lucy

qTextArr: ['Still, Freddy never hit it off with Vyse much, did he? I gathered that\nhe disliked the engagement, and felt it might separate him from you.']
qText:
Still, Freddy never hit it off with Vyse much, did he? I gathered that
he disliked the engagement, and felt it might separate him from you.
speaker: Mr. Beebe

qTextArr: ['Boys are so odd.']
qText: Boys are so odd.
speaker: Lucy

qTextArr: ['I have had an\nabsurd letter from Miss Alan. That was really what brought me over. I\nthought it might amuse you all.']
qText:
I have had an
absurd letter from Miss Alan. That was really what brought me over. I
thought it might amuse you all.
speaker: Mr. Beebe

qTextArr: ['How delightful!']
qText: How delightful!
speaker: Lucy

qTextArr: ['Going abroad? When do they start?']
qText: Going abroad? When do they start?
speaker: Lucy

qTextArr: ['Next week, I gather.']
qText: Next week, I gather.
speaker: Mr. Beebe

qTextArr: ['Did Freddy say whether he was driving straight back?']
qText: Did Freddy say whether he was driving straight back?
speaker: Lucy

qTextArr: ["No, he didn't."]
qText: No, he didn't.
speaker: Mr. Beebe

qTextArr: ["Because I do hope he won't go gossiping."]
qText: Because I do hope he won't go gossiping.
speaker: Lucy

qTextArr: ['Oh,\ndo tell me more about the Miss Alans! How perfectly splendid of them to\ngo abroad!']
qText:
Oh,
do tell me more about the Miss Alans! How perfectly splendid of them to
go abroad!
speaker: Lucy

qTextArr: ['I want them to start from Venice, and go in a cargo steamer down the\nIllyrian coast!']
qText:
I want them to start from Venice, and go in a cargo steamer down the
Illyrian coast!
speaker: Mr. Beebe

qTextArr: ["Oh, delightful! I wish they'd take me."]
qText: Oh, delightful! I wish they'd take me.
speaker: Lucy

qTextArr: ['Has Italy filled you with the fever of travel? Perhaps George Emerson\nis right. He says that']
qText:
Has Italy filled you with the fever of travel? Perhaps George Emerson
is right. He says that
speaker: Mr. Beebe

qTextArr: ["Oh, not Italy, but Constantinople. I have always longed to go to\nConstantinople. Constantinople is practically Asia, isn't it?"]
qText:
Oh, not Italy, but Constantinople. I have always longed to go to
Constantinople. Constantinople is practically Asia, isn't it?
speaker: Lucy

qTextArr: ['with Delphi, perhaps, if the roads\nare safe.']
qText:
with Delphi, perhaps, if the roads
are safe.
speaker: Mr. Beebe

qTextArr: ["I didn't realize that you and the Miss Alans were still such friends,\nafter Cissie Villa."]
qText:
I didn't realize that you and the Miss Alans were still such friends,
after Cissie Villa.
speaker: Mr. Beebe

qTextArr: ["Oh, that's nothing; I assure you Cissie Villa's nothing to me; I would\ngive anything to go with them."]
qText:
Oh, that's nothing; I assure you Cissie Villa's nothing to me; I would
give anything to go with them.
speaker: Lucy

qTextArr: ['Would your mother spare you again so soon? You have scarcely been home\nthree months.']
qText:
Would your mother spare you again so soon? You have scarcely been home
three months.
speaker: Mr. Beebe

qTextArr: ['She MUST spare me!', 'I simply MUST\ngo away. I have to.', "Don't you see that I HAVE to go away? I didn't realize at the time--and\nof course I want to see Constantinople so particularly."]
qText:
She MUST spare me! I simply MUST
go away. I have to. Don't you see that I HAVE to go away? I didn't realize at the time--and
of course I want to see Constantinople so particularly.
speaker: Lucy

qTextArr: ['You mean that since you have broken off your engagement you feel--']
qText: You mean that since you have broken off your engagement you feel--
speaker: Mr. Beebe

qTextArr: ["Yes, yes. I knew you'd understand."]
qText: Yes, yes. I knew you'd understand.
speaker: Lucy

qTextArr: ['Yes, of course; to go to Constantinople until they are used to the idea\nand everything has calmed down.']
qText:
Yes, of course; to go to Constantinople until they are used to the idea

speaker: Lucy

qTextArr: ['I am afraid it has been a bothersome business,']
qText: I am afraid it has been a bothersome business,
speaker: Mr. Beebe

qTextArr:
["No, not at all. Cecil was very kind indeed; only--I had better tell
you the whole truth, since you have heard a little--it was that he is
so masterful. I found that he wouldn't let me go my own way. He would
improve me in places where I can't be improved. Cecil won't let a woman
decide for herself--in fact, he daren't. What nonsense I do talk! But
that is the kind of thing."]
qText:
No, not at all. Cecil was very kind indeed; only--I had better tell
you the whole truth, since you have heard a little--it was that he is
so masterful. I found that he wouldn't let me go my own way. He would
improve me in places where I can't be improved. Cecil won't let a woman

speaker: Lucy

['It is what I gathered from my own observation of Mr. Vyse; it is what I

gather from all that I have known of you. I do sympathize and agree

qTextArr: ['But I must go somewhere!', 'I have been worrying all the\nmorning, and here comes the very thing.']
qText:
But I must go somewhere! I have been worrying all the
morning, and here comes the very thing.
speaker: Lucy

qTextArr: ["I must! And the time I shall have with\nmother, and all the money she spent on me last spring. You all think\nmuch too highly of me. I wish you weren't so kind."]
qText:
I must! And the time I shall have with
mother, and all the money she spent on me last spring. You all think

One is very thankful that she has such a resource. She is evidently
much worried, as, of course, she ought to be. I know all about it. The

qTextArr: ['she might yet reveal depths of strangeness, if not of\nmeaning.']
qText:
she might yet reveal depths of strangeness, if not of

refExp: he had put it to himself

qTextArr: ['We had much better let the matter\ndrop.']
qText:
We had much better let the matter
drop.
speaker: Miss Bartlett

qTextArr: ['I wonder.']
qText: I wonder.
speaker: Mr. Beebe

qTextArr: ["It is of the highest importance that there should be no gossip in\nSummer Street. It would be DEATH to gossip about Mr. Vyse's dismissal at\nthe present moment."]
qText:
It is of the highest importance that there should be no gossip in

speaker: Miss Bartlett

qTextArr: ['Of course, Miss\nHoneychurch will make the fact public in her own way, and when she\nchooses. Freddy only told me because he knew she would not mind.']
qText:
Of course, Miss
Honeychurch will make the fact public in her own way, and when she
chooses. Freddy only told me because he knew she would not mind.

I know, Yet Freddy ought not to have told
even you. One cannot be too careful.
speaker: Miss Bartlett

qTextArr: ['Quite so.']
qText: Quite so.
speaker: Mr. Beebe

qTextArr: ['I do implore absolute secrecy. A chance word to a chattering friend,\nand--']
qText:
I do implore absolute secrecy. A chance word to a chattering friend,
and--
speaker: Miss Bartlett

qTextArr: ['Exactly.']
qText: Exactly.
speaker: Mr. Beebe

qTextArr:
["Have you heard from any Bertolini people lately? I believe
you keep up with Miss Lavish. It is odd how we of that pension,
who seemed such a fortuitous collection, have been working into one
another's lives. Two, three, four, six of us--no, eight; I had forgotten
the Emersons--have kept more or less in touch. We must really give the
Signora a testimonial."]
qText:
Have you heard from any Bertolini people lately? I believe
you keep up with Miss Lavish. It is odd how we of that pension,
who seemed such a fortuitous collection, have been working into one
another's lives. Two, three, four, six of us--no, eight; I had forgotten
the Emersons--have kept more or less in touch. We must really give the
Signora a testimonial.
speaker: Mr. Beebe

qTextArr:
["We shan't have
rain, but we shall have darkness, so let us hurry on. The darkness last
night was appalling.", 'I have been thinking, Miss Bartlett,', 'and, unless you
very much object, I would like to reopen that discussion.', "Nothing about the past. I know little and care less about that; I am
absolutely certain that it is to your cousin's credit. She has acted

qText:
We shan't have
rain, but we shall have darkness, so let us hurry on. The darkness last
night was appalling. I have been thinking, Miss Bartlett, and, unless you
very much object, I would like to reopen that discussion. Nothing about the past. I know little and care less about that; I am
absolutely certain that it is to your cousin's credit. She has acted
loftily and rightly, and it is like her gentle modesty to say that we
think too highly of her. But the future. Seriously, what do you think of
this Greek plan? I don't know whether
you overheard, but she wants to join the Miss Alans in their mad career.
It's all--I can't explain--it's wrong.
speaker: Mr. Beebe
menEnts: [[['Minnie Beebe', 'Miss Bartlett', 'Mr. Beebe'], ['Minnie Beebe', 'Miss Bartlett', 'Mr. Beebe'], ['Minnie Beebe', 'Miss Bartlett', 'Mr. Beebe']], [['Miss Bartlett']], [['Miss Bartlett']], [['Lucy'], ['Lucy'], ['Lucy'], ['Miss Bartlett', 'Mr. Beebe'], ['Lucy']], [['Miss Bartlett'], ['Lucy'], ['Miss Catharine', 'Miss Teresa'], ['Miss Catharine', 'Miss Teresa']]]

qTextArr: ["I can't see the point of it myself."]
qText: I can't see the point of it myself.
speaker: Mr. Beebe

qTextArr: ["There I cannot agree with you. In it\nI spy Lucy's salvation."]
qText:
There I cannot agree with you. In it
I spy Lucy's salvation.
speaker: Miss Bartlett

qTextArr: ['Really. Now, why?']
qText: Really. Now, why?
speaker: Mr. Beebe

qTextArr: ['She wanted to leave Windy Corner.']
qText: She wanted to leave Windy Corner.
speaker: Miss Bartlett

qTextArr: ['I know--but it seems so odd, so unlike her, so--I was going to\nsay--selfish.']
qText:
I know--but it seems so odd, so unlike her, so--I was going to
say--selfish.
speaker: Mr. Beebe

qTextArr: ['It is natural, surely--after such painful scenes--that she should\ndesire a change.']
qText:
It is natural, surely--after such painful scenes--that she should
desire a change.
speaker: Miss Bartlett

qTextArr:
["So she says herself, and since another
lady agrees with her, I must own that I am partially convinced. Perhaps
she must have a change. I have no sisters or--and I don't understand
these things. But why need she go as far as Greece?"]
qText:
So she says herself, and since another
lady agrees with her, I must own that I am partially convinced. Perhaps
she must have a change. I have no sisters or--and I don't understand
these things. But why need she go as far as Greece?
speaker: Mr. Beebe

qTextArr:
['You may well ask that,', 'Why Greece?
(What is it, Minnie dear--jam?) Why not Tunbridge Wells? Oh, Mr. Beebe!
I had a long and most unsatisfactory interview with dear Lucy this
morning. I cannot help her. I will say no more. Perhaps I have already
said too much. I am not to talk. I wanted her to spend six months with
me at Tunbridge Wells, and she refused.']
qText:
You may well ask that, Why Greece?
(What is it, Minnie dear--jam?) Why not Tunbridge Wells? Oh, Mr. Beebe!
I had a long and most unsatisfactory interview with dear Lucy this
morning. I cannot help her. I will say no more. Perhaps I have already
said too much. I am not to talk. I wanted her to spend six months with
me at Tunbridge Wells, and she refused.
speaker: Miss Bartlett

qTextArr:
["But my feelings are of no importance. I know too well that I get on
Lucy's nerves. Our tour was a failure. She wanted to leave Florence, and
when we got to Rome she did not want to be in Rome, and all the time I
felt that I was spending her mother's money--."]
qText:
But my feelings are of no importance. I know too well that I get on
Lucy's nerves. Our tour was a failure. She wanted to leave Florence, and
when we got to Rome she did not want to be in Rome, and all the time I
felt that I was spending her mother's money--.
speaker: Miss Bartlett

qTextArr: ['Let us keep to the future, though,', 'I want your\nadvice.']
qText:
Let us keep to the future, though, I want your
advice.
speaker: Mr. Beebe

qTextArr: ['Very well,', 'I for one will help her to go to Greece.\nWill you?']
qText:
Very well, I for one will help her to go to Greece.
Will you?
speaker: Miss Bartlett

qTextArr:
['It is absolutely necessary,', 'I know--I know.', 'She must not stop here a moment, and we must
keep quiet till she goes. I trust that the servants know nothing.
Afterwards--but I may have said too much already. Only, Lucy and I are
helpless against Mrs. Honeychurch alone. If you help we may succeed.
Otherwise--']
qText:
It is absolutely necessary, I know--I know. She must not stop here a moment, and we must
keep quiet till she goes. I trust that the servants know nothing.
Afterwards--but I may have said too much already. Only, Lucy and I are
helpless against Mrs. Honeychurch alone. If you help we may succeed.
Otherwise--
speaker: Miss Bartlett

qTextArr:
["I should be told, dear, that I am
unsympathetic. But I cannot see why you didn't tell your friends about
Cecil and be done with it. There all the time we had to sit fencing, and
almost telling lies, and be seen through, too, I dare say, which is most
unpleasant."]
qText:
I should be told, dear, that I am
unsympathetic. But I cannot see why you didn't tell your friends about
Cecil and be done with it. There all the time we had to sit fencing, and
almost telling lies, and be seen through, too, I dare say, which is most
unpleasant.
speaker: Mrs. Honeychurch

qTextArr: ["But why shouldn't it be everywhere in no time?"]
qText: But why shouldn't it be everywhere in no time?
speaker: Mrs. Honeychurch

qTextArr: ["Because I settled with Cecil not to announce it until I left England. I\nshall tell them then. It's much pleasanter. How wet it is! Let's turn in\nhere."]
qText:
Because I settled with Cecil not to announce it until I left England. I
shall tell them then. It's much pleasanter. How wet it is! Let's turn in
here.
speaker: Lucy

qTextArr: ["Oh, well, let it be shop, then. Let's go to Mudie's. I'll buy a\nguide-book."]
qText:
Oh, well, let it be shop, then. Let's go to Mudie's. I'll buy a
guide-book.
speaker: Lucy

qTextArr:
["You know, Lucy, you and Charlotte and Mr. Beebe all tell me I'm
so stupid, so I suppose I am, but I shall never understand this
hole-and-corner work. You've got rid of Cecil--well and good, and I'm
thankful he's gone, though I did feel angry for the minute. But why not
announce it? Why this hushing up and tip-toeing?"]
qText:
You know, Lucy, you and Charlotte and Mr. Beebe all tell me I'm
so stupid, so I suppose I am, but I shall never understand this
hole-and-corner work. You've got rid of Cecil--well and good, and I'm
thankful he's gone, though I did feel angry for the minute. But why not
announce it? Why this hushing up and tip-toeing?
speaker: Mrs. Honeychurch

qTextArr: ["It's only for a few days."]
qText: It's only for a few days.
speaker: Lucy

qTextArr: ['But why at all?']
qText: But why at all?
speaker: Mrs. Honeychurch

qTextArr: ["Because George Emerson has been bothering me, and if he\nhears I've given up Cecil may begin again"]
qText:
Because George Emerson has been bothering me, and if he
hears I've given up Cecil may begin again
speaker: Lucy

qTextArr:
["My daughter won't
answer me; she would rather be with those inquisitive old maids than
with Freddy and me. Any rag, tag, and bobtail apparently does if she
can leave her home."]
qText:
My daughter won't
answer me; she would rather be with those inquisitive old maids than
with Freddy and me. Any rag, tag, and bobtail apparently does if she
can leave her home.

qTextArr: ["You're tired of Windy Corner."]
qText: You're tired of Windy Corner.
speaker: Mrs. Honeychurch

qTextArr:
['I do not love George; I broke off my engagement
because I did not love George; I must go to Greece because I do not
love George; it is more important that I should look up gods in the
dictionary than that I should help my mother; everyone else is behaving
very badly.']
qText:
I do not love George; I broke off my engagement
because I did not love George; I must go to Greece because I do not
love George; it is more important that I should look up gods in the
dictionary than that I should help my mother; everyone else is behaving
very badly.
speaker: Lucy

qTextArr: ["Oh, mother, what rubbish you talk! Of course I'm not tired of Windy\nCorner."]
qText:
Oh, mother, what rubbish you talk! Of course I'm not tired of Windy
Corner.
speaker: Lucy

qTextArr: ['Then why not say so at once, instead of considering half an hour?']
qText: Then why not say so at once, instead of considering half an hour?
speaker: Mrs. Honeychurch

qTextArr: ['Half a minute would be nearer.']
qText: Half a minute would be nearer.
speaker: Lucy

qTextArr: ['Perhaps you would like to stay away from your home altogether?']
qText: Perhaps you would like to stay away from your home altogether?
speaker: Mrs. Honeychurch

qTextArr:
['Hush, mother! People will hear you', 'Of course I want to live at home;
but as we are talking about it, I may as well say that I shall want to
be away in the future more than I have been. You see, I come into my
money next year.']
qText:
Hush, mother! People will hear you Of course I want to live at home;
but as we are talking about it, I may as well say that I shall want to
be away in the future more than I have been. You see, I come into my

qTextArr:
["I've seen the
world so little--I felt so out of things in Italy. I have seen so little
of life; one ought to come up to London more--not a cheap ticket like
to-day, but to stop. I might even share a flat for a little with some
other girl."]
qText:
I've seen the
world so little--I felt so out of things in Italy. I have seen so little
of life; one ought to come up to London more--not a cheap ticket like
to-day, but to stop. I might even share a flat for a little with some
other girl.
speaker: Lucy

qTextArr:
['And mess with typewriters and latch-keys,', "And agitate and scream, and be carried off kicking by the police. And
call it a Mission--when no one wants you! And call it Duty--when
it means that you can't stand your own home! And call it Work--when
thousands of men are starving with the competition as it is! And then
to prepare yourself, find two doddering old ladies, and go abroad with
them."]
qText:
And mess with typewriters and latch-keys, And agitate and scream, and be carried off kicking by the police. And
call it a Mission--when no one wants you! And call it Duty--when
it means that you can't stand your own home! And call it Work--when
thousands of men are starving with the competition as it is! And then
to prepare yourself, find two doddering old ladies, and go abroad with
them.
speaker: Mrs. Honeychurch

qTextArr: ['I want more independence,']
qText: I want more independence,
speaker: Lucy

qTextArr:
['Very well. Take your independence and be gone. Rush up and down and
round the world, and come back as thin as a lath with the bad food.
Despise the house that your father built and the garden that he planted,
and our dear view--and then share a flat with another girl.']
qText:
Very well. Take your independence and be gone. Rush up and down and
round the world, and come back as thin as a lath with the bad food.
Despise the house that your father built and the garden that he planted,
and our dear view--and then share a flat with another girl.
speaker: Mrs. Honeychurch

qTextArr:
['True, everlastingly true, though my day
is over, and though there is the result. Poor boy! He is so sorry!
He said he knew it was madness when you brought your cousin in; that

qText:
True, everlastingly true, though my day
is over, and though there is the result. Poor boy! He is so sorry!
He said he knew it was madness when you brought your cousin in; that

dropped water on him in church! Is it possible, Miss Honeychurch? Shall
we slip back into the darkness for ever?']

refExp: He heard her in silence and then said

qTextArr:
["Take an old man's word; there's nothing worse than a muddle in all the
world. It is easy to face Death and Fate, and the things that sound
so dreadful. It is on my muddles that I look back with horror--on the
things that I might have avoided. We can help one another but little. I
used to think I could teach young people the whole of life, but I know
better now, and all my teaching of George has come down to this: beware
of muddle. Do you remember in that church, when you pretended to be
annoyed with me and weren't? Do you remember before, when you refused
the room with the view? Those were muddles--little, but ominous--and I
am fearing that you are in one now."]
qText:
Take an old man's word; there's nothing worse than a muddle in all the
world. It is easy to face Death and Fate, and the things that sound
so dreadful. It is on my muddles that I look back with horror--on the
things that I might have avoided. We can help one another but little. I
used to think I could teach young people the whole of life, but I know
better now, and all my teaching of George has come down to this: beware
of muddle. Do you remember in that church, when you pretended to be
annoyed with me and weren't? Do you remember before, when you refused
the room with the view? Those were muddles--little, but ominous--and I
am fearing that you are in one now.
speaker: Mr. Emerson

qTextArr: ["Don't trust me,\nMiss Honeychurch. Though life is very glorious, it is difficult."]

qTextArr:
["You're shocked, but I mean to shock you. It's the only hope at times. I
can reach you no other way. You must marry, or your life will be wasted.
You have gone too far to retreat. I have no time for the tenderness, and
the comradeship, and the poetry, and the things that really matter, and
for which you marry. I know that, with George, you will find them, and
that you love him. Then be his wife. He is already part of you. Though
you fly to Greece, and never see him again, or forget his very name,
George will work in your thoughts till you die. It isn't possible to
love and to part. You will wish that it was. You can transmute love,
ignore it, muddle it, but you can never pull it out of you. I know by
experience that the poets are right: love is eternal."]
qText:
You're shocked, but I mean to shock you. It's the only hope at times. I
can reach you no other way. You must marry, or your life will be wasted.
You have gone too far to retreat. I have no time for the tenderness, and
the comradeship, and the poetry, and the things that really matter, and
for which you marry. I know that, with George, you will find them, and
that you love him. Then be his wife. He is already part of you. Though
you fly to Greece, and never see him again, or forget his very name,
George will work in your thoughts till you die. It isn't possible to
love and to part. You will wish that it was. You can transmute love,
ignore it, muddle it, but you can never pull it out of you. I know by
experience that the poets are right: love is eternal.
speaker: Mr. Emerson

qTextArr:
['I only wish poets would say this, too: love is of the body; not
the body, but of the body. Ah! the misery that would be saved if we
confessed that! Ah! for a little directness to liberate the soul! Your
soul, dear Lucy! I hate the word now, because of all the cant with which
superstition has wrapped it round. But we have souls. I cannot say how
they came nor whither they go, but we have them, and I see you ruining
yours. I cannot bear it. It is again the darkness creeping in; it
is hell.']
qText:
I only wish poets would say this, too: love is of the body; not
the body, but of the body. Ah! the misery that would be saved if we
confessed that! Ah! for a little directness to liberate the soul! Your
soul, dear Lucy! I hate the word now, because of all the cant with which
superstition has wrapped it round. But we have souls. I cannot say how
they came nor whither they go, but we have them, and I see you ruining
yours. I cannot bear it. It is again the darkness creeping in; it
is hell.
speaker: Mr. Emerson

qTextArr:
['What nonsense I have talked--how
abstract and remote! And I have made you cry! Dear girl, forgive my
prosiness; marry my boy. When I think what life is, and how seldom love
is answered by love--Marry him; it is one of the moments for which the
world was made.']
qText:
What nonsense I have talked--how
abstract and remote! And I have made you cry! Dear girl, forgive my
prosiness; marry my boy. When I think what life is, and how seldom love
is answered by love--Marry him; it is one of the moments for which the
world was made.
speaker: Mr. Emerson

qTextArr:
['Now it is all dark. Now Beauty and Passion seem never to have existed.

if I were George, and gave you one kiss, it would make you brave. You
have to go cold into a battle that needs warmth, out into the muddle
that you have made yourself; and your mother and all your friends
will despise you, oh, my darling, and rightly, if it is ever right to
despise. George still dark, all the tussle and the misery without a word
from him. Am I justified?']
qText:

qTextArr:
["Silly boy! He thinks he's being dignified. He knew we should go off in
the spring--he has known it for six months--that if mother wouldn't give
her consent we should take the thing into our own hands. They had fair
warning, and now he calls it an elopement. Ridiculous boy--"]
qText:
Silly boy! He thinks he's being dignified. He knew we should go off in
the spring--he has known it for six months--that if mother wouldn't give
her consent we should take the thing into our own hands. They had fair
warning, and now he calls it an elopement. Ridiculous boy--
speaker: Lucy

qText: Signorino, domani faremo uno giro--

qTextArr:
["But it will all come right in the end. He has to build us both up
from the beginning again. I wish, though, that Cecil had not turned so
cynical about women. He has, for the second time, quite altered. Why
will men have theories about women? I haven't any about men. I wish,
too, that Mr. Beebe--"]
qText:
But it will all come right in the end. He has to build us both up
from the beginning again. I wish, though, that Cecil had not turned so
cynical about women. He has, for the second time, quite altered. Why
will men have theories about women? I haven't any about men. I wish,
too, that Mr. Beebe--
speaker: Lucy

qTextArr:
["He will never forgive us--I mean, he will never be interested in us
again. I wish that he did not influence them so much at Windy Corner. I
wish he hadn't--But if we act the truth, the people who really love us
are sure to come back to us in the long run."]
qText:
He will never forgive us--I mean, he will never be interested in us
again. I wish that he did not influence them so much at Windy Corner. I
wish he hadn't--But if we act the truth, the people who really love us
are sure to come back to us in the long run.
speaker: Lucy

qText:

qText:

you remember, and then went straight to the church. She said so.
speaker: Lucy

qTextArr:
['My father,', "saw her, and I prefer
his word. He was dozing by the study fire, and he opened his eyes,
and there was Miss Bartlett. A few minutes before you came in. She was
turning to go as he woke up. He didn't speak to her."]
qText:
My father, saw her, and I prefer
his word. He was dozing by the study fire, and he opened his eyes,
and there was Miss Bartlett. A few minutes before you came in. She was
turning to go as he woke up. He didn't speak to her.
speaker: George Emerson

qTextArr: ['Mean what, George?']
qText: Mean what, George?
speaker: Lucy

qTextArr:
["Is it this? Is this possible? I'll put a marvel to you.
That your cousin has always hoped. That from the very first moment we
met, she hoped, far down in her mind, that we should be like this--of
course, very far down. That she fought us on the surface, and yet she
hoped. I can't explain her any other way. Can you? Look how she kept me
alive in you all the summer; how she gave you no peace; how month after
month she became more eccentric and unreliable. The sight of us haunted
her--or she couldn't have described us as she did to her friend. There
are details--it burnt. I read the book afterwards. She is not frozen,
Lucy, she is not withered up all through. She tore us apart twice, but
in the rectory that evening she was given one more chance to make us
happy. We can never make friends with her or thank her. But I do believe
that, far down in her heart, far below all speech and behaviour, she is
glad."]
qText:
Is it this? Is this possible? I'll put a marvel to you.
That your cousin has always hoped. That from the very first moment we
met, she hoped, far down in her mind, that we should be like this--of
course, very far down. That she fought us on the surface, and yet she
hoped. I can't explain her any other way. Can you? Look how she kept me
alive in you all the summer; how she gave you no peace; how month after
month she became more eccentric and unreliable. The sight of us haunted
her--or she couldn't have described us as she did to her friend. There
are details--it burnt. I read the book afterwards. She is not frozen,
Lucy, she is not withered up all through. She tore us apart twice, but
in the rectory that evening she was given one more chance to make us
happy. We can never make friends with her or thank her. But I do believe
that, far down in her heart, far below all speech and behaviour, she is
glad.
speaker: George Emerson
